## Front Matter & Preface

### Book Structure & Approach
- **Non-chronological presentation** — key to understanding the Federal Reserve is "in the middle," not at the beginning
- Organized as a **mystery to be solved**, not a curriculum to master
- Four books in one: crash course on money, central banks as war catalysts, history of US central banking, analysis of Fed's record since 1913

### Seven Reasons for Abolition (Griffin's Core Argument)
1. Incapable of accomplishing stated objectives
2. A cartel operating against the public interest
3. Supreme instrument of usury
4. Generates the most unfair tax
5. Encourages war
6. Destabilizes the economy
7. Instrument of totalitarianism

### Author's Motivation
- **Struggled with credibility problem** — the story is "truly incredible, which means unbelievable"
- Public doesn't want bad news; monetary experts can't agree on basics
- Evidence now "so overpowering" that sanity questions aside, truth demands acceptance
- Book grew from planned one-year project to four books worth of material

> "The bad news is that every detail of what follows is true." — G. Edward Griffin

### Publication History
- Third edition: May 1998
- First edition: July 1994
- Seven printings by 1998

## Introduction: A Mental Exercise (Punch Magazine, 1957)

### Banking Paradox — Q&A Format

**What banks are for?**
- To make money — for the banks, not customers

**On Reserves & Assets:**
- Banks advertise reserves of $249M "or thereabouts" — money they've made from customers
- Assets of $500M — money they use to make money (lent to customers)
- **Key paradox**: Assets are what they've lent out; Liabilities are deposits owed back
- Assets and Liabilities "cancel out" — banks theoretically have no money at all

**The Profit Question:**
- Banks charge interest on loans at "Bank Rate" (e.g., 5.5%)
- Depositors receive minimal interest (e.g., 0.5%)
- **Customer's objection**: "Why isn't it my profit? Isn't it my money?"

**The Banking Theory:**
- Banks assume customers won't all withdraw at once
- System depends on **not meeting commitments simultaneously**
- If everyone wanted money at once, banks would collapse

**Final punch line:**
> Q. Wouldn't I do better to go off and open up a bank?

## Section I: What Creature Is This?

### The Central Mystery
- **Surprising answer**: Federal Reserve is not federal, there are no reserves, Federal Reserve Banks aren't even banks
- Answer found "in the middle" of the story, not beginning
- Presented as mystery, not chronological curriculum

## Chapter 1: The Journey to Jekyll Island

### The Secret Meeting — November 1910

**Setting:**
- New Jersey railway station, approaching 10 PM, first snow of winter
- Year 1910: rail cars with hard chairs, metal surfaces, dark green and gray colors
- Private luxury car "ALDRICH" at end of platform — gleaming black paint, polished brass, mahogany paneling, velvet drapes, plush armchairs, stocked bar

**Nelson Aldrich — The Commander:**
- **Senator from Rhode Island**, Republican "whip" in Senate
- Chairman of **National Monetary Commission**
- Investment associate of **J.P. Morgan**
- Son-in-law: **John D. Rockefeller, Jr.**
- Grandson (60 years later): **Nelson Aldrich Rockefeller**, Vice-President
- Private railway car frequently seen at NY/NJ terminals during Wall Street trips
- Political spokesman for big business
- Wore fur-collared coat, silk top hat, silver-tipped walking stick

**Security Measures:**
- Passengers instructed to arrive separately
- Avoid reporters
- Pretend not to know each other inside station
- Use first names only to avoid revealing identities
- Even private-car porters and servants didn't know guests' names
- Last passenger arrived carrying a shotgun case

### The Seven Passengers (One-Fourth of World's Wealth)

1. **Nelson W. Aldrich** — Senate leader, National Monetary Commission chair, J.P. Morgan associate, Rockefeller father-in-law

2. **Abraham Piatt Andrew** — Assistant Secretary of US Treasury

3. **Frank A. Vanderlip** — President of National City Bank of New York (most powerful bank then), representing **William Rockefeller** and **Kuhn, Loeb & Company**

4. **Henry P. Davison** — Senior partner, J.P. Morgan Company

5. **Charles D. Norton** — President, J.P. Morgan's First National Bank of New York

6. **Benjamin Strong** — Head of J.P. Morgan's Bankers Trust Company

7. **Paul M. Warburg** — Partner in Kuhn, Loeb & Company, representative of **Rothschild banking dynasty** (England & France), brother to **Max Warburg** (head of Warburg consortium in Germany & Netherlands)

**Note on attendance dispute**: Author Andrew L. Gray (grand-nephew of A.P. Andrew) claims Strong wasn't there; Vanderlip's memoirs say he was. Vanderlip possibly wrote account "in his late seventies" with wishful thinking. Regardless, "Strong would have been among those few to be let in on the secret."

### Concentration of Wealth

**By 1910:**
- Two main focal points in US: **Morgan group** and **Rockefeller group**
- Each orbit contained maze of commercial banks, acceptance banks, investment firms
- Europe: further consolidated into **Rothschild group** and **Warburg group**
- **New York Times (May 3, 1931)**: "One-sixth of total wealth of the world was represented by members of the Jekyll Island Club" (Morgan group only)
- **When all groups combined**: previous estimate that one-sixth becomes far larger

**True scope of power:**
> "Seven men who represented an estimated one-fourth of the total wealth of the entire world."

