## Chapter 1: A Meeting at Jekyll Island (continued)

### The Power Behind the Meeting

**1913 Pujo Committee Investigation** documented financial concentration:
- **Arsene Pujo** of Louisiana chaired House subcommittee on Currency and Banking
- Final report concluded "an established and well defined identity and community of interest between a few leaders of finance"
- "Great and rapidly growing concentration of the control of money and credit in the hands of these few men"

> "Under our system of issuing and distributing corporate securities the investing public does not buy directly from the corporation. The securities travel from the issuing house through middlemen to the investor. It is only the great banks or bankers with access to the mainsprings of the concentrated resources made up of other people's money... who have had the power to underwrite or guarantee the sale of large-scale security issues."

- Banks controlled where capital flowed, creating "great reservoirs of the people's money"
- Agents for out-of-town banks in the only public money market
- **1,748 bank failures** in the two decades preceding 1913
- This concentration developed "largely within the past five years" and was "fraught with peril to the welfare of the country"

**Estimate**: One-fourth of world's wealth represented by the seven men on that train (likely conservative)

### Destination Jekyll Island

**The Journey**:
- Train stopped in switching yard outside Raleigh, NC
- Private car uncoupled, passengers disappeared into regular southbound train
- Route: Raleigh → Atlanta → Savannah → Brunswick, Georgia

**Brunswick & Jekyll Island**:
- Small fishing village, population few thousand
- Jekyll Island: winter resort for the wealthy, purchased by **J.P. Morgan** and associates
- Cover story: duck hunting trip

**Secrecy Measures**:
- First-names-only for nine days
- Regular staff given vacation, new carefully screened staff brought in
- **Mr. Davison** (Jekyll Island owner) deflected newspaper reporters' questions about the mysterious Aldrich party
- Claimed it was merely personal friends duck hunting

> "It is difficult to imagine any event in history—including preparation for war—that was shielded from public view with greater mystery and secrecy."

### Purpose: Creating a Banking Cartel

**Jekyll Island meeting goal**:
- Structure and operation of a banking cartel
- Maximize profits by minimizing competition
- Make entry difficult for new competitors
- **Use police power of government to enforce the cartel agreement**
- Actual outcome: blueprint for the **Federal Reserve System**

### The Story is Confirmed

**Initial Denial**:
- For years, educators and historians denied Jekyll Island meeting happened
- **Ron Chernow**: "The Jekyll Island meeting would be the fountain of a thousand conspiracy theories"
- Story pieced together from participants themselves

**First Leak (1916)**:
- **B.C. Forbes** (founder of Forbes Magazine) wrote in Leslie's Weekly
- Article praised **Paul Warburg**
- Dramatic opening paragraph accurately described the secret expedition

**Paul Warburg's Confirmation (1930)**:
- Published 1,750-page book *The Federal Reserve System, Its Origin and Growth*
- Described the meeting but withheld location and names
- "The results of the conference were entirely confidential. Even the fact there had been a meeting was not permitted to become public"
- Footnote: "Though eighteen years have since gone by, I do not feel free to give a description of"

**James Warburg Confirmation (1964)**:
- **James Warburg** (Paul's son), appointed by FDR as Director of the Budget
- Book: *The Long Road Home*
- Father borrowed shotgun to disguise himself as duck hunter

**Nathaniel Wright Stephenson** (Aldrich's official biography):
- Six men went out to shoot ducks in autumn 1910
- **Paul Warburg** brought duck-shooting gear despite never having shot a duck
- "The duck shoot was a blind"
- Station master at Brunswick knew identities, reporters waiting
- Davison managed the situation: "They won't give us away"

**Frank Vanderlip Confirmation (1935)**:
- Saturday Evening Post article: "From Farm Boy to Financier"
- Described being "as secretive—indeed, as furtive—as any conspirator"
- "I do not feel it is any exaggeration to speak of our secret expedition to Jekyll Island as the occasion of the actual conception of what eventually became the Federal Reserve System"
- Participants told to leave last names behind, avoid dining together, come unobtrusively to train
- Used code names: Ben, Paul, Nelson, Abe (Abraham Piatt Andrew)
- Adopted aviation pioneers' names: **Wilbur and Orville** (Wright brothers)

> "If it were to be exposed publicly that our particular group had got together and written a banking bill, that bill would have no chance whatever of passage by Congress."

### The Structure Was Pure Cartel

**Cartel definition**: Independent businesses coordinating production, pricing, or marketing to reduce competition and increase profitability through shared monopoly

**Jekyll Island Participants**:
- Representatives of world's leading banking consortia
- **Morgan, Rockefeller, Rothschild, Warburg, Kuhn-Loeb**
- Often competitors with distrust, but united against common enemy: **competition**

**Competitive Threats (1910)**:
- Number of US banks **more than doubled** in previous ten years to over 20,000
- Most new banks in South and West, eroding New York banks' market share
- 1880s: almost all banks were **national banks** (federally chartered)
- 1896: non-national banks at 61%, holding 54% of deposits
- 1913: **71% non-national banks** holding **57% of deposits**
- This trend "simply had to be reversed"

**Industrial Capital Formation Threat**:
- Companies financing growth from profits rather than borrowed capital
- Free-market interest rates balanced debt and thrift
- 1900-1910: **70% of corporate funding generated internally**
- Federal government becoming thrifty, accumulating gold, redeeming Greenbacks, reducing national debt
- Banks losing influence

**Bankers' Goal**:
- Intervene in free market, tip interest rates downward to favor debt over thrift
- Disconnect money supply from gold, make it "more elastic"

### The Specter of Bank Failure

**Run on the Bank**:
- Customer deposits create "balance" (promise to pay back on demand)
- Loan customers receive balances withdrawn immediately
- Bank issues more promises than money in vault
- **Promises-to-pay often exceed savings deposits by 10-to-1**
- Only ~3% retained as cash in vault
- **Bank reserves underfunded by over 33,333%** (10-to-1 divided by 0.03)
- Small percentage withdrawal triggers collapse

**Currency Drains**:
- Occur even without depositor panic
- People write checks, deposited at different banks
- If check flows unequal, one bank must send real money to another
- Imbalance of few percentage points = same as run by depositors
- **Currency drain**: demand by other banks rather than depositors

**Common Cause (1910)**:
- Banks declaring bankruptcy usually followed **reckless loan policy**
- Loaned 90% of deposits (keeping $1 per $10), some pushed to 95%, 99%
- "The more loans, the better" to collect interest
- Practice of "loaning up" = pushing down reserve ratios

### A Bankers' Utopia

**Cartel Solution**:
- Force all banks to issue loans at same ratio to reserves
- No individual bank could be blamed for failure
- Blame shifted to "economy," "government policy," "interest rates," "trade deficits," "exchange-value of the dollar," "capitalist system"

**Without Cartel (1910)**:
- Reckless bank draws against reserves to make payments to conservative banks
- When reserves exhausted, forced into bankruptcy

**Historian John Klein**:
- "Financial panics of **1873, 1884, 1893, and 1907** were outgrowth of reserve pyramiding and excessive deposit creation by reserve city banks"
- Panics triggered by currency drains during prosperity when banks were loaned up
- Banks didn't fail because system was weak—**banks were weak** (practically no reserves)

### Jekyll Island Agenda

**Main challenges facing the seven men**:

1. **Stop growing influence of small rival banks**, ensure control over nation's financial resources remained with those present

2. **Make money supply more elastic** to reverse private capital formation trend and recapture industrial loan market

3. **Pool nation's bank reserves** into one large reserve so all banks motivated to follow same loan-to-deposit ratios, protecting cartel members from currency drains and bank runs

4. **Shift losses from bank owners to taxpayers** if whole banking system collapses

5. **Convince Congress the scheme protected the public** (most important task)

### The Cartel Adopts a Name

**The Problem**:
- Americans didn't like cartels
- Business enterprises fixing prices alien to free-enterprise system
- Word "cartel" could never be sold to voters

**The Solution**:
- Use emotionally neutral or alluring words
- Follow European practice: operate as a **central bank**
- Avoid word "bank," conjure image of federal government
- Establish regional branches as selling point
- **Nelson Aldrich** wanted to transplant Bank of England system to America
- **John Kenneth Galbraith**: "It was his [Aldrich's] thought to outflank the opposition by having not one central bank but many. And the word bank would itself be avoided."

**Only One Expert**:
- All present were bankers except Aldrich
- Only one expert on European central bank model
- **Paul Warburg** became dominant guiding mind
- **Galbraith**: "Warburg has, with some justice, been called the father of the system"
- **Professor Edwin Seligman** (J. & W. Seligman banking family, Columbia University Economics): "In its fundamental features, the Federal Reserve Act is the work of Mr. Warburg more than any other man in the country"

### The Real Daddy Warbucks

**Paul Moritz Warburg**:
- Leading member of **M.M. Warburg & Company** (Hamburg, Germany, Amsterdam)
- Came to US nine years prior (1901)
- Funded by Rothschild group to buy partnerships in **Kuhn, Loeb & Company** (New York)
- Continued as partners in Warburg of Hamburg
- Within twenty years: one of wealthiest men in America
- Unchallenged domination over railroad system
- Inspiration for **Daddy Warbucks** character in Little Orphan Annie comic strip

**Brother Max Warburg**:
- Financial adviser to Kaiser
- Director of **Reichsbank** (Germany's central bank)
- Cartel model used for Federal Reserve System
- Reichsbank later created massive hyperinflation, wiping out German middle class and economy

**Paul Warburg's Campaign**:
- Three years before Jekyll Island: published pamphlets
- *Defects and Needs of Our Banking System*
- *A Plan for A Modified Central Bank*
- Wide attention in financial and academic circles
- Complained American monetary system crippled by gold dependency and limited government bonds supply
- Needed **elastic money supply**
- Solution: follow German example—banks create currency based on "commercial paper" (IOUs from corporations)
- Tireless speaker, steady stream of published articles
- March 1910: NY Times eleven-part series by Warburg on Reserve Bank of United States

### The Message Was Plain for Those Who Understood

**Public Relations Strategy**:
- Thick smoke screen of technical jargon
- Focus on supposed benefits: lower interest rates, industrial project funding, prevent panics
- **No hint** underneath was master plan to serve private interests at public expense

**Insiders Understood**:
- **Aldrich** (1911 American Bankers Association address): "The organization proposed is not a bank, but a cooperative union of all the banks of the country for definite purposes." Precisely. A union of banks.
- **A. Barton Hepburn** (Chase National Bank, 1913): "The measure recognizes and adopts the principles of a central bank. Indeed, if it works out as the sponsors of the law hope, it will make all incorporated banks together joint owners of a central dominating power." Perfect cartel definition.

### Myth Accepted as History

**Official Story**: Federal Reserve created to stabilize economy

**Reality Since Inception**:
- Presided over crashes of 1921, 1929
- Great Depression 1929-1939
- Recessions in 1953, 1957, 1969, 1975, 1981
- Stock market Black Monday 1987
- **1000% inflation destroying 90% of dollar's purchasing power**

**By 1990**: $10,000 required to buy what $1,000 bought in 1914
- Incredible loss transferred to federal government as hidden taxation
- Federal Reserve System was the mechanism

**Current Consequences**:
- Corporate debt soaring
- Personal debt greater than ever
- Business and personal bankruptcies all-time high
- Banks, savings and loan associations failing in larger numbers than ever
- Interest on national debt consuming half of tax dollars
- Heavy industry replaced by overseas competitors
- International trade deficit for first time in history
- 75% of downtown LA and metropolitan areas owned by foreigners
- Over half the nation in economic recession

### First Reason to Abolish the System

**80-Year Track Record**:
- System failed its stated objectives
- After repeated personnel changes, operations under both parties, numerous monetary experiments, almost 100 charter revisions, countless new formulas and techniques
- Ample opportunity to work out procedural flaws

**Conclusion**: System failed not because it needs new rules or directors, but because **incapable of achieving stated objectives**

**Painful Answer**:
- Stated objectives were never the true objectives
- Created under circumstances of secrecy
- Authored by cartel members
- Actual performance over years reveals truth
- **Merely a cartel with government facade**

> "When there is a conflict between the public interest and the private needs of the cartel—a conflict that arises almost daily—the public will be sacrificed. That is the nature of the beast. It is foolish to expect a cartel to act in any other way."

**Establishment Defense**:
- System not intrinsically flawed
- Just in hands of bumbling oafs
- Economic factors "sooo complicated"

**William Greider** (*Secrets of the Temple*, 1987):
- Critical of Fed failures
- But claims not caused by System defect—just too complicated for the good men trying

**Greider's Own Research** contradicts this:
- New companies prospered without Wall Street
- New regional banks handled their funds
- New York's share of bank deposits still huge (half nation's total) but declining steadily
- Wall Street still "biggest kid on the block" but less able to bully

> "This trend was a crucial fact of history, a misunderstood reality that completely alters the political meaning of the reform legislation that created the Federal Reserve.... The money reforms enacted in 1913... helped to preserve the status quo, to stabilize the old order. Money-center bankers would not only gain dominance over the new central bank, but would also enjoy new insulation against instability and their own decline."

**Anthony Sutton** (Hoover Institution, California State University):

> "Warburg's revolutionary plan to get American Society to go to work for Wall Street was astonishingly simple.... The Federal Reserve System is a legal private monopoly of the money supply operated for the benefit of the few under the guise of protecting and promoting the public interest."

**Paul Warburg's biographer Harold Kellock**:

> "Paul M. Warburg is probably the mildest-mannered man that ever personally conducted a revolution. It was a bloodless revolution: he did not attempt to rouse the populace to arms. He stepped forth armed simply with an idea. And he conquered. That's the amazing thing. A shy, sensitive man, he imposed his idea on a nation of a hundred million people."

### Summary

The Federal Reserve System blueprint was drafted at secret November 1910 meeting at J.P. Morgan's Jekyll Island resort by seven men representing one-fourth of world's wealth, designed as banking cartel to eliminate competition and use government power for enforcement.

