## Chapter 1 (continued): The Jekyll Island Meeting

### The Five Objectives of the Cartel

- Stop growing competition from newer banks
- Obtain franchise to create money out of nothing for lending
- Get control of reserves of all banks to protect reckless members from currency drains and bank runs
- Get taxpayers to pick up cartel's inevitable losses
- Convince Congress the purpose was to protect the public

> "The Fed has failed to achieve its stated objectives. That is because those were never its true goals. As a banking cartel, and in terms of the five objectives stated above, it has been an unqualified success."

### The Seven Attendees at Jekyll Island

**The seven men represented an estimated one-fourth of the total wealth of the entire world:**

1. **Nelson W. Aldrich** — Republican "whip" in Senate, Chairman of National Monetary Commission, father-in-law to John D. Rockefeller, Jr.
2. **Henry P. Davison** — Senior Partner of J.P. Morgan Company
3. **Charles D. Norton** — President of 1st National Bank of New York
4. **A. Piatt Andrew** — Assistant Secretary of Treasury; **Frank A. Vanderlip**, President of National City Bank of New York, representing William Rockefeller
5. **Benjamin Strong** — head of J.P. Morgan's Bankers Trust Company, later became head of the Federal Reserve System
6. **Paul M. Warburg** — partner in Kuhn, Loeb & Company, representing the Rothschilds and Warburgs in Europe

## Chapter 2: The Name of the Game is Bailout

### Football Analogy

- Understanding Federal Reserve operations requires knowing the rules of the "game"
- Like witnessing professional football for the first time — total chaos without understanding the rules
- Federal Reserve monetary system operates with repeated "plays," definite rules, clear objectives
- Most Americans don't understand the rules regarding monetary matters

### The Objective: Shifting Losses to Taxpayers

**The name of the game is Bailout**

- Objective: shift inevitable losses from owners of larger banks to taxpayers
- Federal Reserve, FDIC, and Federal Deposit Loan Corporation guarantee that massive loans to large corporations and governments will not fall entirely on bank owners if those loans default
- Prevents vast unemployment and economic disruption — or so the argument goes

### Rules of the Game

**How banks create profit:**
- Federal Reserve allows commercial banks to create checkbook money out of nothing (detailed in Chapter 10: The Mandrake Mechanism)
- Banks profit by lending this created money and collecting interest

**The accounting problem:**
- Loan shows as asset (earning interest, will be repaid)
- Equal liability exists (newly created checkbook money in circulation, eventually returns as canceled checks)
- Bank has potential money pay-out liability equal to loan amount

**When borrowers default:**
- Most money was created from nothing, cost bank nothing except bookkeeping overhead
- Little tangible value actually lost — primarily a bookkeeping entry
- But bookkeeping loss is undesirable: removes loan asset without reducing liabilities
- Difference must come from equity of stockholders or deducted from current profits
- If bank forced to write off large bad loans, amount could exceed entire value of owners' equity
- When that happens, game over — bank is insolvent

### The Perpetual-Debt Play

**Banks prefer large loans to corporations and governments:**
- Single loan to third-world country netting hundreds of millions in annual interest is easier to process than $50,000 loan to local merchant
- Government mechanisms ensure banks continue receiving interest even if loan defaults
- Small businessman finds it increasingly difficult to borrow at reasonable rates
- Public won't accept bailing out "the little guy" — dollar amounts too small
- Only when figures become mind-boggling does bailout become plausible

**Banks prefer perpetual debt:**
- Don't really want loans repaid, except as evidence of borrower dependability
- Profit comes from interest, not repayment
- Better to have existing borrower pay only interest, never principal
- Process called **rolling over the debt**
- Banks prefer lending to governments because they don't expect those loans ever to be repaid

> "If we had a truth-in-Government act comparable to the truth-in-advertising law, every note issued by the Treasury would be obliged to include a sentence stating: 'This note will be redeemed with the proceeds from an identical note which will be sold to the public when this one comes due.'" — **Walter Wriston**, Chairman of Citicorp Bank (1982)

**Treasury bill auctions:**
- When conducted in U.S., described as "Treasury bill auction"
- When conducted abroad in foreign language, media speaks of country "rolling over its debts"
- Perception remains that disaster is inevitable — but it is not

**Government borrowing reality:**
- Few recorded instances in history of government actually getting out of debt
- In era of $100-billion deficits, no one lending money to government expects it will be paid at maturity except by government selling a new bill of like amount

### The Debt Roll-Over Play

**The roll-over mechanism:**
- System makes it profitable for banks to make large, unsound loans
- Most unsound loans eventually go into default
- Bank rolls over the loan — often stage-managed to appear as concession, but actually moves toward perpetual interest
- Eventually borrower can't pay even the interest
- Bank creates additional money out of nothing, lends it to borrower to continue paying interest
- This maintains old loan on books as asset, increases apparent size of asset, results in higher interest payments and greater profit

### The Up-the-Ante Play

**When borrower becomes restless:**
- Borrower realizes he's merely working for the bank
- Interest payments stop
- Teams go into huddle, then rush to scrimmage line
- Borrower can't/won't pay — collect if you can
- Lender threatens to blackball borrower
- "Compromise" worked out: bank creates still more money out of nothing, lends it to borrower
- Covers interest on both previous loans AND provides additional money for borrower to spend on something other than interest
- **Perfect score:** borrower has fresh money plus enough to keep making interest payments
- Bank has larger assets, higher interest income, greater profits

### The Rescheduling Play

**When debt pit deepens:**
- Previous plays repeated until borrower sinks deeper with no prospects of climbing out
- Interest payments become so large they represent almost entire corporate earnings or country's total tax base
- Default seems inevitable
- Players return to scrimmage line
- Referees called in, horn blasts, announcement: "This loan has been rescheduled"

**What rescheduling means:**
- Usually combination of lower interest rate and longer repayment period
- Effect primarily cosmetic — reduces monthly payment but extends period into future
- Makes current burden easier to carry, but makes repayment of capital even more unlikely
- Postpones day of reckoning
- **The loan remains as an asset, and the interest payments continue**

### The Protect-the-Public Play

**The final maneuver:**
- Borrower realizes he can never repay capital, flatly refuses to pay interest
- Time for Final Maneuver

**Banking Safety Digest finding:**
> "Note that, except for third-world loans, most of the large banks in the country are operating quite profitably. In contrast with the continually-worsening S&L crisis, the banks' profitability has been the engine with which they have been working off (albeit slowly) their overseas debt.... At last year's profitability levels, the banking industry could, in theory, 'buy out' the entirety of their own Latin American loans within two years."

**Why banks don't absorb losses:**
- Would be major loss to stockholders (little/no dividends during adjustment)
- Chief executive officer would soon be looking for new job
- Banks continue making gigantic loans to governments in Africa, Red China, Eastern Europe
- Little hope these loans will perform differently than Latin America
- Most important reason: **standard play can breathe life back into dead loans and reactivate income stream**

**The play:**
- Captains of both teams approach referee and Game Commissioner
- Request game be extended — in interest of the public (spectators enjoying themselves)
- Request parking-lot attendants quietly remove hub caps from every car
- Hub caps sold to provide additional salaries for players, referee, Commissioner
- "Fair" since they're working overtime for benefit of spectators

**In recognizable form:**
- President of lending bank and finance officer of defaulting corporation/government approach Congress
- Explain borrower exhausted ability to service loan
- Without federal government assistance, dire consequences for American people
- Unemployment, hardship at home, massive world market disruptions
- Exports will drop, foreign capital dry up
- Congress needed to provide money to borrower (directly or indirectly) to continue paying interest and initiate new spending programs
- Eventually borrower will be able to pay everyone back

**The proposal elements:**
- Borrower accepts direction of third-party referee adopting austerity program
- Bank writes off small part of loan as gesture of willingness to share burden
- This move foreseen from beginning — small step backward to achieve giant stride forward
- Amount lost through write-off created out of nothing initially
- Without Final Maneuver, entirety would be written off
- Modest write-down dwarfed by amount gained through restoration of income stream

### The Guaranteed-Payment Play

**Government becomes co-signer:**
- One standard variation: government doesn't directly provide funds, but guarantees future payments should borrower default
- Once Congress agrees, government becomes co-signer
- Inevitable losses finally lifted from bank ledger and placed onto backs of American taxpayer

**How money flows:**
- Through complex system of federal agencies, international agencies, foreign aid, direct subsidies
- All extract payments from American people, channel them to deadbeat borrowers who send them to banks to service loans
- Very little money actually comes from taxes
- Almost all generated by Federal Reserve System
- Newly created money returns to banks, quickly moves into economy where it mingles with and dilutes value of money already there
- **Result: appearance of rising prices but, in reality, lowering of the value of the dollar**

**Public ignorance:**
- American people have no idea they're paying the bill
- Think greedy businessman raises prices, selfish laborer demands higher wages, unworthy farmer demands too much for crop, wealthy foreigner bids up prices
- Don't realize these groups also victimized by monetary system constantly being eroded in value by Federal Reserve System

**Phil Donahue show example:**
- Topic: Savings and Loan crisis, billions it would cost taxpayer
- Man from audience rose, asked angrily: "Why can't the government pay for these debts instead of the taxpayer?"
- Audience of several hundred people actually **cheered in enthusiastic approval**

### Prosperity Through Insolvency

**The fractional-reserve banking system:**
- Large corporate loans often guaranteed by federal government
- One would think banks making those loans would never have problem
- Yet many still manage to bungle into insolvency
- **Insolvency actually inherent in system itself** — system called **fractional-reserve banking**

**Banks can operate while insolvent:**
- As long as customers don't know it
- Money brought into being, transmuted from one imaginary form to another by ledger entries
- Creative bookkeeping can make bottom line appear to balance
- Problem arises when depositors decide to withdraw money

**When bank runs out of money:**
- Can't keep promise that deposits "payable upon demand"
- Bank must close doors, depositors waiting outside keep waiting

**Proper solution:**
- Require banks to honor contracts like all other businesses
- If deposits "payable upon demand," should hold enough cash to make good regardless of when customers want it or how many want it
- Should keep cash in vault equal to 100% of deposit accounts
- **Hat-check girl analogy:** when we give hat to hat-check girl and get receipt, we don't expect her to rent it out while we eat dinner hoping she'll get it back in time for our departure
- Expect all hats to remain there all the time so there's no question of getting ours back precisely when we want it

**What banks actually do:**
- If bank tells us it's going to lend our deposit to earn interest, should also tell us forthrightly we cannot have money back on demand
- Cannot have money back because it's loaned out, not in vault any longer
- Customers earning interest on accounts should be told they have **time deposits, not demand deposits**
- Bank needs stated amount of time to recover loaned money

**The reality:**
- Bank customers seldom informed
- Told they can have money any time they want it AND paid interest as well
- Even if they don't receive interest, bank does
- This is how so many customer services can be offered at little or no direct cost

**Federal Reserve's role:**
- System legalized and institutionalized dishonesty of issuing more hat checks than hats
- Devised complex methods of disguising this practice as perfectly proper and normal feature of banking
- Students of finance told there's simply no other way for system to function
- Once premise accepted, attention focused not on inherent fraud, but on ways and means to live with it and make it as painless as possible

**Thin layer of cash:**
- Based on assumption only small percentage of depositors will ever want to withdraw money at same time
- Federal Reserve allows nation's commercial banks to operate with incredibly thin layer of cash to cover their promises to pay "on demand"
- When bank runs out of money and unable to keep promise, **System acts as lender of last resort**
- Banker language: stands ready to create money out of nothing and immediately lend it to any bank in trouble
- Details in Chapter 8

**Practical limits:**
- Even Fed won't support bank that's gotten itself so deeply in hole it has no realistic chance of digging out
- When bank's bookkeeping assets finally become less than liabilities, rules call for transferring losses to depositors themselves
- **Depositors pay twice: once as taxpayers and again as depositors**
- Mechanism: **Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation**

### The FDIC Play

**What FDIC does:**
- Guarantees every insured deposit will be paid back regardless of financial condition of bank
- Money comes from special fund derived from assessments against participating banks
- Banks don't pay assessment — bulk of cost ultimately passed to customers via higher service fees and lower interest rates on deposits

**FDIC as "insurance" — deceptive advertising:**
- Primary condition of insurance: must avoid what underwriters call **"moral hazard"**
- Situation where policyholder has little incentive to avoid or prevent what's being insured against
- When moral hazard present, normal for people to become careless, likelihood increases what's being insured against will actually happen

**Parking-fine analogy:**
- Government program forcing everyone to pay equal amount into fund to protect from parking fines
- Result: (1) just about everyone soon getting parking tickets; (2) since so many tickets, taxes to pay for them would greatly exceed previous cost of paying without "protection"

**How FDIC operates:**
- Depositors told insured accounts protected in event bank becomes insolvent
- To pay for protection, each bank assessed specified percentage of total deposits
- Percentage same for all banks regardless of previous record or how risky their loans
- Banks making reckless loans earn higher rate of interest than conservative loans
- Also far more likely to collect from fund, yet pay not one cent more
- Conservative banks penalized, gradually motivated to make riskier loans to keep up with competitors and get "fair share" of fund's protection
- **Moral hazard built right into system**
- With protection against parking tickets, FDIC increases likelihood what's being insured against will actually happen
- **Not solution to problem, part of the problem**

### Real Insurance Would Be a Blessing

**True deposit-insurance program (voluntary, risk-geared rates):**
- Banks with solid loans could obtain protection for depositors at reasonable rates (chances of insurance company paying would be small)
- Banks with unsound loans would have to pay much higher rates or possibly couldn't obtain coverage at any price
- Depositors would know instantly a bank without insurance not place where they want money
- To attract deposits, banks would have to have insurance
- To have insurance at affordable rates, would have to demonstrate to insurance company financial affairs in good order
- Banks failing to meet minimum standards of sound business practice would soon have no customers and be forced out of business
- **Voluntary, private insurance program would act as powerful regulator of entire banking industry far more effectively and honestly than any political scheme ever could**

**FDIC "protection" reality:**
- Not insurance in any sense of the word
- Merely part of political scheme to bail out most influential members of banking cartel when they get into financial difficulty
- First line of defense: have large, defaulted loans restored to life by Congressional pledge of tax dollars
- If that fails and bank can no longer conceal insolvency through creative bookkeeping, almost certain anxious depositors will line up to withdraw money (which bank doesn't have)
- **Second line of defense: FDIC steps in, makes payments for them**

**Who really benefits:**
- Bankers don't want this to happen — last resort
- If bank rescued this fashion, management fired, what's left of business usually absorbed by another bank
- Stock value will plummet, but affects small stockholders only
- Those with controlling interest and those in management know long in advance of pending catastrophe
- Able to sell bulk of shares while price still high
- **People who create problem seldom suffer economic consequences**

### The FDIC Will Never Be Adequately Funded

**FDIC's inadequate reserves:**
- Never will have enough money to cover potential liability for entire banking system
- If that amount were in existence, could be held by banks themselves, insurance fund wouldn't be necessary
- FDIC operates on same assumption as banks: only small percentage will ever need money at same time
- Amount held in reserve never more than few percentage points of total liability
- Typically, FDIC holds about $1.20 for every $100 of covered deposits
- At time of writing, figure slipped to only 70 cents and still dropping
- **Financial exposure about 99.3% larger than safety net supposed to catch it**
- Failure of just one or two large banks in system could completely wipe out entire fund

**Gets even worse:**
- Although ledger may show millions or billions in fund, also creative bookkeeping
- By law, money collected from bank assessments must be invested in Treasury bonds (loaned to government, spent immediately by Congress)
- In final stage, FDIC itself runs out of money, turns first to Treasury, then to Congress for help
- Step presented in media as though it were sign of system's great strength

> "Should the agencies need more money yet, Congress has pledged the full faith and credit of the federal government." — U.S. News & World Report

**What "full faith and credit" actually means:**
- Congress, already deeply in debt, has no money either
- Doesn't dare openly raise taxes for shortfall
- Applies for additional loan by offering still more Treasury bonds for sale
- Public picks up portion of I.O.U.s
- Federal Reserve buys the rest

**The Fed has no money either:**
- Responds by creating out of nothing an amount of brand new money equal to I.O.U.s
- Through magic of central banking, FDIC finally funded
- New money gushes into banks where used to pay off depositors
- From there floods through economy diluting value of all money, causing prices to rise
- Old paycheck doesn't buy as much any more
- But bank's doors open again, all depositors happy — until they return to cars and discover missing hub caps

**That is what is meant by "the full faith and credit of the federal government"**

## Summary

**Understanding the bailout game:**
- Although national monetary events may appear mysterious and chaotic, governed by well-established rules bankers and politicians rigidly follow
- Central fact: all money in banking system created out of nothing through process of making loans
- Defaulted loan costs bank little tangible value, but shows up on ledger as reduction in assets without corresponding reduction in liabilities
- If bad loans exceed size of assets, bank becomes technically insolvent, must close doors

**First rule of survival:**
- Avoid writing off large, bad loans
- If possible, at least continue receiving interest payments on them
- To accomplish: endangered loans rolled over and increased in size
- Provides borrower with money to continue paying interest plus fresh funds for new spending
- Basic problem not solved, but postponed for little while and made worse

**Final solution:**
- Have federal government guarantee payment of loan should borrower default in future
- Accomplished by convincing Congress that not to do so would result in great damage to economy and hardship for people
- From that point forward, burden of loan removed from bank's ledger, transferred to taxpayer

**Should this fail:**
- Last resort: use FDIC to pay off depositors
- FDIC not insurance — presence of "moral hazard" makes thing it supposedly protects against more likely to happen
- Portion of FDIC funds derived from assessments against banks
- Ultimately paid by depositors themselves
- When funds run out, balance provided by Federal Reserve System in form of freshly created new money
- Floods through economy causing appearance of rising prices but, in reality, lowering of value of dollar
- **Final cost of bailout passed to public in form of hidden tax called inflation**

## Chapter 3: Protectors of the Public

**Upcoming examples:**
- Game-Called-Bailout as actually applied to specific cases including Penn Central, Lockheed, New York City, Chrysler, Commonwealth Bank of Detroit, First Pennsylvania Bank, Continental Illinois, and others
<!-- pp. 61-80 -->

## Chapter 3: Protectors of the Public (continued)

### Penn Central Railroad: Anatomy of a Bailout

#### The Three-Way Bonanza
- 1972 investigation by **Congressman Wright Patman** (Chairman, House Banking Committee) exposed systematic fraud
- Banker-managers engineered profits through:
  - (1) Received dividends on worthless stock
  - (2) Earned interest on loans that paid those dividends
  - (3) Unloaded 1.8 million shares at artificially high prices
- Top executives personally saved over $1 million through stock manipulation
- Pattern: borrow funds, seize control, bleed assets, dump debt on taxpayers or remaining stockholders

#### The Federal Reserve's Weekend Rescue
- **Arthur Burns** (Fed Chairman) wanted direct money infusion but rules prevented it
- Over weekend, Burns called heads of Federal Reserve banks nationwide
- **William Treiber** (first vice-president, NY Fed) contacted ten largest NYC banks Sunday
- **Discount Window** opened Monday — Fed created money from nothing, loaned to commercial banks who re-lent to Penn Central
- Burns kept Board in session all Monday to change **Regulation Q** enabling money flow to CDs

> "I kept the Board in session practically all day to change regulation Q so that money could flow into CDs at the banks." — Arthur Burns

- **Chris Welles** called it "the Fed's finest hour"

#### Banks Demand Taxpayer Guarantees
- Banks refused to advance funds without taxpayer co-signature
- Penn Central executives, bankers, union reps descended on Congress
- Navy Department invoked "defense resources" argument
- Congress response: 13% pay raise for union employees (worsening cash drain), then **Emergency Rail Services Act of 1970** — $125 million in federal loan guarantees

#### The Nationalization Solution
- "Nationalization" = euphemism for tax dollars disappearing into losses
- 1971: **AMTRAK** created (passenger services)
- 1973: **CONRAIL** created (freight services, five other Eastern railroads)
- CONRAIL: 85% government-owned initially, returned to private sector 1987, now profitable
- AMTRAK: political control, operates at loss, sustained by subsidies — $5.7 billion from Congress by 1997, liabilities exceeded assets by $14 billion (1998)

### Lockheed Corporation

#### The Defense Contractor Bailout
- 1970: Lockheed, nation's largest defense contractor, near bankruptcy
- Bank of America and smaller banks had loaned $400 million
- Banks joined with management, stockholders, labor unions to lobby Washington
- Arguments: 31,000 jobs lost, hundreds of sub contractors bankrupted, suppliers forced out, national security jeopardized
- **Treasury Secretary John B. Connally** engineered bailout: government guaranteed $250 million in additional loans

#### The Perverse Incentive
- Government now motivated to award Lockheed maximum defense contracts at maximum profit
- Indirect method of repaying banks with tax dollars without arousing public indignation
- More efficient contractors lost business, but "that could not be proven"
- By 1977: loan repaid, widely advertised as proof of bailout success

**Critical insight**: No evidence Lockheed became more cost efficient. Every dollar repaying loans came from defense contracts awarded by same government guaranteeing those loans. Taxpayers paid either way.

### New York City

#### The Welfare-State Economy
- 1975: NYC unable to make payroll
- Cause: welfare state within itself, political corruption, bureaucratic fraud
- Employment: 49 city employees per 1,000 residents vs. average large city's 31 (58% excess)
- Municipal salaries far exceeded private sector: city porter $203/week vs. private hospital X-ray tech $187/week; city bank teller $154/week; city subway change maker $212/week
- Municipal benefits fully twice as generous as private industry
- Additional costs: free college, subsidized housing, free medical care, endless welfare programs

#### The $2.3 Billion Debt
- City taxes inadequate even with Albany and Washington transfers
- By 1975: floated maximum bonds, market saturated, no more lenders
- Two billion dollars of debt held by small group: **Chase Manhattan** and **Citicorp**
- Bankers and city fathers lobbied Congress: largest city in world cannot be allowed to fail
- **David Rockefeller** (Chase Manhattan) persuaded **Helmut Schmidt** (West German Chancellor) to warn media that NYC disaster could trigger international financial crisis

#### The Federal Rescue
- December 1975: Congress authorized Treasury to make direct loans up to $2.3 billion — more than doubling city's debt to banks
- Interest payments on old debt resumed immediately
- Money borrowed by Congress (itself deeply in debt), created by Federal Reserve System
- Money taken from taxpayers through inflation, but banks repaid

**Outcome**: Austerity program and repayment schedule attached to loan — none honored. NYC continued as welfare Utopia, unlikely to ever escape debt.

### Chrysler Corporation

#### The Auto Giant's Crisis
- 1978: Chrysler on verge of bankruptcy after rolling over debt multiple times
- OPEC embargo pushed up gasoline costs, small-automobile imports gained popularity
- Chrysler continued building traditional gas hogs, now saddled with unsaleable inventory and staggering debt
- High interest rates + fears of U.S. military involvement in Cambodia = stock market slump
- Banks felt credit crunch; "money makers themselves were scouring for money"

#### The Political Pressure Campaign
- Chrysler needed over $1 billion in new capital; banks hard-pressed to create that money
- Managers, bankers, union leaders found common cause in Washington
- Arguments: hardship to thousands of employees and families; unemployment shock waves across country; loss of competition (only two major brands instead of three)
- Bill passed: Treasury to guarantee up to $1.5 billion in new loans
- Banks wrote down $600 million old loans, exchanged $700 million for preferred stock

#### The Hidden Subsidy
- Stock exchanged for previously uncollectable debt rose drastically after settlement announced
- Interest payments resumed on old debt balance; banks replaced written-down portion with fresh loans fully guaranteed by taxpayers
- **Interest rate advantage**: Chrysler obtained loans at 10.35% while more solvent competitor Ford paid 13.5%
- Applying 3.15% difference to $1.5 billion over six declining years = $165 million savings minimum
- **Real value far greater**: without guarantee, corporation would have ceased to exist and banks would have taken loss of almost entire loan exposure

### Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (FDIC)

#### Three Bailout Options
- **Payoff**: pay insured depositors, let bank fall to liquidators (small banks, no political clout)
- **Sell off**: larger bank assumes assets and liabilities of failing bank; services uninterrupted, customers unaware (small and medium banks)
- **Bailout**: bank does not close, everyone fully protected — insured or not (large banks only, "rarely to an elect few")

> "In a bailout, the bank does not close, and everyone — insured or not —is fully protected.... Such privileged treatment is accorded by FDIC only rarely to an elect few." — **Irvine Sprague**, former FDIC director

#### The Essentiality Doctrine
- **FDI Act** gives FDIC board sole discretion to prevent bank failure "at whatever cost"
- Board need only find insured bank "in danger of failing" and "is essential to provide adequate banking service in its community"
- FDIC boards reluctant to make essentiality finding unless "clear and present danger to the nation's financial system"

#### Favoritism Toward Large Banks
- In bailout, FDIC covers all deposits whether insured or not
- Banks pay assessment only on insured deposits
- Uninsured deposits get free coverage paid by someone else
- **Which deposits are uninsured?** Those over $100,000 and those held outside United States
- **Which banks hold majority of such deposits?** Large ones, particularly those with extensive overseas operations
- Large banks get free ride on uninsured accounts; cost passed to smaller banks and taxpayer

> "Part of the plan at Jekyll Island was to give a competitive edge to the large banks."

### Unity Bank (Boston)

#### The First Essentiality Exception (1971)
- **Unity Bank and Trust Company** (Roxbury section of Boston): hopelessly insolvent
- Federal agency findings: capital depleted, most loans bad, weak collection practices, worst personnel problem (overstaffing + inexperience)
- Examiners: "two persons for every job, and neither one had been taught the job"
- Only $11.4 million on books — small by current standards

#### Political Considerations Trump Market Discipline
- Normally depositors paid back, stockholders lose investment (market discipline)
- **Unity Bank different**: located in black neighborhood, minority-owned
- 1971: specter of rioting in black communities haunted Congress halls
- Political pressures determined decision more than logic or merit

> "If market discipline means anything, stockholders should be wiped out when a bank fails. Our assistance should have the side effect ... of keeping the stockholders alive at government expense." — **Irvine Sprague**

> "Neither Wille [another director] nor I had any trouble viewing the problem in its broader social context. We were willing to look for a creative solution.... My vote to make the 'essentiality' finding and thus save the little bank was probably foreordained, an inevitable legacy of Watts.... The Watts riots ultimately triggered the essentiality doctrine." — Sprague

- July 22, 1971: FDIC declared Unity Bank operation essential, authorized $1.5 million direct infusion
- 1976: FDIC staff report confirmed operations "as slipshod and haphazard as ever"; agency rolled over "loan" five more years
- June 30, 1982: Massachusetts Banking Commissioner finally revoked charter
- No riots; FDIC quietly wrote off $4,463,000 as final bailout cost

### Commonwealth Bank of Detroit (1972)

#### The $1.5 Billion Chase Manhattan Takeover
- Unity bailout = exception to rule (small banks dispensable, giants must be saved)
- From that point forward: FDIC game plan strictly according to Hoyle
- 1972: **Bank of the Common-Wealth of Detroit** ($1.5 billion) — Commonwealth funded most growth through loans from Chase Manhattan (NYC)
- When Commonwealth went belly up (securities speculation, self-dealing by management), Chase seized 39% of common stock, took control attempting to recover money

#### The Essentiality Arguments
- Chase officers suggested Commonwealth was "public interest problem" for government to resolve
- Bankers argued: (1) served many minority neighborhoods; (2) not enough other banks in city to absorb operation without unhealthy concentration
- **Minority issue**: every neighborhood with Commonwealth branch served by other banks; if liquidated, branches would have been purchased by competitors, service continued
- Thrown in for good measure; no one took it seriously

#### The Saudi Arabian Solution
- January 17, 1972: Commonwealth bailed out with $60 million loan plus federal guarantees
- Chase absorbed some losses from Commonwealth's weak bond portfolio (minor compared to what would have been lost without FDIC intervention)
- FDIC engineered sale to **First Arabian Corporation**, Luxembourg firm funded by Saudi princes
- "Better to have financial power concentrated in Saudi Arabia than in Detroit"
- Bank continued to flounder; 1983: resold to former **Detroit Bank & Trust Company** (now Comerica)
- Dreaded concentration of local power realized after all, but not until Chase Manhattan walked away with most losses covered

### First Pennsylvania Bank (1980)

#### The Nation's Twenty-Third Largest Bank
- First Penn: nation's 23rd largest bank, assets exceeding $9 billion (six times Commonwealth, 900 times Unity)
- Nation's oldest bank, dating to **Bank of North America** (created by Continental Congress, 1781)

#### Aggressive Go-Go Banking
- Rapid growth and handsome profits under **John Bunting** (chief executive, formerly economist at Federal Reserve Bank of Philadelphia)
- Bunting epitomized era's go-go bankers: vastly increased earnings ratios by reducing safety margins, risky loans, bond market speculation
- Gambles profitable while economy expanded; stockholders loved him
- Bond market gamble turned sour; by 1979 First Penn forced to sell off profitable subsidiaries for operating funds
- Carrying $328 million in questionable loans — $16 million more than entire stockholder investment
- Bank insolvent; time to hit up taxpayer

#### The Domino Theory
- Bankers went to Washington with case; spokesmen from **Bank of America**, **Citibank**, ever-present **Chase Manhattan**
- Argued: bailout "essential" for continuation of banking services in Philadelphia AND critical to preservation of world economic stability
- Bank so large, if allowed to fail, would act as first domino leading to international financial crisis
- FDIC directors initially resisted, earned angry impatience of Federal Reserve

> "We were far from a decision on how to proceed. There was strong pressure from the beginning not to let the bank fail. Besides hearing from the bank itself, the other large banks, and the comptroller, we heard frequently from the Fed. I recall at one session, Fred Schultz, the Fed deputy chairman, argued in an ever rising voice, that there were no alternatives —we had to save the bank. He said, 'Quit wasting time talking about anything else!'" — **Irvine Sprague**

#### The Fed vs. FDIC Tension
- Fed's role as lender of last resort generated contention during this period
- Fed lending heavily to First Pennsylvania, fully secured
- **Fed Chairman Paul Volcker** planned to continue funding indefinitely until merger or bailout arranged

> "The theory had never been tested. I was not sure I wanted it to be just then." — Sprague

- FDIC directors did not want to cross swords with Federal Reserve System; did not want to be blamed for tumbling entire world economic system by allowing first domino to fall
- Bailout package: $325 million loan from FDIC (interest-free first year, subsidized rate thereafter — about half market rate)
- Several other banks financially tied to First Penn loaned additional $175 million, offered $1 billion line of credit
- FDIC insisted on this to demonstrate banking industry itself helping, had faith in venture
- Federal Reserve opened Discount Window offering low-interest funds for that purpose

#### The Happier Outcome (Partially)
- At end of five-year taxpayer subsidy: FDIC loan fully repaid
- Bank remained on shaky ground; final page of episode not yet written
- **Every dollar used to pay back loans came from defense contracts awarded by same government guaranteeing those loans**

### Continental Illinois (1984)

#### The Big Event
- Early 1980s: Chicago's **Continental Illinois** = nation's seventh-largest bank
- $42 billion assets, 12,000 employees in offices worldwide
- Loan portfolio undergone spectacular growth: net income on loans literally doubled in five years, reached $254 million annually by 1981
- Named by **Dun's Review** as one of five best-managed companies
- Opinion leaders failed to perceive spectacular performance due to financing shaky business enterprises and foreign governments (not expertise in banking/investment)

#### The Unraveling Begins
- Gaudy fabric unraveled Fourth of July weekend 1982 with **Penn Square Bank** (Oklahoma) failure
- Penn Square: notorious shopping-center bank booked $1 billion in oil and gas loans, resold them to Continental just before energy market collapse
- Other loans began souring simultaneously: Mexican and Argentine debt crisis, major corporate bankruptcies receiving daily headlines
- Continental placed large chunks of easy money with all of them
- Credit rating dropped; cautious depositors withdrew funds; new funding dwindled to trickle
- Bank desperate for cash to meet daily expenses; began offering unrealistically high CD rates
- Loan officers sent to scour European and Japanese markets, conduct public relations campaign convincing market managers bank was calm and steady

> "We had the Continental Illinois Reassurance Brigade and we fanned out all over the world." — **David Taylor**, bank chairman

#### Image Over Substance
- "In fantasy land of modern finance, glitter often more important than substance, image more valuable than reality"
- Bank paid usual quarterly dividend in August despite intensifying cash crunch
- Like Penn Central Railroad twelve years earlier: calculated to project business-as-usual prosperity image
- Ploy worked for a while; by November public confidence restored, stock recovered to pre-Penn Square level
- By March 1983 risen even higher; worst yet to come

#### The Cascade of Non-Performing Loans
- End of 1983: burden of non-performing loans reached unbearable proportions, growing at alarming rate
- 1984: $2.7 billion non-performing loans
- Bank sold off profitable credit-card operation for income, obtain money for paying stockholders expected quarterly dividend
- Internal structure near collapse; external facade continued to look like business as usual

#### The World's First Electronic Bank Run
- First crack in facade: 11:39 AM Tuesday, May 8, 1984
- **Reuters** (British news agency) wire service: banks in Netherlands, West Germany, Switzerland, Japan increased interest rates on loans to Continental, some withdrawing funds
- Story quoted bank's official statement: bankruptcy rumors "totally preposterous"
- Hours later, **Commodity News Service** second rumor: Japanese bank interested in buying Continental

**The Electronic Panic**:
- Following morning: foreign investors began withdrawing deposits
- $1 billion in Asian money moved out first day
- Next day (24+ hours after Continental's bankruptcy assurance): long-standing customer **Board of Trade Clearing Corporation** withdrew $50 million
- Word spread through financial wire services; panic began
- **World's first global electronic bank run**

> "The Continental run was like some modernistic fantasy: there were no throngs of hysterical depositors, just cool nightmare flashes on computer screens." — Ron Chernow

> "Inside the bank, all was calm, the teller lines moved as always, and bank officials recall no visible sign of trouble — except in the wire room. Here the employees knew what was happening as withdrawal order after order moved on the wire, bleeding Continental to death. Some cried." — Sprague

- By Friday: borrowed $3.6 billion from Federal Reserve to cover escaping deposits
- Consortium of sixteen banks (led by **Morgan Guaranty**) offered generous thirty-day line of credit — far short of need
- Within seven more days: outflow surged to over $6 billion

#### The Institutional Run
- "Beginning, almost all action at institutional level: other banks and professionally managed funds closely monitoring every minuscule detail of financial markets"
- General public had no inkling of catastrophe unfolding

#### The Golden Moment for the Fed and FDIC
- **This was the moment for which Federal Reserve and FDIC were created**
- Without government intervention: Continental would have collapsed, stockholders wiped out, depositors badly damaged, financial world learned banks must practice prudent management
- Future banking practices severely altered; long-term economic benefit to nation enormous
- **With government intervention**: discipline of free market suspended; cost of failure/fraud politically passed to taxpayers
- Depositors live in dream world of false security; banks operate recklessly, fraudulently with knowledge political partners will rescue them

### FDIC Generosity with Tax Dollars

#### The Uninsured Deposit Subsidy
- Continental challenge: only 4% of liability covered by FDIC "insurance"
- Regulators felt compelled to cover entire exposure
- Bank paid insurance premiums based on only 4% of total coverage
- Taxpayers picked up other 96%

> "Although Continental Illinois had over $30 billion in deposits, 90 percent were uninsured foreign deposits or large certificates substantially exceeding the $100,000 insurance limit."

- Off-book liabilities swelled Continental's real size to $69 billion
- In massive liability structure: only $3 billion within insured limit scattered among 850,000 deposit accounts

> "So it was in our power and entirely legal simply to pay off the insured depositors, let everything else collapse, and stand back to watch the carnage."

- **Never seriously considered by any players**
- Only two questions: (1) how to come to Continental's rescue covering total liabilities; (2) how to politically justify fleecing taxpayer

#### Political Justification Through Scale
- Rules of game require scam described as heroic effort to protect public
- Continental's sheer size made ploy relatively easy
- So many depositors, billions at risk, other banks interlocked — could claim economic fabric of entire nation (world itself) at stake

> "An early morning meeting was scheduled for Tuesday, May 15, at the Fed. .. We talked over the alternatives. They were few —none really.... [Treasury Secretary] Regan and [Fed Chairman] Volcker raised the familiar concern about a national banking collapse, that is, a chain reaction if Continental should fail. Volcker was worried about an international crisis. We all were acutely aware that never before had a bank even remotely approaching Continental's size closed. No one knew what might happen in the nation and in the world. It was no time to find out just for the purpose of intellectual curiosity."

### The Final Bailout Package

#### The Predictable Pattern
- Preliminary lip service to necessity of allowing banks to work out own problem
- Plan to have banks and government share burden
- Finally collapse into mere public-relations illusion
- End: almost entire cost assumed by government, passed to taxpayer

#### The Make-Believe Rescue
- May 15 meeting: **Treasury Secretary Regan** spoke eloquently about free market value, necessity of banks mounting own rescue plan (at least for part of money)
- Summit meeting arranged next morning among seven largest banks: **Morgan Guaranty**, **Chase Manhattan**, **Citibank**, **Bank of America**, **Chemical Bank**, **Bankers Trust**, **Manufacturers Hanover**
- Meeting perfunctory at best; bankers knew Reagan Administration would not risk political embarrassment of major bank failure at re-election time
- Some tokenism called for to preserve Administration's conservative image
- With urging from Fed and Treasury: consortium agreed to put up $500 million — average only $71 million each, far short of actual need

> "They pretended to mount a rescue." — Chernow

#### The Charade Unfolds
- By 7:30 AM: little progress made; situation would be totally out of control in few hours
- Continental would expose itself to new business day; stock market would open at 10 o'clock
- FDIC directors held halfway conversation, agreed to go ahead without banks
- Told Conover (third FDIC director) the plan; he concurred
- Later: got word from **Bernie McKeon** (regional director in New York) that bankers had agreed to be at risk
- **Actually risk was remote** since announcement had promised 100% insurance

#### The Takeover
- Final bailout package was whopper
- Government took over Continental Illinois, assumed all losses
- FDIC took $4.5 billion in bad loans, paid Continental $3.5 billion for them
- Difference made up by infusion of $1 billion fresh capital (stock purchase)
- Bank now had federal government as stockholder controlling 80% of shares; bad loans dumped onto taxpayer

<!-- pp. 81-100 -->

### Lender of Last Resort

- Fed's role as **"lender of last resort"** was crucial to Continental Illinois bailout — FDIC couldn't have covered losses without draining funds needed for thousands of other banks
- The System was created at Jekyll Island specifically to manufacture whatever money necessary to cover cartel losses
- Money created by Fed and pumped into banks via "credit" and "liquidity" guarantees ultimately extracted from taxpayers through **inflation** — the **hidden tax**

> "The operation is the most basic function of the Federal Reserve. It was why it was founded." — Fed Chairman **Paul Volcker**, 1986

- By 1984, Fed's "unlimited liquidity support" for Continental reached $8 billion
- By early 1986, figure climbed to $9.24 billion and still rising

### Small Banks Be Damned

- Large banks receive free ride on FDIC coverage at expense of small banks
- **Continental Illinois** example (1983): paid only $6.5 million in premiums to protect $3 billion in insured deposits, but actual liability (including institutional and overseas deposits) was **10 times that figure** — FDIC guaranteed payment on whole amount
- Same week FDIC/Fed provided billions for Continental, they closed tiny **Bledsoe County Bank** (Pikeville, TN) and **Planters Trust and Savings Bank** (Opelousas, LA)
- During first half of that year, **43 smaller banks failed** without FDIC bailout — in most cases only uninsured deposits at risk

> "Small banks pay proportionately far more for their insurance and have far less chance of a Continental-style bailout." — **Irvine Sprague**, FDIC director

- Impact: sends message that small banks will be allowed to fold, large banks safe regardless of management
- NY investment analyst: Continental Illinois, even though just failed, was "obviously the safest bank in the country to have your money in"
- Since 1984, hundreds of small banks forced out while average size of surviving banks (with government protection) more than doubled
- Big bank advantage was one of the **objectives of the Jekyll Island plan**

### Reagan and the Shift to Statism

- Most depressing aspect: lack of public indignation over using taxes/inflation to protect banking industry
- Smaller banks complained about unfair advantage to larger banks, but NOT on basis government shouldn't have let giant fall
- They wanted government to protect them in same paternalistic fashion
- Even **Ronald Reagan** praised the Continental bailout: "It was a thing that we should do and we did it. It was in the best interest of all concerned"

**William Greider** (former writer for Washington Post and Rolling Stone) observes:

> "The nationalization of Continental was, in fact, a quintessential act of modern liberalism—the state intervening in behalf of private interests and a broad public purpose."

- In supposedly conservative era, federal authorities set aside harsh verdict of market competition while expanding involvement in private economy
- Conservative scholars/pundits had objected to federal intervention in private economy, particularly emergency assistance for failing companies — now they hardly seemed to notice
- Perhaps would have been more vocal if deed done by someone other than conservative champion Reagan

### BankOklahoma (1988)

- Four years after Continental, same pattern used to rescue **BankOklahoma** (holding company)
- FDIC pumped $130 million into main banking unit, took warrants for 55% ownership
- Pattern established: accepting stock in failing bank in return for bailing it out = ingenious way to **nationalize banks without calling it that**
- Issuing stock sounds like private-sector business transaction
- Public didn't notice Uncle Sam was going into banking

### Second Reason to Abolish the Federal Reserve

Far from being protector of public, Fed is **cartel operating against public interest**.

### Summary: The Big Bailouts

**Penn Central Railroad (1970)**
- Banks had taken over board, driven it deeper into debt with bigger loans to cover losses
- Directors concealed reality from stockholders, made additional loans so company could pay dividends (false front)
- Directors/banks unloaded stock at unrealistically high prices
- When truth became public, stockholders left holding empty bag
- Bailout: Fed engineered government subsidies to other banks for additional loans
- Congress granted $125 million in loan guarantees so banks wouldn't be at risk
- Railroad eventually failed anyway, but bank loans covered
- Penn Central nationalized into **AMTRAK**, continues operating at loss

**Lockheed (1970)**
- Congress guaranteed $250 million in new loans, putting Lockheed 60% deeper into debt
- To ensure profitability, government granted lucrative defense contracts at non-competitive bids
- Banks paid back

**New York City (1975)**
- Borrowed heavily to maintain extravagant bureaucracy and miniature welfare state
- Congress authorized additional direct loans up to $2.3 billion, more than doubling current debt
- Banks continued receiving interest

**Chrysler (1978)**
- Congress guaranteed up to $1.5 billion in new loans
- Banks reduced part of loans, exchanged another portion for preferred stock
- News pushed up market value of stock, largely offset loan write-off
- Banks' previously uncollectable debt converted into **government-backed, interest-bearing asset**

**Commonwealth Bank of Detroit (1972)**
- $1.5 billion in assets, became insolvent
- Borrowed heavily from Chase Manhattan to invest in high-risk ventures
- FDIC pumped in $60 million loan plus federal guarantees of repayment
- Sold to Arab consortium
- Chase took minor write down but converted most potential loss into government-backed assets

**First Pennsylvania Bank of Philadelphia (1979)**
- Assets in excess of $9 billion, nine times size of Commonwealth
- Aggressive player in '80s
- FDIC gave $325 million loan (interest-free first year, half market rate thereafter)
- Fed offered money to other banks at subsidized rate specifically for relending to First Penn
- Result: $175 million in immediate loans plus $1 billion line of credit

**Continental Illinois (1982)**
- Nation's seventh largest bank, $42 billion in assets
- Previous year profits soared from high-risk business ventures and foreign government loans
- Although had darling status of market analysts, quickly unraveled when cash flow turned negative and overseas banks began withdrawing deposits
- World's first **electronic bank run**
- Fed Chairman Volcker told FDIC unthinkable to allow world economy ruined by bank failure of this magnitude
- FDIC assumed $4.5 billion in bad loans, took 80% ownership in form of stock
- Bank nationalized but no one called it that
- **United States government now in banking business**

All bailout money made possible by **Federal Reserve System acting as "lender of last resort"** — one of purposes for which it was created. Money created out of nothing, resulting in confiscation of nation's wealth through hidden tax called **inflation**.

## Chapter Four: Home, Sweet Loan

History of increasing government intervention in housing industry; stifling of free-market forces in residential real estate; the redlining crisis in S&L industry; bailout with money from taxpayers.

Banking cartel damage made possible because money can be created out of nothing. Also destroys purchasing power through **hidden tax called inflation**. Mechanism is hidden and subtle.

### Socialism Takes Root in America

- Concept took root largely as result of **Great Depression of 1930s**
- American politicians impressed at how radical Marxists attracted popular support by blaming capitalist system and promising socialist Utopia
- Political figures began mimicking soap-box orators, voters put them into office
- While extreme/violent aspects of Communism rejected, more genteel theories of socialism became popular among educated elite
- Concept became widely accepted at all levels — "downtrodden masses" and educated elite — that government should take care of citizens and protect them in economic affairs

**Herbert Hoover** — and willing Congress — created **Federal Home Loan Bank Board** to protect depositors after 1900+ S&Ls went belly-up in Great Depression. Began issuing charters to institutions submitting to regulations. Public led to believe government regulators more wise, prudent, honest than private managers. Federal charter became government seal of approval.

**FDR** succeeded Hoover, became epitome of new breed. Earlier in political career, paragon of free enterprise and individualism. Spoke out against big government and for free market. But mid-life reset his sail to catch shifting political wind. Went down in history as **pioneer of socialism in America**.

FDR established **Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (FDIC)** and **Federal Saving and Loan Insurance Corporation (FSLIC)**. From that point forward, neither public nor managers of thrifts needed to worry about losses — everything reimbursed by government.

### A House on Every Lot

- Loans on private homes subsidized through **Federal Housing Authority (FHA)** — allowed S&Ls to make loans at rates lower than possible without subsidy
- Goal: make easier for everyone to realize dream of owning home
- While Marxists promising chicken in every pot, New Dealers winning elections pushing house on every lot
- Initially helped people who might not have been able to purchase or would have waited longer for higher down payment
- But FHA-induced easy credit pushed up house prices for middle class, quickly offsetting any real advantage
- Voters not perceptive enough to understand canceling effect, continued voting for politicians promising to expand system

**Federal Reserve Board** required banks to offer interest rates lower than S&Ls. Result: funds moved from banks into S&Ls, became abundantly available for home loans. Deliberate national policy to favor home industry at expense of other industries competing for same investment dollars. May not have been good for economy as whole, but good politics.

### Abandonment of the Free Market

- These measures effectively **removed real estate loans from free market**, placed them into political arena where they've remained ever since
- Damage to public delayed long time in coming, but when it came, would be cataclysmic
- Reality: government disruption of free market at heart of present and future crisis
- Savings institutions controlled by government at every step: protection against losses, rigid guidelines for capitalization levels, number of branches, territories covered, management policies, services rendered, interest rates charged
- Additional compliance cost estimated by **American Bankers Association** at about **$11 billion per year** — whopping 60% of all profits
- Healthy institutions must spend over $1 billion/year for extra premiums into insurance fund to make up for failures of unhealthy component — penalty for success
- When some healthy institutions tried converting to banks to escape penalty, regulators said no — cash flow needed to support bailout fund

### Insurance for the Common Man?

- Average private savings deposit about $6,000
- Under Carter administration, FDIC insurance level raised from $40,000 to $100,000 per account
- Those with more merely opened several accounts — in reality, sky was limit
- Clearly had nothing to do with protecting common man
- Purpose: prepare way for brokerage houses to reinvest huge blocks of capital at high interest rates virtually without risk — insured by federal government

**Interest Rate Squeeze (1979-1980)**
- Fed policy pushed up interest rates
- S&Ls had to keep pace to attract deposits
- By December 1980, paying 15.8% interest on money-market certificates
- Average rate charging for new mortgages only 12.9%
- Many old loans still crunching at 7% or 8%
- Some in default (really paying 0%)
- Thrifts operating deep in red, had to make up difference somewhere

**Moral Hazard**
- Weakest S&Ls paid highest interest rates to attract depositors, obtained large blocks of brokered funds
- Brokers no longer cared how weak operation was — funds fully insured, only cared about interest rate
- S&L managers reasoned they had to make funds work miracles for short period they had them — only chance to dig out
- Government's insurance program removed any chance of loss to depositors
- Many plunged into **high-profit, high-risk real-estate developments**

1979 = first year since Great Depression that total net worth of federally insured S&Ls became negative, despite expansion almost everywhere else in economy. Public began to worry.

### Full Faith and Credit

- 1982: Congress joint resolution declaring **"full faith & credit of United States government"** stood behind FSLIC
- Reassuring phrase, but people had gnawing feeling we'd pay for it ourselves — and they were right

> "Behind the troubled banks and the increasingly troubled insurance agencies stands 'the full faith and credit' of the Government—in effect, a promise, sure to be honored by Congress, that all citizens will chip in through taxes or through inflation to make ail depositors whole." — **Consumer Reports**

**Home State Savings Bank of Cincinnati (1985)**
- Collapsed due to potential $150 million loss in Florida securities firm
- Triggered run not only on 33 Home State branches but many other S&Ls
- News impacted international markets — overseas speculators dumped paper dollars for other currencies, some rushed to buy gold
- Within days, depositors demanding money caused $60 million to flow out of Ohio's $130 million "insurance" fund
- Fund terribly inadequate — if run continued, would have been obliterated next day
- Time for political fix

**Ohio Governor Richard Celeste** declared "bank holiday" March 15, closed all 71 state-insured thrifts. Assured public nothing to worry about — merely "cooling-off period ... until we can convincingly demonstrate soundness of our system." Flew to Washington, met with **Paul Volcker** (Fed chairman) and **Edwin Gray** (Federal Home Loan Bank Board chairman) to request federal assistance. They assured him it was available.

Few days later, depositors authorized to withdraw up to $750 from accounts. March 21, **President Reagan** calmed world money markets with assurances crisis was over, problem "limited to Ohio."

**Nebraska insurance fund failure**: Commonwealth Savings Company of Lincoln had over $60 million in deposits, but insurance fund had less than $2 million to cover not just Commonwealth but whole system. Depositors lucky to get 65 cents on dollar, expected to take up to 10 years.

### An Invitation to Fraud

Early Reagan administration changed regulations:
- S&Ls no longer restricted to issuance of home mortgages (sole reason for creation in first place)
- No longer required to obtain down payment on loans
- Could finance **100% of deal — or even more**
- Office buildings and shopping centers sprang up everywhere regardless of need
- Developers, builders, managers, appraisers made millions
- Field became overbuilt, riddled with fraud
- Billions disappeared into defunct projects
- At least **22 failed S&Ls had evidence of Mafia and CIA involvement**

**Garn-St. Germain Act** allowed thrifts to lend amount equal to **appraised value** rather than market value. Wasn't long before appraisers receiving handsome fees for unrealistic appraisals. Amount by which appraisal exceeded market value defined as **"appraised equity"**, counted same as capital. Since S&Ls required to have $1 in capital for every $33 in deposits, an appraisal exceeding market by $1 million could pyramid $33 million in deposits from Wall Street brokerage houses. Anticipated profits from funds was one way S&Ls supposed to recoup losses without government coughing up money — which it didn't have.

Government essentially saying: "We can't make good on our protection scheme, so go get the money yourself by putting the investors at risk. Not only will we back you up if you fail, we'll show you exactly how to do it."

### The Fallout Begins

Despite accounting gimmicks to make walking-dead S&Ls look healthy, by 1984 fallout began. FSLIC closed one institution that year, arranged merger of 26 others which were insolvent. To persuade healthy firms to absorb insolvent ones, government provided cash settlements to compensate for liabilities. By 1984, subsidized mergers costing FDIC over $1 billion per year — just the small beginning.

**1980-1986: 664 insured S&Ls failed**. Government regulators promised to protect public in event of losses, but losses already far beyond what they could handle. Couldn't afford to close down all insolvent thrifts — didn't have enough money to cover pay out. By March 1986, FSLIC had only **3 cents for every dollar of deposits**. By end of year, figure dropped to **two-tenths of a penny** for each dollar "insured." Had to keep thrifts in business, which meant inventing even more accounting gimmicks to conceal reality.

Postponement made matters worse. Keeping S&Ls in business costing FSLIC $6 million per day. By 1988, thrift industry as whole losing $9.8 million per day, unprofitable ones (corpses propped up by FSLIC) losing $35.6 million per day. Still, game continued.

By 1989, FSLIC no longer had even two-tenths of penny for each dollar insured. Reserves vanished altogether. Like thrifts it supposedly protected, FSLIC itself insolvent, looking for loans. Tried offering bond issues, fell far short of needs. Congress discussed problem but failed to provide new funding. Collapse of Lincoln Savings brought crisis to head. **No money, period.**

### The Fed Usurps the Role of Congress

February 1989: agreement reached between **Alan Greenspan** (Fed Chairman) and **M. Danny Wall** (Federal Home Loan Bank Board Chairman) to have **$70 million of bailout funding for Lincoln Savings come directly from Federal Reserve**.

Major break in precedent. Historically, Fed served to create money only for government or banks. If people's will to bail out savings institution, up to Congress to approve funding. If Congress doesn't have money or can't borrow from public, then Fed can create it (out of nothing, of course) and give to government. But in this instance, **Fed usurping role of Congress**, making political decisions entirely on its own. No basis in Federal Reserve Act for this action. Congress remained silent, apparently out of collective guilt for own paralysis.

August 1989: Congress passed **Financial Institutions Reform and Recovery Act (FIRREA)**, allocated minimum $66 billion for following 10 years, $300 billion over 30 years. Of this, $225 billion from taxes or inflation, $75 billion from healthy S&Ls. **Biggest bailout ever**, bigger than combined cost for Lockheed, Chrysler, Penn Central, and New York City.

FSLIC eliminated (hopelessly insolvent), replaced by **Savings Association Insurance Fund**. Also created **Banking Insurance Fund** for commercial banks, both administered by FDIC.

Four entirely new layers of bureaucracy added: **Resolution Trust Oversight Board**, **Resolution Funding Corporation**, **Office of Thrift Supervision**, **Oversight Board for Home Loan Banks**. Purpose vague but probably to ensure S&Ls continue serving political directive of subsidizing home industry.

**President Bush**: "This legislation will safeguard and stabilize America's financial system and put in place permanent reforms so these problems will never happen again. Moreover, it says to tens of millions of savings-and-loan depositors, 'You will not be the victim of others' mistakes."

### The Estimates Are Slightly Wrong

By middle of following year, clear $66 billion greatly inadequate. Treasury spokesmen now quoting $130 billion, about twice original estimate.

How much is $130 billion? In 1990:
- 30% more than salaries of all schoolteachers in America
- More than combined profits of all Fortune-500 industrial companies
- Would send 1.6 million students through best four-year colleges, including room and board
- Figure didn't include cost of liquidating huge backlog of thrifts already seized nor interest on borrowed funds

Within days, Treasury revised figure upward from $130 billion to **$150 billion**. **Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady**: "No one should assume that the estimates won't change. They will."

Indeed, estimates continued changing each passing week. Government sold or merged 223 thrifts during 1988, given grossly inadequate cost estimates. Financiers like **Ronald Perelman** and **Temple-Inland, Inc.** picked up many at fantastic bargains, especially considering given cash subsidies and tax advantages to sweeten deal. **Danny Wall** announced these deals "took care" of worst thrift problems, said cost was $39 billion. **Wall Street Journal** reported actual cost would be **$90 billion to $95 billion**, including tax benefits and huge amount of interest on government debt to help finance.

Real flaw: none of deals ended or limited government's exposure to mismanagement, hidden losses on real estate, or vicissitudes of future markets. Some appeared to be sham transactions — failing thrifts sold to failing thrifts.

**Danny Wall** defended strategy: "We didn't have the money to liquidate."

When Congress passed HRREA previous year to "safeguard and stabilize America's financial system," staggering sum of $300 billion authorized from taxes/inflation over following 30 years. Now Fed Chairman **Alan Greenspan** saying true long-term cost would be **$500 billion** — amount greater than default of loans to all Third-World countries combined. Figure still too low. Non-biased private study by **Veribank, Inc.** showed when all hidden costs included, bill to American people would be about **$532 billion**. Problems President Bush promised would "never happen again" were happening again.

### Bookkeeping Sleight of Hand

Long before, real estate market begun to contract, many mortgages exceeded actual price property could be sold for. Furthermore, market interest rates risen far above rates locked into most S&L loans, decreasing value of mortgages. True value of $50,000 mortgage paying 7% interest only half of $50,000 mortgage earning 14%. Protectors of public devised scheme whereby S&Ls allowed to **value assets according to original loan value rather than true market value**. Helped, but much more still needed.

Next: create bookkeeping assets out of thin air. Accomplished by authorizing S&Ls to place monetary value on **community "good will"**! With mere stroke of pen, referees created $2.5 billion in such assets, players continued game.

Then FSLIC began issuing **"certificates of net worth"** — basically promises to bail out ailing S&Ls should they need it. Government already promised but by printing on pieces of paper and calling them "certificates of net worth," S&Ls allowed to count them as assets on books. Such promises are assets but since thrifts would be obligated to pay back any money received in bailout, those pay-back obligations should also have been on books as liabilities. Net position: no change. Only way they could count certificates as assets without adding offsetting liabilities would be for bailout promises to be outright gifts with no obligation to ever repay. May be eventual result, but not way plan set up. In any event, thrifts told could count these pieces of paper as capital, same as if owners put up their own cash. Game continued.

Moment of truth arrives when S&Ls have to liquidate holdings (sale of mortgages or foreclosed homes to other S&Ls, commercial banks, private parties). That's when inflated bookkeeping value converted into true market value, difference entered into ledger as loss. But not in never-never land of socialism where government is great protector. **Dennis Turner** explains:

**FSUC** permits S&L which sold mortgage to take loss over **40-year period**. Most companies selling asset at loss must take loss immediately — only S&Ls can engage in this patent fraud. Two failing S&Ls could conceivably sell their lowest-yielding mortgages to one another, both would raise their net worth! This dishonest accounting approved by highest regulatory authorities.

> "Today, scores of savings-and-loan associations, kept alive mainly by accounting gimmicks, continue to post big losses.... Only a fraction of the industry's aggregate net worth comprises hard assets such as mortgage notes. Intangible assets, which include bookkeeping entries such as good will, make up nearly all of the industry's estimated net Worth of 37.6 billion dollars." — **U.S. News & World Report**

### Accounting Gimmicks Are Not Fraud

Well-managed institution would never assume these kinds of risks or resort to fraudulent accounting if wanted to stay in business for long haul. But with Washington setting guidelines and standing by to make up losses, manager would be fired if didn't take advantage of opportunity. After all, Congress specifically said OK when passed laws. These were loopholes deliberately put there to be used. **Dr. Edward Kane** explains:

> "Deception itself doesn't constitute illegal fraud when it's authorized by an accounting system such as the Generally Accepted Accounting Principles (GAAP) system which allows institutions to forego recording assets at their true worth, maintaining them instead at their inflated value. The regulatory accounting principles system in 1982 added even new options to overstate capital.... Intense speculation, such as we observed in these firms, is not necessarily bad management at all. In most of these cases, it was clever management. There were clever gambles that exploited, not depositors or savers, but taxpayers."

Press greatly exaggerated role of illegal fraud with much time excoriating likes of **Donald Dixon** at Vernon S&L and **Charles Keating** at Lincoln Savings. True, these flops cost taxpayer well over $3 billion, but all illegal fraud put together amounts to only about one-half of one per cent of total losses. Focusing on that minuscule component serves only to distract from fact that **real problem is government regulation itself**.

### Junk Bonds Are Not Junk

Another part of distraction: making it appear thrifts got into trouble because heavily invested in "junk bonds."

Wait a minute! What are junk bonds? May come as surprise, but those held by S&Ls were anything but junk. In fact, in terms of risk-return ratios, most were **superior-grade investments** to bonds from Fortune-500 companies.

So-called junk bonds merely those offered by smaller companies not large enough to be counted among nation's giants. Large reinvestors (managers of mutual funds and retirement funds) prefer to stay with well-known names like General Motors and IBM. They need to invest truly huge blocks of money every day, smaller companies just don't have enough to offer to satisfy needs. Consequently, many stocks and bonds from smaller companies not traded in New York Stock Exchange — traded in smaller exchanges or directly between brokers ("over the counter"). Because they don't have advantage of being traded in larger
<!-- pp. 101-120 -->

## Chapter 4: Home Sweet Loan (continued)

### High-Yield Bonds: Capital Without Inflation

- **Junk bonds** emerged as alternative financing for small companies excluded from traditional markets
- Derided as "not investment grade" but performed well — backbone of new industry in 1980s
- While Fortune-500 shrank 3.6M jobs, small-company sector created 18M new jobs
- 1981-1991 returns: Treasury bills 10.4%, Dow Jones 12.9%, junk bonds 14.1%
- Attracted $180B+ from investors including S&Ls
- **Michael Milken** at **Drexel Burnham Lambert** orchestrated this new market

> "Here was $180 billion that no longer was being channeled through Wall Street. Here was $180 billion that was coming from people's savings instead of being created out of nothing by the banks. In other words, here was growth built upon real investment, not inflation."

### Attack on High-Yield Market

**Glenn Yago** (Economic Research Bureau, SUNY Stony Brook) explains the backlash:

> "It was not until high yield securities were applied to restructuring through deconglomeration and takeovers that hostilities against the junk bond market broke out.... The high yield market grew at the expense of bank debt, and high yield companies grew at the expense of the hegemony of many established firms."

- First tactic: label them "junk" — word itself frightened investors away
- Second tactic: **Financial Institutions Reform and Recovery Act (1989)** forced S&Ls to liquidate junk bond holdings
- Only 5% of S&Ls held these bonds (1.2% of total assets)
- Bonds were performing well and generating needed revenue
- Forced liquidation crashed prices, weakened thrifts further

**Jane Ingraham**: "Overnight, profitable S&Ls were turned into government-owned basket cases in the hands of the **Resolution Trust Corporation (RTC)**."

- RTC flooded market with $1.6B of holdings at bottom in 1990
- Government crashed the market, not Milken
- Milken jailed, Drexel settled $1.3B in lawsuits despite government being the cause
- Bonds later recovered — S&Ls would be healthier if allowed to keep them

### Wall Street Recaptures the Market

- With California upstarts eliminated, establishment bought bonds at bargain prices
- **Salomon Brothers** (former Drexel critic) became leading trader in the market Drexel created

### Real Problem Is Government Regulation

**Wall Street Journal** (March 10, 1992):

> "If you're going to wreck a business the size of the U.S. Thrift industry, you need a lot more power than Michael Milken ever had. You need the power of national political authority, the kind of power possessed only by regulators and Congress."

- By book publication, half of 1980s S&Ls had failed or merged
- Two groups remain: (1) RTC-owned zombies hemorrhaging $6B/year in losses, (2) privately-owned recovering institutions
- President Clinton requested $45B more for bailout — "but no promises"

### Congress Is Paralyzed, With Good Reason

Two reasons Congress won't investigate:

1. **Campaign contributions** — S&Ls, banks, federally regulated institutions fund legislators who write regulatory laws
2. **Congress itself is the primary cause** — following socialist path, suspended natural economic laws, created uncontrollable Frankenstein monster

**Hans Sennholz**: "The real cause of the disaster is the very financial structure that was fashioned by legislators and guided by regulators; they together created a cartel that, like all other monopolistic concoctions, is playing mischief with its victims."

### A Cartel Within a Cartel

- S&L industry is **cartel within a cartel**
- Could not function without Congress funding unlimited bailout money
- Congress cannot do that without the **Federal Reserve System** as "lender of last resort"
- Arrangement lets Congress vote for any scheme regardless of cost
- Raising money through taxes would get politicians thrown out
- "Borrowing" from Fed via inflation allows hidden collection — no voter complaints

> "The thrifts have become the illegitimate half-breed children of the Creature."

### Citizens Must Learn Economics

- Must stop reaching for political carrots (subsidized housing, etc.)
- 60 years of housing subsidies/regulation drove prices beyond reach
- Laws of supply/demand plus **hidden inflation tax** wiped out down payments
- Without such costs, common people would have more purchasing power and affordable homes

