## Chapter Eleven: THE ROTHSCHILD FORMULA (pp. 252)

### Chapter Summary
- Rise of **House of Rothschild** in Europe
- Tradition among financiers of **profiting from both sides of armed conflict**
- Formula by which **war is converted into debt** and **debt converted back into war**

### The Profits of War (pp. 253)

- Focus: profits of war and tendency of profit-reapers to **manipulate governments into military conflicts** for **private gain**, not national/patriotic reasons
- Pre-capitalist war financing mechanism more complex than simple lending + interest collection
- Real payoff: **political favoritism in the market place**
- **Richard Lewinsohn** (1937, French historian):

> "Although often called bankers, those who financed wars in the pre-capitalist period... were not bankers in the modern sense of the word. Unlike modern bankers who operate with money deposited with them by their clients [or, in more recent times, created out of nothing by a central bank—E.G.], they generally worked with the fortune which they themselves had amassed or inherited"

> "They lent at a high rate of interest. Thus those who risked the financing of a war were for the most part already very rich, and this was the case down to the seventeenth century."

- When they agreed to finance a war, rich lenders did not always attach great importance to interest rate
- Often showed greatest complaisance to their august clients
- In return they secured for themselves **privileges** which could be turned into **industrial or commercial profit**: mining concessions, monopolies of sale or importation, etc.
- Sometimes even given the **right to appropriate certain taxes** as guarantee of their loans
- Though the loan itself carried very real risk and often did not bring in much interest, **indirect profits were very considerable**, and lenders' leniency well rewarded

### The Rothschild Dynasty (pp. 254-255)

- No discussion of banking as mechanism for financing wars would be complete without turning to **name Rothschild**
- **Mayer Amschel Rothschild** quoted: **"Let me issue and control a nation's money and I care not who writes the laws"**
- Biographer **Frederic Morton** concluded Rothschild dynasty had: **"conquered the world more thoroughly, more cunningly, and much more lastingly than all the Ceasars before or all the Hitlers after them"**

#### Mayer Amschel Bauer/Rothschild
- Dynasty begun in Frankfurt, Germany, middle of 18th century by **Mayer Amschel Bauer**, son of goldsmith
- Mayer became clerk in **Oppenheimer Bank** in Hanover, eventually promoted to junior partner
- After father's death, returned to Frankfurt to continue family business
- Over door hung **red shield with eagle** as sign to identify establishment
- German words for red shield: **roth schild** — changed name from Bauer to **Rothschild**
- Added **five gold arrows** held in eagle's talons to represent his **five sons**

#### The Five Sons
- Rothschild fortune began when Mayer adopted practice of **fractional-reserve banking**
- Not alone in this, but **House of Rothschild greatly surpassed the competition**
- Due to his **sharp business acumen** and also his **five most unusual sons**
- All became **financial power centers of their own**
- As they matured and learned magic of converting debt into money, moved beyond confines of Frankfurt
- Established additional operations in **financial centers** not only of Europe, but of much of civilized world

#### Rothschild Operations (First Half of 19th Century)
- Brothers conducted important transactions on behalf of governments of:
  - England, France, Prussia, Austria, Belgium, Spain, Naples, Portugal, Brazil, various German states, and other smaller countries
- Were **personal bankers of many of the crowned heads of Europe**
- Made large investments through agents in markets as distant as:
  - United States, India, Cuba, and Australia
- Were **financiers to Cecil Rhodes**, making it possible for him to establish monopoly over diamond fields of South Africa
- Still connected with **de Beers**

#### Biographer Derek Wilson on Rothschild Power

> "Those who lampooned or vilified the Rothschilds for their 'sinister' influence had a considerable amount of justification for their anger and anxiety. The banking community had always constituted a 'fifth estate' whose members were able, by their control of royal purse strings, to affect important events. But the house of Rothschild was immensely more powerful than any financial empire that had ever preceded it. It commanded vast wealth. It was international. It was independent. Royal governments were nervous of it because they could not control it. Popular movements hated it because it was not answerable to the people. Constitutionalists resented it because its influence was exercised behind the scenes —secretly."

#### Secrecy & Clandestinity
- **Secrecy essential for success of a cabal**
- Rothschilds perfected the art
- By remaining **behind the scenes**, able to avoid brunt of public anger directed instead at political figures which they largely controlled
- Technique practiced by **financial manipulators ever since**
- Fully utilized by those who operate the Federal Reserve System today

#### Gandestinity Feature (Wilson)

> "Gandestinity was and remained a feature of Rothschild political activity. Seldom were they to be seen engaged in open public debate on important issues. Never did they seek government office. Even when, in later years, some of them entered parliament, they did not feature prominently in the assembly chambers of London, Paris or Berlin. Yet all the while they were helping to shape the major events of the day: by granting or withholding funds; by providing statesmen with an official diplomatic service; by influencing appointments to high office; and by an almost daily intercourse with the great decision makers."

### A Fortune in Smuggling (pp. 256)

- Continual war in Europe created excellent opportunities for profit from **smuggling scarce consumer goods past military blockades**
- Since Rothschilds often financed both sides in conflict and were known to have great political influence, mere sight of **red shield on leather pouch, carriage, or ship's flag** was sufficient to insure messenger or cargo could pass through check points in either direction
- This immunity allowed them to deal in thriving black market for:
  - cotton goods, yarn, tobacco, coffee, sugar, and indigo
- Moved freely through borders of Germany, Scandinavia, Holland, Spain, England, and France
- **Government protection** was one of those **indirect benefits** that generated **commercial profits far in excess of interest received** on underlying government loans

#### Two Centuries of Profiting from Wars & Economic Collapses
- Generally true that **one man's loss is another man's gain**
- Even friendliest of biographers admit that for more than two centuries, **House of Rothschild profited handsomely from wars and economic collapses**, the very occasions on which others sustained the greatest losses

### Napoleon vs The Bankers (pp. 256-259)

- One example surely must be worth a dozen explanations
- No better example than **economic war waged by financiers of 19th-century Europe against Napoleon Bonaparte**
- **Easily forgotten fact of history**: Napoleon had **restored law and order** to chaotic, post-revolutionary France
- Had turned his attention not to war, but to **establishing peace and improving economic conditions at home**
- Particularly anxious to get his country and people **out of debt and out of control of bankers**
- **R. McNair Wilson**, in *Monarchy or Money Pozver*:

> "It was ordained by him that money should not be exported from France on any pretext whatever except with the consent of the Government, and that in no circumstance should loans be employed to meet current expenditure whether civil or military.... 'One has only to consider,' Napoleon remarked, 'what loans can lead to in order to realize their danger. Therefore, I would never have anything to do with them and have always striven against them'..."

> "The object was to withhold from finance the power to embarrass the Government as it had embarrassed the Government of Louis XVI. When a Government, Bonaparte declared, is dependent for money upon bankers, they and not the leaders of that Government control the situation, since 'the hand that gives is above the hand that takes'..."

> "'Money,' he declared, 'has no motherland; financiers are without patriotism and without decency: their sole object is gain.'"

#### Napoleon's Independent Bank of France
- One of Napoleon's first blows against bankers: establish **independent Bank of France** with himself as president
- Even this bank was not trusted — **government funds were never placed into it**
- It was his **refusal to borrow** that caused most concern among financiers
- To them this was mixture of both bad and good news:
  - **Bad**: denied benefit of royalty payments on fractional money
  - **Good**: was that without resorting to debt, they were confident **Napoleon could not militarily defend himself**
- Thus, he could easily be toppled and replaced by **Louis XVI of old monarchic dynasty** who was receptive to banker influence

#### Wilson Continues:

> "They had good hope of compassing his downfall. None believed that he could finance war on a great scale now that the resource of paper money had been denied him by the destruction of the Assignat. Where would he obtain the indispensable gold and silver to feed and equip a great army? Pitt [the Prime Minister of England] counted already on a coalition of England, Austria, Prussia, Russia, Spain,"

- **The Assignat** was pure fiat money which rapidly became totally worthless in commerce and all but destroyed French economy

> "Sweden, and numerous small states. Some 600,000 men would be put into the field. All the resources of England's wealth —that is to say, of the world's wealth —would be placed at the disposal of this overwhelming force. Could the Corsican muster 200,000? Could he arm them? Could he feed them? If the lead bullets did not destroy him, the gold bullets would soon make an end. He would be forced, like his neighbors, to come, hat in hand, for loans and, like them, to accept the banker's terms...."

> "He could not put his hands on £2,000,000, so empty was the Treasury and so depleted the nation's stock of metallic money. London waited with interest to see how the puzzle would be solved."

#### Napoleon's Louisiana Purchase Solution
- Napoleon solved puzzle quite simply by **selling off some real estate**
- Those crazy Americans gave him **£3,000,000 for a vast swamp called Louisiana**

### A Plan to Destroy the United States (pp. 259-260)

- Napoleon did not want war, but he knew **Europe's financial rulers would not settle for peace**
- Unless they were forced into it by defeat of their puppet regimes
- Unless, somehow, it would be to their **monetary advantage**
- It was in pursuit of latter tactic that he threatened to take **direct possession of Holland**, then ruled by his brother, King Louis
- Napoleon knew Dutch were heavily in debt to English bankers
- If Holland were to be annexed by France, **this debt would never be repaid**
- So Napoleon made proposal to England's bankers: if they would **convince English government to accept peace with France**, he would agree to **leave Holland alone**

#### The Negotiations
- Negotiations handled by banker **Pierre-Cesar Labouchere** (sent by Dutch) and English banker **Sir Francis Baring** (Labouchere's father-in-law)
- Although attractive proposal to bankers, at least on short-term basis, was still **against their nature** to forego immense profits of war and mercantilism
- They revised the proposal to include **plan whereby both England and France would combine forces to destroy newly independent United States**
- Bring at least half of it — the industrial half — back under domination of England
- Incredible plan, conceived by French banker **Ouvard**, called for:
  - **Military invasion and conquest**
  - Followed by **division of the spoils**
- England would receive **northern states, united with Canada**
- Southern states would fall to France
- Napoleon to be tempted by offering him awesome title of **"King of America"**

#### Labouchere's Letter to Baring (March 21)
- **McNair Wilson** tells us:

> "Labouchere wrote to Baring on March 21, and enclosed a note for [British Foreign Secretary] Wellesley dictated by Ouvrard which ran:"

> "'From a conqueror he (Napoleon) is becoming a preserver: the first result of his marriage with Marie Louise will be that he will make an offer of peace to England. It is to this nation's (i.e., England's) interest to make peace, for it has the command of the sea; on the contrary, it is really in the interest of France to continue war, which allows her to expand indefinitely and make a fresh fleet, which cannot be done once peace is established. Why does not the English Cabinet make a proposal to France to destroy the United States of America, and by making them again dependent on England, persuade Napoleon to lend his aid to destroy the life-work of Louis XVI?... It is to her (England's) interest to conclude peace and to flatter Napoleon's vanity by recognizing his work and his imperial title.'..."

#### Cabinet Approval
- Cabinet discussed proposals and approved them
- **Wellesley at once hurried to Baring's house** to give him good news
- Dutch would be able to pay and would be compelled to pay in gold

#### Napoleon's Objection & Consequences
- Unhappily **Napoleon found out** what was afoot and took somewhat strong objections to plan of joint attack on United States
- He arrested **Ouvard**, dismissed and exiled **Fouche**, and published whole story
- To grave distress of **Wellesley and Baring**

#### Napoleon Not a Paragon of Virtue
- Must not be concluded from this that Napoleon was **paragon of virtue** or **champion of honest money**
- His objection to bankers was that their **monetary power was able to threaten sovereignty of his own political power**
- He allowed them a free hand while they served purpose of state
- Then, when need for military financing subsided, he would **condemn them for making "unholy profits"** and simply **take it from them in the name of the people**
- If bankers protested, they were **sent to prison**

#### Battle Lines Drawn
- And so **battle lines were drawn**
- Napoleon had to be destroyed at all costs
- To make this possible, **Bank of England created vast new amounts of fiat money** to "lend" to government so it could finance an overpowering army
- Steady stream of gold flowed out of country to finance armies of **Russia, Prussia, and Austria**
- Economy staggered once again under **load of war debt**
- Little people paid the bill with hardly a grumble because they hadn't slightest knowledge it was being charged to their account

#### Wilson Concludes:

> "The bankers won. Louis XVIII was restored by British arms and British diplomacy to the throne of his ancestors. Loans were placed at his disposal,"

