### Gold for the Duke of Wellington

- When **Napoleon** returned from exile (1815), he needed military funding — **City of London** loaned him £5,000,000 to equip the army defeated at **Waterloo**
- **Duke of Wellington** faced difficulty convincing Portuguese/Spanish merchants to accept British government promises-to-pay, even with official guarantees — notes were deeply discounted
- **Nathan Rothschild** offered to smuggle gold to Wellington through enemy territory at better terms while making "magnificent profit"
- The operation required moving gold through Napoleon-controlled France

> "There was only one way to route the cash: through the very France England's army was fighting." — **Frederic Morton**

- **James Rothschild** (19 years old, youngest son) went to Paris with dual mission:
  - Provide French authorities false reports about British gold movements, convincing them to convert British gold into "commercially sound banknotes"
  - Coordinate gold receipt into France, conversion to Spanish banknotes, and movement to Wellington
- The **Rothschild brothers** executed elaborate smuggling operation:
  - **Nathan** sent British guineas and Portuguese gold across the Channel
  - **James** saw them to Paris, secretly transmuted into bills on Spanish bankers
  - **Kalmann** materialized south of capital, took over bills, blurred them into Pyrenees canyons, reappeared with Wellington's receipts
  - **Salomon** was everywhere trouble-shooting
  - **Amschel** stayed in Frankfurt to staff headquarters

> "A teen-age Rothschild tricked the imperial government into sanctioning the very process that helped to ruin it." — **Morton**

- French police occasionally caught suspicious activity but couldn't stop the operation
- **Nathan** later boasted at dinner: East India Company had £800,000 gold to sell, he bought it all, knew Wellington needed it, government sent for him asking how to get it to Portugal — he undertook it all and sent through France: "It was the best business I have ever done."

### The Battle of Waterloo

- Waterloo outcome was crucial both politically and economically for Europe
- If **Napoleon** had won, England would have faced:
  - Greater economic trouble than before
  - Loss of international power and prestige
  - Subjects disgruntled over wartime sacrifices
  - Inability to repay war loans
  - In London stock exchange, British government bonds traded anxiously awaiting news

- **Rothschilds** had developed private courier service for transporting gold and moving investment-useful information rapidly
- **Nathan** in London would be first to know the victor's name after cannon smoke cleared
- **Rothworth** (Rothschild agent) waited in Brussels; first news of Wellington's victory arrived midnight June 18, 1815
- Mounted fresh horse for port of Ostend where boat waited to speed him to London
- Arrived at Nathan's door early June 20, full 24 hours before Wellington's own courier **Major Henry Percy**

- Nathan's first act: deliver news to Prime Minister (though some biographers say government officials hesitant to believe it)
- Second act: went to stock exchange to take position at his usual pillar
- Slumped dejectedly, staring at floor, then raised gaze with pained expression and began to sell
- The whisper spread: "Nathan is selling?" "Nathan is selling!" "Wellington must have lost." "Our government bonds will never be repaid." "Sell them now. Sell. Sell!"
- Prices tumbled, Nathan sold again. Prices plummeted, Nathan sold more
- Finally prices collapsed altogether — Nathan reversed his call and **purchased the entire market in government bonds**
- In just a few hours, acquired the dominant holding of England's entire debt at tiny fraction of its worth

### Sidonia

- **Benjamin Disraeli** (Prime Minister of England) wrote novel **Coningsby** (1844)
- Included character **Sidonia** — exact replica of real **Lord Rothschild**, whom Disraeli greatly admired
- Novel depicted Rothschild's emigration from Germany, family and banking ties throughout Europe, handling gold for Wellington, financial coup after Waterloo

> "Europe did require money, and Sidonia was ready to lend it to Europe. France wanted some; Austria more; Prussia a little; Russia a few millions. Sidonia could furnish them all...."

- **New York Times** (April 1, 1915) reported **Baron Nathan Mayer de Rothschild** attempted court order to suppress book by **Ignatious Balla** titled **The Romance of the Rothschilds** claiming Waterloo story was untrue and libelous
- Court ruled the story was true, dismissed suit, ordered Rothschild to pay all court costs

> "He had established a brother, or a near relative, in whom he could confide, in most of the principal capitals. He was lord and master of the money market of the world, and of course virtually lord and master of everything else. He literally held the revenues of Southern Italy in pawn; and monarchs and ministers of all countries courted his advice and were guided by his suggestions."

- **James Rothschild** himself boasted when U.S. Treasury agents approached him in Paris (1842) for loan: **"You have seen the man who is at the head of the finances of Europe."**

### The Rothschild Character Profile

- Men positioned to make private fortunes by cooperating with both sides in war — Rothschilds perfected this art
- Not necessarily evil in moral sense — preoccupied with profit and loss, not right or wrong
- Analytical indifference to human suffering aptly described by one Rothschild: **"When the streets of Paris are running with blood, I buy."**
- Held citizenship in countries of residence but **patriotism was beyond their comprehension**
- Very bright and cunning — made them role model of cool pragmatists dominating political and financial world today

> "He was a man without affections. It would be harsh to say he had no heart, for he was susceptible of deep emotions, but not for individuals.... The individual never touched him. Woman was to him a toy, man a machine." — **Disraeli on Sidonia**

- Absence of patriotism and cold analytical outlook might seem to lead financiers to avoid government loans (private borrowers can be hauled to court, assets confiscated)
- **But governments control legalized use of force** — they are the courts, the police. Who will seize their assets? Another government.

### Government Loans and Military Power

- **Ron Chernow** example: new alliance between monetary and political scientists was mutually advantageous
- Washington wanted to harness financial power to coerce foreign governments into opening markets or adopting pro-American policies
- Banks needed levers to force debt repayment, welcomed government's police powers in distant places
- Threat of military intervention was excellent means to speed loan repayment
- **Kuhn, Loeb** considered loan to Dominican Republic backed by customs receipts
- **Jacob Schiff** inquired of his London associate **Sir Ernest Cassel**: "If they do not pay, who will collect these customs duties?"
- Cassel replied: **"Your marines and ours."**

### Why Governments Always Go Into Debt

- One of great puzzles of history: why governments always go into debt, seldom attempt pay-as-you-go basis
- Partial answer: kings and politicians lack courage to tax subjects the enormous sums required
- Deeper question: why are expenditures so high in first place?

### The Rothschild Formula

Given the mentality of financial lords described by Disraeli, author proposes **The Rothschild Formula** — hypothetical strategy to ensure governments maintain/expand debt:

**1. War is the ultimate discipline to any government.**
- If it can successfully meet challenge of war, it will survive; if cannot, will perish
- All else is secondary: sanctity of laws, prosperity of citizens, solvency of treasury will be quickly sacrificed by any government in primal act of self-survival

**2. All that is necessary to insure government will maintain or expand debt is to involve it in war or threat of war.**
- The greater the threat and more destructive the war, the greater the need for debt

**3. To involve a country in war or threat of war, it will be necessary for it to have enemies with credible military might.**
- If such enemies already exist, all the better
- If exist but lack military strength, necessary to provide them money to build war machine
- If enemy does not exist at all, necessary to create one by financing rise of hostile regime

**4. The ultimate obstacle is a government which declines to finance its wars through debt.**
- Although seldom happens, when it does, necessary to encourage internal political opposition, insurrection, or revolution to replace that government with one more compliant
- The assassination of heads of state could play important role in this process

**5. No nation can be allowed to remain militarily stronger than its adversaries.**
- That could lead to peace and reduction of debt
- To accomplish balance of power, may be necessary to finance both sides of conflict
- Unless one combatant is hostile to our interests and must be destroyed, neither side should be allowed decisive victory or defeat
- While must always proclaim virtues of peace, **the unspoken objective is perpetual war**

### Implementation and Historical Evidence

- Whether anyone actually put this strategy into words or passed it along from generation to generation is not important
- Whether product of conscious planning or merely consequence of men responding to profit opportunities in fiat money
- World's financial lords have acted as though following such a plan — especially apparent since creation of **central-bank Mandrake Mechanism** three centuries ago

### Balance of Power Doctrine

- Most history texts present balance-of-power as natural social phenomenon that worked to benefit of mankind
- Implication: it's wonderful that after all European wars, no nation was strong enough to completely dominate others
- When United States emerged from WWII with exactly such power, it was widely deplored
- Massive political/financial mechanisms (foreign aid, disarmament) set in motion to restore balance
- This became almost revered doctrine of international democracy
- **Overlooked consequence: wars "between equals" have become the permanent landscape of history**

### Selective Financing Example: 1830 Belgium

- Not every war-like group will find easy financing from lords and masters — depends on whom they threaten and likelihood to succeed
- 1830: Dutch facing uprising of subjects in Belgium
- Both ruling government and revolutionaries were dependent upon Rothschilds for financing their conflict
- Dutch rulers were reliable customers for loans and reliable in payment of interest
- Would have been foolhardy to provide more than token assistance to rebels who, if they came to power, quite likely would have refused to honor debts of former puppet regime

> "These gentlemen should not count on us unless they decide to follow a line of prudence and moderation.... Our goodwill does not yet extend to the point of putting clubs into the hands that would beat us, that is, lending money to make war and ruin the credit that we sustain with all our efforts and all our means." — **Salomon Rothschild**

- After revolution resolved by negotiation, new government in Brussels was natural target for financial takeover
- **James Rothschild** laid out strategy that has become model ever since:

> "Now is the moment of which we should take advantage to make ourselves absolute masters of that country's finances. The first step will be to establish ourselves on an intimate footing with Belgium's new Finance Minister, to gain his confidence ... and to take all the treasury bonds he may offer us."

### Perpetual War in Eighteenth Century England

- Wars always been plague to Europe, but not until easy to finance through central banking and fiat money did they become virtually perpetual
- War chronicle begins immediately following formation of **Bank of England** (created for specific purpose of financing a war):

**1689-1697** The War of the League of Augsberg
**1702-1713** The War of Spanish Succession
**1739-1742** The War of Jenkin's Ear
**1744-1748** The War of Austrian Succession
**1754-1763** The French and Indian War
**1793-1801** The War against Revolutionary France
**1803-1815** The Napoleonic Wars

- In addition: two wars with America (War for Independence, War of 1812)
- In 126 years between 1689 and 1815, England was at war 63 of them
- **That is one out of every two years in combat. The others were spent preparing for combat.**

- Mark of Rothschild Formula unmistakable in these conflicts
- Monetary scientists often seen financing both sides
- Whether ending in victory or defeat, outcome merely preserved or restored European "balance of power"
- **Most permanent result of any of these wars was expanded government debt for all parties**

### Summary

By end of eighteenth century, **House of Rothschild** had become one of most successful financial institutions world has ever known:

- Meteoric rise attributed to industry and shrewdness of five brothers who established themselves in various capitals of Europe
- Forged world's first international financial network
- As pioneers in practice of lending money to governments, learned this provided unique opportunities to parlay wealth into political power
- Before long, most princes and kings of Europe had come within their influence

- Mastered art of smuggling on grand scale, often with tacit approval of governments whose laws they violated
- Perceived by all parties as unofficial bonus for providing needed funding, particularly in time of war
- Fact that different branches might also be providing funds for the enemy was pragmatically ignored
- Thus, time-honored practice among financiers was born: **profiting from both sides**

- Operated highly efficient intelligence gathering system providing advance knowledge of important events
- When exhausted Rothschild courier delivered first news of Battle of Waterloo, Nathan able to deceive London bond traders into selling panic
- Acquired dominant holding of England's entire debt at tiny fraction of its worth

- Study reveals personality profile not just of Rothschilds but of special breed of international financiers
- Success built upon: **cold objectivity, immunity to patriotism, indifference to human condition**
- That profile is basis for proposing theoretical strategy called **The Rothschild Formula**
- Motivates such men to propel governments into war for profits they yield
- Formula most likely never been consciously phrased as appears here
- But **subconscious motivations and personality traits work together to implement it nevertheless**
- As long as mechanism of central banking exists, will be to such men irresistible temptation to convert debt into perpetual war and war into perpetual debt

## Chapter Twelve: Sink the Lusitania!

### World War I Overview

Chapter preview: Role of **J.P. Morgan** in providing loans to England and France in WWI; souring of loans as Germany appeared likely to win; betrayal of British ship and sacrifice of American passengers as stratagem to bring America into war; use of American taxes to pay off the loans.

### WWI Origins Beyond the Assassination

- Origin of WWI usually attributed to assassination of **Archduke Francis Ferdinand** of Austria-Hungary by Serbian nationalist (1914)
- Serious affront to Austria but hardly sufficient reason to plunge world into mortal conflict claiming over ten million lives and twenty million wounded
- American schoolchildren taught Uncle Sam came into war "to make the world safe for democracy"
- But American war drums were pounded by men with far less idealistic objectives

### The Rothschild Formula and WWI

- Since latter part of eighteenth century, **Rothschild Formula** had controlled political climate of Europe
- Nations increasingly confronted each other over border disputes, colonial territories, trade routes
- Arms race in progress for many years; large standing armies recruited and drilled; military alliances hammered together
- All in preparation for war
- Assassination of Ferdinand was not the cause but the trigger — merely spark that lit fuse that fired first loaded cannon

### An Investment in War

- Exigencies of war in Europe required England and France to go heavily into debt
- When their central banks and local merchant banks could no longer meet that need, beleaguered governments turned to Americans
- Selected **House of Morgan** (acting as partners of Rothschilds) to act as sales agent for their bonds
- Most money raised in this fashion quickly returned to United States to acquire war-sensitive materials
- Morgan selected as U.S. purchase agent for those as well
- **Commission paid on all transactions in both directions**: once when money borrowed, again when spent
- Furthermore, many companies receiving production contracts were either owned outright by Morgan holding companies or were securely within his orbit of bank control
- Under such arrangement, not surprising Morgan was not overly anxious to see hostilities come to close
- Even most honorable of men can be corrupted by temptation of such gigantic flows of cash

**John Moody** (writing 1919):

> "Not only did England and France pay for their supplies with money furnished by Wall Street, but they made their purchases through the same medium. Inevitably the house of Morgan was selected for this important task. Thus the war had given Wall Street an entirely new role. Hitherto it has been exclusively the headquarters of finance; now it became the greatest industrial mart the world had ever known. In addition to selling stocks and bonds, financing railroads, and performing the other tasks of a great banking center, Wall Street began to deal in shells, cannon, submarines, blankets, clothing, shoes, canned meats, wheat, and the thousands of other articles needed for the prosecution of a great war."

### Morgan's Profits from War

- Money began to flow January 1915 when House of Morgan signed contract with British Army Council and Admiralty
- First purchase: horses, amount tendered $12 million (but that was just first drop before deluge)
- Total purchases would eventually climb to astronomical $3 billion
- Firm became largest consumer on earth, spending up to $10 million per day
- Morgan offices at 23 Wall Street mobbed by brokers and manufacturers seeking to cut a deal
- Bank had to post guards at every door and at partners' homes
- Each month, Morgan presided over purchases equal to gross national product of entire world just one generation before

- Morgan vigorously claimed to be pacifist: "Nobody could hate war more than I do," he told Senate Munitions Committee
- But such professions difficult to accept

**Lewinsohn**:

> "The 500 million dollar loan contracted in autumn 1915 brought to the group of bankers, at whose head Morgan was, a net profit of 9 million dollars.... Again, in 1917, the French government paid to Morgan's and other banks a commission of 1,500,000 dollars, and a further million in 1918."

- Besides loans: another source of profit was purchase and sale of American stock which Allies surrendered so they could buy munitions in United States
- Estimated that in course of war some **$2 billion** passed this way through Morgan's hands
- Even if commission very small, transactions of such dimensions would give him influence on stock market carrying very real advantages

- His hatred against war did not prevent him, citizen of neutral country, from furnishing belligerent powers with **4,400,000 rifles** for matter of **$194,000,000**
- Profits such as to compensate to some degree his hatred of warfare
- According to his own account, received as agent of English and French governments commission of **1% on orders totalling $3,000,000,000** — that is, **received some $30,000,000**

- Morgan also acted for Russia ($412,000,000) and for Italy and Canada (figures not published)
- J.P. Morgan and some partners were at time shareholders in companies that were concerns which made substantial profits from orders he placed with them
- "It is really astonishing that a central buying organization should have been confided to one who was buyer and seller at the same time."

### Germany's U-Boats Almost Won the War

- Dark clouds gathering above Wall Street as war began to go badly for Allies
- Easy to forget Germany and Central Powers almost won war prior to U.S. entry
- Employing small fleet of newly developed submarines, Germany well on her way to cutting off England and allies from all outside help
- Amazing feat that changed forever concept of naval warfare
- Germany had total of twenty-one U-boats, but because constantly had to be repaired and serviced, maximum number at sea was only seven at any one time
- Yet between 1914 and 1918, German submarines had sunk over **5,700 surface ships**
- **Three-hundred thousand tons of Allied shipping sent to bottom every week**
- **One out of every four steamers leaving British Isles never returned**

**Arthur Balfour** (British Foreign Secretary) wrote: "At that time, it certainly looked as though we were going to lose the war."

**Robert Ferrell** (in Woodrow Wilson and World War I): "The Allies approached the brink of disaster, with no recourse other than to ask Germany for terms."

**William McAdoo** (Secretary of Treasury) in memoirs:

> "Across the sea came the dismay of the British—a dismay that carried a deepening note of disaster. There was a fear, and a well-grounded one, that England might be starved into abject surrender.... On April 27, 1917, Ambassador Walter H. Page reported confidentially to the President that the food in the British Isles was not more than enough to feed the civil population for six weeks or two months."

### Morgan Couldn't Find New Bond Buyers

- Under these circumstances, became impossible for Morgan to find new buyers for Allied war bonds
- Neither for fresh funding nor to replenish old bonds coming due and facing default
- Serious on several counts:
  - If bond sales came to halt, no money to continue purchasing war materials — commissions lost at both ends
  - If previously sold bonds went into default (as they certainly would if Britain and France forced to accept peace on Germany's terms), investors would sustain gigantic losses
- Something had to be done. But what?

**Robert Ferrell** hints at answer:

> "In the mid thirties a Senate committee headed by Gerald P. Nye of North Dakota investigated the pre-1917 munitions trade and raised a possibility that the Wilson administration went to war because American bankers needed to protect their Allied loans."

### Ambassador Page's Telegram

- As previously mentioned by William McAdoo, American ambassador to England at that time was **Walter Hines Page**
- Trustee of **Rockefeller's** social-engineering foundation called **General Education Board**
- Learned by Nye committee that, in addition to government salary, Page also received allowance of **$25,000 a year** (enormous amount in 1917) from **Cleveland Dodge**, president of Rockefeller's **National City Bank**
- On **March 15, 1917**, Ambassador Page sent telegram to State Department outlining financial crisis in England
- Since sources of new capital had dried up, only way to keep war going was to make direct grants from U.S. Treasury
- But since this would be violation of neutrality treaties, United States would have to abandon its neutrality and enter the war

> "I think that the pressure of this approaching crisis has gone beyond the ability of the Morgan Financial Agency for the British and French Governments.... The greatest help we could give the Allies would be such a credit.... Unless we go to war with Germany, our Government, of course, cannot make such a direct grant of credit."

### Morgan Group's $1.5 Billion at Risk

- Morgan group had floated **one-and-a-half billion dollars** in loans to Britain and France
- With fortunes of war turning against them, investors facing threat of total loss

**Ferdinand Lundberg**:

> "The declaration of war by the United States, in addition to extricating the wealthiest American families from a dangerous situation, also opened new vistas of profits."

### Colonel House

**Colonel Edward Mandell House** — one of most influential men behind scenes:
- Personal adviser to Woodrow Wilson and later to F.D.R.
- Had close contacts with both J.P. Morgan and old banking families of Europe
- Received several years schooling in England
- In later years, surrounded himself with prominent members of **Fabian Society**
- Man of great personal wealth, most acquired during War Between the States
- His father, **Thomas William House**, had acted as confidential American agent of unknown banking interests in London
- Commonly believed he represented the Rothschilds
- Although settled in Houston, Texas, the elder often remarked he wanted his sons to "know and serve England"
- One of few residents of Confederate state who emerged from War with great fortune

- Widely acknowledged that Colonel House was the man who selected Wilson as presidential candidate and secured his nomination
- Became Wilson's constant companion
- President admitted publicly he depended on him greatly for instruction and guidance
- Many of Wilson's important appointive posts in government were hand selected by House
- He and Wilson developed private code so they could communicate freely over telephone

**The President himself** had written: **"Mr. House is my second personality. He is my independent self. His thoughts and mine are one."**

**George Viereck** (admiring biographer of House):

> "House had the Texas delegation in his pocket.... Always moving quietly in the background, he made and unmade several governors of Texas.... House selected Wilson because he regarded him as the best available candidate.... For seven long years Colonel House was Woodrow Wilson's other self. For six long years he shared with him all but the title of the Chief Magistracy of the Republic. For six years two men were at his disposal in the North Wing of the White House.... It was House who made the slate for the Cabinet, formulated the first policies of the Administration and practically directed the foreign affairs of the United States. We had, indeed, two Presidents for one!... Super-ambassador, he talked to emperors and kings as an equal. He was the spiritual generalissimo of the Administration. He was the pilot who guided the ship."

### A Secret Agreement to Get the U.S. Into War

- As presidential election neared for Wilson's second term, Colonel House entered into series of confidential talks with **Sir William Wiseman**
- Wiseman attached to British embassy in Washington
- Acted as secret intermediary between House and British Foreign Office

**Charles Seymour** writes: "Between House and Wiseman there were soon to be few political secrets."

- This was upsetting to Secretary of State **William Jennings Bryan**
- **Mrs. Bryan** (co-author of husband's memoirs) writes:

> "While Secretary Bryan was bearing the heavy responsibility of the Department of State, there arose the curious conditions surrounding Mr.
<!-- pp. 281-300 -->

## The Secret Treaty: Wilson's Commitment to War

### Colonel House's Secret Negotiations

- **E.M. House** bypassed Secretary of State **William Jennings Bryan**, conducting unofficial foreign policy on Wilson's behalf
- Ten months before the 1916 election (where Wilson campaigned on "he kept us out of war"), **House negotiated a secret agreement with England and France** pledging U.S. intervention on behalf of the Allies
- **March 9, 1916**: Wilson formally sanctioned the undertaking
- The **Secret Treaty** created without Senate knowledge or consent, chaining the U.S. to the Entente
- After the war, the agreement leaked; discussed by **Sir Edward Grey**, **C. Hartley Grattan** (*Why We Fought*), but "never penetrated the consciousness of the American people"

> "If an inkling of the conversations between Colonel House and the leaders of England and France had reached the American people before the election, it might have caused incalculable revulsions of public opinion...." — Viereck

### The Rigged Peace Proposal

- Terms: U.S. would offer to negotiate peaceful settlement between Germany and the Allies, then propose specific terms
- **The catch**: terms were "carefully drafted so that Germany could not possibly accept them"
- Result: Germany would appear at fault, U.S. would look humanitarian
- **Ambassador Page's memo** (Feb 9, 1916): House and British Cabinet would work out "a minimum programme of peace—the least that the Allies would accept, which, he assumed, would be unacceptable to the Germans"
- The side declining the proposal would be blamed for continuing the war

> "Of course, the fatal moral weakness of the foregoing scheme is that we should plunge into the War, not on the merits of the cause, but by a carefully sprung trick" — Ambassador Page

### Wilson's Internationalist Motivation

- Surface paradox: Wilson the pacifist enters secret agreement for war
- Key: Wilson was an **internationalist** who dreamed of **world government** with House
- Both recognized Americans would only accept loss of national sovereignty in "extenuating circumstances"
- A long, costly war was "probably the only event that could condition the American mind" to accept world government
- Wilson calculated: enter war early enough to make a battlefield difference, loan large sums to Allies → position to **dictate peace terms** afterward

> "England and France have not the same views with regard to peace as we have by any means. When the war is over, we can force them to our way of thinking, because by that time they will among other things be financially in our hands." — Wilson to House

### Selling War: The Pacifist Platform of 1916

- March 1917: Wilson hinted at both war and world government
- **Democratic breakfast meeting**: Wilson asked leaders to help sell war to Congress and voters despite public opposition
- Leaders rejected; Wilson dropped it to avoid splitting the party before election
- Pacifist platform mapped out with **Colonel House**: **"He kept us out of war!"** slogan
- **Governor Martin Glynn** and **Senator Ollie James** gave keynote speeches at St. Louis convention on this theme
- Germans then played into Wilson's hands: resumed submarine warfare
- **Britain overdrawn $450 million** on American credit; bankers needed Federal Treasury to take over financing the Entente

### Wall Street Media Control

- **J.P. Morgan firm** chose executives for Harper & Brothers publishing house
- **Pierpont Morgan** had "effective control of the New York Sun... Boston News Bureau, Barron's magazine, and the Wall Street Journal"
- **March 1915**: Morgan interests, steel, shipbuilding, powder interests recruited "12 men high up in the newspaper world" to control policy of daily press
- Purchased controlling interest in 25 greatest papers; editors paid monthly to supervise content on "preparedness, militarism, financial policies"

> "An agreement was reached; the policy of the papers was bought, to be paid for by the month an editor was furnished for each paper to properly supervise and edit information regarding the questions of preparedness, militarism, financial policies, and other things of national and international nature considered vital to the interests of the purchasers." — Representative Callaway, Congressional Record, Feb 9, 1917

- **Charles S. Mellen** (New Haven Railroad) testified: Morgan-owned railroad had 1,000+ New England newspapers on payroll (costing ~$400,000 annually), held $500,000 in Boston Herald bonds
- Morgan trust also controlled media through **advertising power** — "More advertising is controlled by the J.P. Morgan junta than by any single financial group"

### Morgan's Parallel Media Strategy: The Rockefeller Approach

- 1912 Senate hearings revealed **Joseph Sibley** (Pennsylvania Rep.) funneled Rockefeller money to cooperative Congressmen
- **1905 letter to John D. Archbold** (Standard Oil): "An efficient literary bureau is needed... permanent healthy control of the Associated Press and kindred avenues"
- Rockefellers shifted from owning newspapers outright to **controlling publications** through advertising revenue and direct payments for "friendly editorial attitude"

### Morgan Control Over Shipping

- Morgan created **international shipping trust** including Germany's two largest lines plus **White Star Lines** (England)
- Attempted 1902 takeover of **Cunard Company** blocked by British Admiralty (wanted Cunard available for military service)
- **Lusitania and Mauretania** built by Cunard, became major competitors to Morgan cartel
- From Morgan's perspective, Lusitania was "quite dispensable"
- **Albert Ballin's Hamburg-Amerika Steamship Line** was world's largest shipping company, architect of the trust
- After Boer War, Morgan combine and Cunard "exhausted each other in debilitating rate wars"

### Morgan as Britain's War Trade Agent

- Morgan retained as **official British trade agent** in U.S.
- Handled all war materials purchasing and shipping coordination
- Learned profitable wartime smuggling skills (following Rothschild precedent)
- **British servicemen in civilian clothes worked at Morgan's**, establishing "labyrinthine network of false shippers, bank accounts and all the paraphernalia of smuggling"
- Fooled Germans but also created "serious occasions when they flummoxed the Admiralty and Cunard"

## The Lusitania

### The Ship's Dual Nature

- British passenger liner, Liverpool-New York route, owned by Cunard (Morgan's only major shipping competitor)
- Left New York **May 1, 1915**, sunk by German submarine off Ireland **six days later**
- **1,195 dead, 195 Americans**
- Turning point: "provided the advocates of war with a convincing platform"

**But she was not simply a passenger ship:**

- Construction specifications drawn by **British Admiralty** for conversion to warship
- Engines/hull designed for ammunition storage, built to carry **twelve six-inch guns**
- British government paid construction costs for military features
- Required crew include **Royal Navy Reserve** officers/seamen even in peacetime
- **May 1913**: Brought to dry dock for armor, revolving gun rings, shell racks, ammunition elevators
- **Twelve high-explosive cannons** delivered to dry dock
- **September 17, 1913**: Entered Admiralty fleet register "not as a passenger liner, but an **armed auxiliary cruiser**"
- Listed in **Jane's Fighting Ships** and British publication **The Naval Annual** as armed merchant man

### Military Cargo on Final Voyage

- Lower deck passenger accommodations removed to make room for military cargo
- **600 tons pyroxyline** (gun cotton), **six-million rounds ammunition**, **1,248 cases shrapnel shells**
- Unknown quantities of munitions filled lowest deck holds, trunways, passageways
- Many tons of "cheese," "lard," "furs" later shown to be falsely labeled contraband/weapons
- All consigned through **J.P. Morgan Company**
- Public and American passengers completely unaware

### German Warning Suppressed

- German embassy filed formal complaint about cargo (violating neutrality treaties)
- Wilson Administration issued flat denial
- German embassy placed ad in **fifty East Coast newspapers** warning Americans not to sail Lusitania
- Ad prepaid, requested for travel page **one week before sailing**
- **State Department intervened**, threatened libel suits, frightened publishers
- Only **Des Moines Register** carried ad on requested date

### Secretary Bryan Discovers the Truth

- **George Viereck** (German-owned newspaper editor) asked State Department why ad wasn't published
- Eventually interviewed **William Jennings Bryan** (Secretary of State)
- Bryan saw Lusitania's supplementary manifests (open to public inspection at collector's office)
- Discovered **six million rounds ammunition due to ship Friday**, being loaded at pier 54
- **Bryan picked up telephone, cleared publication** of German warning ad
- Promised to persuade President to publicly warn Americans not to travel
- No warning issued by President
- Wilson later conceded foreknowledge gave him "many sleepless hours" when told of sinking

> "President Wilson was told of the character of the cargo destined for the Lusitania. He did nothing, but was to concede on the day he was told of her sinking that his foreknowledge had given him many sleepless hours."

### Wilson's Tragic Position

- Probably a pacifist at heart, but "not entirely the master of his own destiny"
- Transplanted Princeton professor, **ivy-covered walls**, internationalist dreaming of world government
- "Surrounded by and dependent upon men of strong wills, astute political aptitudes, and powerful financial resources"
- Against these forces, "all but powerless to act on his own"
- Refused to warn countrymen of mortal peril, **sent 195 Americans to watery graves**

## Churchill Sets a Trap

### The Conspiracy Theory

- **Robert Ballard** (National Geographic): "Within days of the sinking, German sympathizers in New York came up with a conspiracy theory. The British Admiralty, they said, had deliberately exposed Lusitania to harm, hoping she would be attacked and thus draw the U.S. into the war."

### Churchill's Strategy

- **Winston Churchill** (First Lord of Admiralty): maneuvers in war include "time, diplomacy, mechanics, psychology"

> "The maneuver which brings an ally into the field is as serviceable as that which wins a great battle. The maneuver which gains an important strategic point may be less valuable than that which placates or overawes a dangerous neutral."

- **October 1914**: Churchill ordered merchant ships must no longer obey U-boat halt orders
- If armed, engage enemy; if not, **attempt to ram the sub**
- Result: forced German U-boats to remain submerged, sink ships without warning

> "The first British countermove, made on my responsibility,... was to deter the Germans from surface attack. The submerged U-boat had to rely increasingly on underwards attack and thus ran the greater risk of mistaking neutral for British ships and of drowning neutral crews and thus embroiling Germany with other Great Powers." — Churchill

### Making Neutral Ships Targets

- To increase likelihood of sinking neutral ships, Churchill ordered:
  - British ships **remove names from hulls**
  - When in port, **fly flag of neutral power** (preferably U.S.)
  - Captured U-boat crews treated **not as prisoners of war but as felons**
  - "Survivors should be taken prisoner or shot—whichever is the most convenient"
  - Official order: **"In all actions, white flags should be fired upon with promptitude"**

### The Final Voyage Setup

- Lusitania's orders: rendezvous with British destroyer **Juno** off Ireland coast for naval protection
- When Lusitania reached rendezvous, she was alone
- **Juno called out of area last minute**, ordered back to Queenstown
- Done with full knowledge Lusitania on direct course into area with **known German submarine**
- Lusitania ordered to **cut back on coal use** (not due to shortage, but expense)
- Shut down one of four boilers → entering submarine waters at **only 75% potential speed**
- Slow targets much easier to hit

### Churchill Watches the Trap Close

- Newspapers in London carried German warnings, recent submarine sinkings
- In Admiralty map room, Churchill watched the play unfold
- Small disks marked two ships torpedoed day before
- Circle showed U-boat operating area
- Larger disk: Lusitania traveling at nineteen knots directly into circle
- **Admiral Coke at Queenstown** given perfunctory instructions to protect her, "had no means to do so"
- **No one notified Lusitania captain** that rendezvous with Juno canceled

### Commander Kenworthy's Assessment

- **Commander Joseph Kenworthy** previously asked by Churchill to submit paper on political results of ocean liner sinking with American passengers
- Left room in disgust at cynicism
- 1927 book **The Freedom of the Seas**: "The Lusitania was sent at considerably reduced speed into an area where a U-boat was known to be waiting and with her escorts withdrawn."

### House and Grey Discuss the Scenario

- **Colonel House in England** on sinking day, scheduled audience with **King George V**
- Accompanied by **Sir Edward Grey**
- Grey asked: "What will America do if the Germans sink an ocean liner with American passengers on board?"
- **House's diary**: "I told him if this were done, a flame of indignation would sweep America, which would in itself probably carry us into the war."
- At Buckingham Palace, **King George** asked: "Suppose they should sink the Lusitania with American passengers onboard...."

## Sink the Lusitania!

### The Attack

- Four hours after House-Grey conversation, **U-20** spotted Lusitania's black smoke
- Ship came directly toward U-boat, allowing ninety-degree bow shot at 750 yards
- Torpedo struck nine feet below waterline, starboard side, slightly forward of bridge
- Second torpedo readied but not needed
- **Second explosion** after impact — much larger, "literally blew the side off of cargo hold number two," started ship toward bottom
- **Sank in less than eighteen minutes**

### The Massive Internal Explosion

- Boiler room survivors attested **boilers did not blow**
- Something else caused catastrophic explosion that blew out bottom of bow
- Possibilities: Bethlehem Company 3-inch shells, six million rounds rifle ammunition, "highly dubious contents of the bales of furs or the small forty-pound boxes of cheese"
- Divers testimony: bow blasted by **massive internal explosion**, large pieces of bow plating buckled from inside

### 1993 Woods Hole Survey

- Cameras swept wreck, reported: **"There was no hole"**
- Wreck resting on starboard (right) side — where torpedo struck
- Hole not visible because on side buried in ocean floor
- Only part of hull's underside inspectable
- Torpedo struck nine feet below waterline; hole would be at midpoint between main deck and bottom (buried side)

> "Failure to see the hole does not undermine the theory of internal explosion. It is exactly what one would expect."

- Lusitania wouldn't sink in eighteen minutes "without a hole somewhere"
- Search team concluded explosion "probably was caused, not by munitions, but by coal dust" to avoid supporting conspiracy theory
- **Whether munitions or coal dust makes little difference** — fact it could have been munitions is sufficient

### The Cover-Up

- Official inquiry under **Lord Mersey** to determine facts and place blame
- "Rigged affair from the beginning" — all evidence pre-screened
- **Captain Richard Webb** paper submitted to Mersey: "I am directed by the board of Admiralty to inform you that it is considered politically expedient that **Captain Turner, the master of the Lusitania, be most prominently blamed for the disaster**"

### Mersey's Verdict

- Final report blamed Captain Turner without knowledge of facts
- Mersey softened: "blame ought not to be imputed to the captain.... His omission to follow the advice in all respects cannot fairly be attributed either to negligence or incompetence"
- Then added final paragraph appearing to condemn Germans but actually indicting Churchill/Wilson/House/Morgan:

> "The whole blame for the cruel destruction of life in this catastrophe must rest solely with those who plotted and with those who committed the crime."

- Two days later, Mersey delivered judgment, wrote to Prime Minister Asquith turning down fee: "I must request that henceforth I be excused from administering His Majesty's Justice."
- Later years: **"The Lusitania case was a damn dirty business."**

## The Cry for War

### Wilson's Outrage Performance

- Wilson sent note of "outraged indignation" to Imperial German Government (widely quoted in press)
- **Bryan became completely disillusioned** by government duplicity
- **May 9**: sent dour note to Wilson opposing war stance

> "Germany has a right to prevent contraband going to the Allies and a ship carrying contraband should not rely upon passengers to protect her from attack-it would be like putting women and children in front of an army."

### Bryan's Near-Resignation

- First note followed by stronger one with threatening overtones
- Intensely discussed at **Cabinet meeting, first of June**
- **McAdoo**: "Bryan had little to say at this meeting; he sat throughout the proceedings with his eyes half closed most of the time After the meeting he told the President, as I learned later, that he could not sign the note"
- Bryan proposed to resign
- McAdoo dispatched to Bryans' home to persuade him to reconsider
- Bryan agreed to think overnight; decision remained firm next morning
- **Couldn't sleep that night** — wife suggested reading to become drowsy
- Read from old book *A Wreath of Appreciation of Andrew Jackson*
- Found it "very interesting"

### Jackson's Warning Echoes

> "Is there no danger to our liberty and independence in a bank that in its nature has so little to bind it to our country?... Controlling our currency, receiving our public monies, and holding thousands of our citizens in dependence, it would be more formidable and dangerous than a naval and military power of the enemy." — Andrew Jackson

- Irony: Bryan recalled Jackson's warning about the **Bank of the United States** (Federal Reserve's predecessor)
- Applied it to artificially created war hysteria "being generated by the financial powers on Wall Street and at the newly created Federal Reserve"

### House's Telegram: The Call to War

- From England, **Colonel House sent telegram to Wilson**, read to Cabinet
- Became genesis of thousands of newspaper editorials:

> "America has come to the parting of the ways, when she must determine whether she stands for civilized or uncivilized warfare. We can no longer remain neutral spectators. Our action in this crisis will determine the part we will play when peace is made, and how far we may influence a settlement for the lasting good of humanity. We are being weighed in the balance, and our position amongst nations is being assessed by mankind."

### House Plays Wilson's Ego

- Two days later, another telegram revealing House as "master psycho-politician playing on Wilson's ego like a violinist":

> "If, unhappily, it is necessary to go to war, I hope you will give the world an exhibition of American efficiency that will be a lesson for a century or more. It is generally believed throughout Europe that we are so unprepared and that it would take so long to put our resources into action, that our entering would make but little difference. In the event of war, we should accelerate the manufacture of munitions to such an extent that we could supply not only ourselves but the Allies, and so quickly that the world would be astounded."

## War Declared: The Payoff

### Congress Declares War

- **April 16, 1917**: U.S. officially declared war on Axis powers
- Eight days later, Congress passed **War Loan Act** extending **$1 billion credit to Allies**
- **First $200 million advance** went to British next day, **immediately applied as payment on debt to Morgan**
- Few days later, **$100 million to France** for same purpose
- Within three months: **British overdraft with Morgan reached $400 million**, firm presented to government for payment

### The Mandrake Mechanism Solution

- Treasury unable to pay without jeopardizing spendable funds
- Initially refused to pay
- **Federal Reserve under Benjamin Strong** created needed money through **Mandrake Mechanism**
- Wilson Administration "offered to help" by bailing out J.P. Morgan
- Treasury-Secretary **McAdoo** (Wilson's son-in-law) solved difficulty
- Over following months 1917-18: **Treasury quietly paid Morgan piecemeal for overdraft**
- By war's end: Treasury loaned total **$9,466,000,000** including **$2,170,000,000 after Armistice**

### War Production Profits

- In addition to Morgan loan repayment, even larger profits from war production
- Government secretly preparing for war **six months before declaration**
- **Franklin D. Roosevelt** (Assistant Secretary of Navy): Navy Department began extensive purchasing fall 1916


<!-- pp. 301-320 -->

## Wall Street Patriots in Government Posts

### Bernard Baruch and the War Industries Board

- **Wilson consulted with Cleveland Dodge** (Rockefeller's National City Bank) who recommended **Bernard Baruch**, a copper stock speculator, as chairman of the **War Industries Board**
- Baruch spent government funds at **$10 billion annually**
- Packed the board with Wall Street manipulators, industrialists, financiers who **fixed prices on cost-plus basis** and padded costs to yield hidden profits
- Investigations revealed costs were grossly inflated to generate profits for insiders

> "The American soldiers fighting in the trenches, the people working at home, the entire nation under arms, were fighting, not only to subdue Germany, but to subdue themselves."

### War Profiteering Statistics

- **Total U.S. war expenditure** (April 6, 1917 - October 31, 1919): **$35.4 billion**
- **Net corporation profits** (January 1916 - July 1921): **$38 billion** — approximately equal to war expenditures
- **Two-thirds of these profits** went to enterprises controlled by the "**Money Trust**" (identified by Pujo Committee)

## Financing the War: The Hidden Tax of Inflation

### The Cycle of War Finance

- Federal Reserve created money for loans to **England and France**
- England/France used funds to purchase from American banks
- Banks repaid — same pattern later repeated in **WWII** and **1980s-90s bailouts**

### Inflation as Primary Funding Mechanism

- **Money supply doubled** 1915-1920: from **$20.6 billion to $39.8 billion**
- **Purchasing power fell almost 50%** during WWI
- Americans unknowingly paid government approximately **half of every dollar through inflation** — on top of direct taxes
- **Mandrake Mechanism** created this money at no cost to banks, yet banks collected interest on it all
- Income tax (recently enacted 1913) useful for revenue, but **greatest funding came from hidden inflation tax**

> "The partnership between the political and monetary scientists had performed its mission well."

## Summary: Morgan's War Business Model

### Morgan's Triple Profit Stream

1. **Bond sales agent** for England/France — profited when money was borrowed
2. **U.S. purchasing agent** for war materials — profited when money was spent
3. **Production contracts** with companies in Morgan orbit

### The Crisis Point

- Germany's submarines took **virtual control of Atlantic shipping lanes**
- If Allies moved toward **defeat or negotiated peace**, bond sales would collapse
- **No bonds = no purchases = Morgan cash flow threatened**
- Previously sold bonds would likely **default**, causing gigantic Morgan losses

### The Solution: American Entry

- Only U.S. government money could save the British Empire, restore bond values, sustain Morgan cash flow
- Treaty prohibited neutral nations from providing such funds
- **Secret agreement** made between British officials and **Colonel House** (Wilson's advisor), with President's concurrence
- Wilson began pressuring Congress for war declaration while **campaigning on "He kept us out of war"**
- **Morgan purchased control of major news media** segments, engineered nation-wide editorial blitz calling for war as patriotic duty

## The Lusitania Incident

### Morgan's Shipping Cartel

- Morgan created **international shipping cartel** including Germany's merchant fleet
- Near monopoly on high seas — only **British Cunard Lines remained independent**
- **Lusitania** owned by Cunard, operated in competition with Morgan's cartel

### Lusitania as Bait

- Built to **military specifications**, registered with British Admiralty as **armed auxiliary cruiser**
- Carried passengers as cover for real mission: **bringing contraband war materials from U.S.**
- Wilson administration knew this but did nothing to stop it
- **German embassy attempted to warn American passengers** via newspaper ads
- **State Department intervened**, prevented newspapers from printing warning except one (Des Moines Register)

### The Sinking

- Lusitania entered hostile waters where **German U-boat was known to be operating**
- **Winston Churchill** (First Lord of Admiralty) ordered **destroyer protection to abandon her**
- Ordered to travel at **reduced speed** — easy target
- **One torpedo hit, second explosion from within** ripped her apart
- Ship believed unsinkable sank in minutes
- **195 Americans aboard** — became center of national campaign for war

### The Aftermath

- Set in motion "great wav revulsion against the Germans"
- Within days Congress voted **$1 billion credit for England and France**
- **$200 million sent to England immediately**, applied to Morgan account
- Federal Reserve System created the money — collected from Americans through **inflation tax**
- Within five years, inflation consumed more than Americans had saved

### Converging Motives

- **Churchill** maneuvered for British advantage
- **Morgan** sought war profits
- **Colonel House** sought power
- **Wilson** dreamed of dominating post-war **League of Nations**

> "Thus it was that the separate motives of diverse personalities as Winston Churchill, J.P. Morgan, Colonel House, and Woodrow Wilson all found common cause in bringing America into World War I."

## Chapter Thirteen: Masquerade in Moscow

### The Bolshevik Revolution Myth

- **Greatest myth of contemporary history**: Bolshevik Revolution was popular uprising of downtrodden masses against Tsarist ruling class
- Reality: **planning, leadership, and especially financing came entirely from outside Russia** — from financiers in **Germany, Britain, and United States**
- **Rothschild Formula** played major role in shaping events

### Jacob Schiff Finances Japan Against Russia

- **Jacob Schiff** (head of **Kuhn, Loeb, and Company**, New York) raised capital for **large war loans to Japan**
- Japanese used funding to launch **stunning attack at Port Arthur** (1904), decimating Russian fleet following year
- **Mikado awarded Schiff** the **Second Order of the Treasure of Japan** (1905) in recognition

### Schiff's Revolutionary Propaganda Campaign

- During Russo-Japanese War, thousands of Russian soldiers/sailors taken prisoner
- Schiff paid for printing **one-and-a-half tons of Marxist propaganda**, delivered to prison camps
- Sent **scores of Russian-speaking revolutionaries** (trained in New York) to distribute materials, indoctrinate prisoners into rebellion
- When war ended, **50,000 officers and enlisted men** returned home as "virtual seeds of treason against the Tsar"
- Played major role in military mutiny during Communist takeover

## Trotsky Was Schiff's Agent

### Trotsky's American Sojourn

- **Leon Trotsky** expelled from France, came to U.S. (January 1916) at **Schiff's invitation**
- **Travel expenses aboard the Monserrat paid by Schiff**
- Remained several months writing for Russian socialist paper **Novy Mir** (New World), giving revolutionary speeches at mass meetings in New York City

### Trotsky's Wealthy Benefactor

- Trotsky driven in **chauffeured limousine** provided by "**Dr. M.**" — wealthy friend
- According to Trotsky's autobiography **My Life**: doctor's wife took Trotsky's family driving, but chauffeur was "a magician, a titan, a superman"
- Boys anxiously asked: "Why doesn't the chauffeur come in?" when visiting tea-rooms
- Ironic sight: great socialist radical enjoying "pleasures of tea rooms and chauffeurs, the very symbols of capitalist luxury"
- **Almost all expenses in New York, including mass rallies, paid by Jacob Schiff**

### Carnegie Hall Celebration (March 23, 1917)

- Mass meeting celebrating **abdication of Nicholas II** and overthrow of Tsarist rule
- Thousands of socialists, Marxists, nihilists, anarchists attended
- Next day **New York Times** published telegram from **Jacob Schiff** (read to audience) expressing regrets he couldn't attend, describing successful revolution as **"...what we had hoped and striven for these long years."**

### Schiff's Grandson Confirms the Investment

- **February 3, 1949** issue of **New York Journal American**: Schiff's grandson **John** quoted saying grandfather gave **about $20 million for triumph of Communism in Russia**

### The $10,000 in Halifax

- When Trotsky returned to Petrograd (May 1917) to organize Bolshevik phase, he carried **$10,000 for travel expenses**
- Amount known with certainty — Trotsky arrested by Canadian/British naval personnel when ship stopped at **Halifax**
- Money became matter of official record
- Assumed to be **German money** (Germany at war with Russia), but evidence shows it came from **Kuhn, Loeb and Company**

### Why England Released Trotsky

- Trotsky arrested as threat to **England's best interests** — Russia was England's ally
- Internal revolution would weaken Russia, thus **strengthen Germany and weaken England**
- Trotsky announced intent: **"I am going back to Russia to overthrow the provisional government and stop the war with Germany."**
- Yet Trotsky **released as prisoner of war** and allowed to proceed

### Mysterious Interventions

- Telegrams began arriving in Halifax from divergent sources: obscure New York attorney, Canadian Deputy Postmaster-General, high-ranking British military officer
- All inquiring into Trotsky's situation, urging **immediate release**
- **Sir William Wiseman** (head of British Secret Service in America, lived in apartment directly above **Edward Mandell House**) advised **President Wilson** wished Trotsky released
- British Admiralty issued orders **April 21st** to send Trotsky on his way
- **Fateful decision** affecting not only war outcome but **future of entire world**

