## Chapter 13: An Object Lesson in South Africa

### The Boer War and Gold Fields
- **Cecil Rhodes** monopolized diamond fields in South Africa under British control
- Discovery of gold in the **Transvaal** (held by **Boers**—Dutch settlers) triggered geopolitical conflict
- Rhodes became obsessed with consolidating Transvaal under British rule, viewing President **Paul Kruger's** independent Transvaal as the main obstacle
- In 1895, Rhodes financed an uprising in Johannesburg led by **Sir Leander Jameson**; the uprising failed and Jameson was arrested

### Round Table Engineering the War
- After the failed coup, Rhodes prepared a second plot through his ally **Lord Alfred Milner** (British High Commissioner for South Africa)
- **Jan Smuts** (Cambridge graduate, Rhodes supporter, agent in Kimberly diamond mines) became state secretary of Transvaal and wrote provocative ultimatums to British troop movements
- Round Table members positioned agents on **both sides**: Milner coordinated British response; Smuts coordinated Boer resistance
- The war began October 1899; after 2.5 years of fighting, Boers surrendered; Milner administered the territory as a military occupation
- Round Table members (called **"Milner's Kindergarten"**) were placed into all key government posts; gold fields were secured

### Morgan's Playing Both Sides
- **J.P. Morgan** applied the same tactic in New York with brilliant precision
- Morgan's firm kept feet in all political camps: Morgan and **Dwight Morrow** allied with Republicans; **Russell C. Leffingwell** with Democrats; **Grayson Murphy** with the extreme Right; **Thomas W. Lamont** with the Left
- **Thomas Lamont** (father of Communist **Corliss Lamont**) was a leftist but also served as unofficial business consultant to **Mussolini** in the 1920s—demonstrating that a single individual could comfortably align with opposing ideologies
- At the same time Morgan funded pro-Bolshevik groups, he founded **United Americans**, a virulent anti-Bolshevik organization claiming a "Red mob" was poised to capture New York City

### The United Americans Paradox
- Officers of United Americans included **Allen Walker** (Guarantee Trust Company—acting as Soviet fiscal agent in U.S.); **Daniel Willard** (president of Baltimore & Ohio Railway, active in Soviet railway development); **H.H. Westing-house** (Westinghouse Air Brake Company operating major plant in Russia); **Otto H. Kahn** (principal financial backer of Hedgling Soviet regime)
- The organization issued shocking reports warning of financial collapse, widespread starvation, and Communist coups—while its own officers profited from Soviet deals
- Inside Russia itself, Round Table was spreading its bets: funding **Admiral Kolchak** (fighting Bolsheviks in Siberia) through British financiers including **Alfred Milner**, while also funding the Bolsheviks themselves

### The Red Cross Mission Deception
- Official narrative: Red Cross mission to Moscow prevented Russia from making separate peace with Germany—kept German troops fighting England and France
- Alternative reading (supported by evidence): Morgan interests were placing bets on all horses so no matter who won, they'd be obligated to them
- When Kerensky (Tsar's replacement) was overthrown, Morgan's financiers supported the Mensheviks; when Bolsheviks took power, they switched support—the "inevitably victorious" faction
- **Lincoln Steffens** (leftist writer aboard S.S. Kristianiafjord with arrested Trotsky) witnessed conversations with **Charles Crane** (vice president of Crane Company, backer of Woodrow Wilson, chairman of Democratic finance committee). Crane had organized **Westinghouse** in Russia with 23 prior visits. Steffens recorded: *"all agree that the revolution is in its first phase only, that it must grow... we shall be in Petrograd for the re-revolution."*—the goal was a *second* revolution, not mere humanitarian relief

