## Chapter 14: The Best Enemy Money Can Buy

### Two Revolutions, Not One
- **February Revolution** (1917): established provisional socialist government under **Aleksandr Kerensky**; moderate, inclusive of Bolsheviks (smallest minority)
- **Lenin** in Switzerland; **Trotsky** in New York writing propaganda—neither in Russia during February Revolution
- **October Revolution** (coup d'état, not revolution): Bolsheviks exploited confusion and indecision among competing groups; used bribes, propaganda, recruited soldiers/sailors with combination of force and money
- Methodical takeover of government buildings and communication centers on October 25 with almost no resistance: government garrison didn't support the regime; most units remained neutral; resistance was "almost non-existent"
- **Professor Leonard Schapiro** (*The Russian Revolutions of 1917*) documented that Petrograd Garrison forces rejected government's call for support; only a few hundred women soldiers and around 2,000 military cadets on government's side; Bolsheviks controlled several regiments and Baltic Fleet units

### The Storming of Winter Palace Was a Myth
- Official Soviet narrative: dramatic siege of Winter Palace
- Reality: small detachment of troops led by two MRC (Military Revolutionary Committee) members entered palace around 2 A.M. on October 26; officer cadets were ordered to surrender without resistance; total casualties were three officer cadets wounded
- The palace takeover was bloodless by design; no preparation for such audacity; resistance was negligible
- Theater and restaurants remained open evening of October 25; Opera played Shaliapin in *Boris Godunov*; streets filled with well-dressed people

### Popular Support Was Not Necessary
- **Eugene Lyons** (U.S. Press correspondent in revolutionary Russia, initially sympathetic): after six years living under new regime, his book *Workers' Paradise Lost* summarized the truth—Lenin and Trotsky overthrew the first democratic society in Russian history (Kerensky's provisional government), not the Tsar
- The Bolsheviks represented the smallest of Russian radical movements; they **scoffed at numbers** and **mistrusted the multitudes**
- **Lenin's** actual view: workers would be educated *after* the revolution; they would not lead—they would be driven to "terrestrial heaven"
- Lenin sneered at competing socialist groups with their "mass base"; his motto: *"Give us an organization of professional revolutionaries"* to turn Russia upside down
- Lenin promised the state would fade away ("all need of force will vanish"), then immediately revived **Tsarist practices**: political prisoners, convictions without trial, savage persecution, suppression of all other parties, internal passports, state monopoly of press, repressive practices exceeding the Tsar's century-long model

### The Official Narrative Was False
- Standard explanation: Western financiers kept Russia in war against Germany to prevent separate German-Russian peace
- Credible reading: Western money was merely doing what it had always done—placing bets on all horses so the winner would be obligated
- **Lincoln Steffens' account** shows the motive was "re-revolution"—another round of instability to benefit financiers, not anti-Semitism or war strategy
- After October coup, Bolsheviks signed peace with Germany (**Treaty of Brest-Litovsk**) and confiscated private property—exactly what they promised all along
- Financial "masqueraders" (Thompson, Robins, etc.) later claimed they were merely trying to keep Russia in the war, but the Bolsheviks never wavered in their ideology
- The masqueraders became supporters precisely because they believed the Bolsheviks would control the new government and guarantee their commercial interests

### Wall Street's Wolves: Motives and Methods
- **Raymond Robins** (head of American Red Cross Mission in Russia): leader in **Roosevelt's "Bull Moose"** campaign (1912); anti-capitalist; hero-worshipped **Cecil Rhodes** and **Roosevelt**; now determined to convince **President Wilson** to recognize the Soviet regime
- **Bruce Lockhart** (British Agent replacing **Sir George Buchanan** as British Ambassador): described meetings with **Lord Milner** (Round Table figure, chief political adviser to **King Edward VII**), who impressed him with belief in "highly organized state, in which service, efficiency, and hard work were more important than titles or money-bags"
- Lockhart's memoirs revealed that **Robins** had promised **Lenin** a train would always be ready for him at an hour's notice—tremendous leverage over the Bolshevik leader
- When Robins dined with Lockhart before leaving Russia, Lockhart recorded: Robins had been reading **Rhodes' life** and gave "wonderful exposition of Rhodes' character"—both Lockhart and Robins were disciples of Cecil Rhodes working for identical objectives

### The Bolsheviks Granted Them Access
- Robins and Lockhart were allowed to attend meetings of the **Central Executive Committee** without restriction and were consulted on important decisions
- The Bolsheviks recognized the power these "capitalists" represented and made no pretense of excluding them
- **Cornelius Kelleher** (head of mission medical team) later reflected on naiveté of **Dr. Franklin Billings** (nominal head): the **Red Cross Mission was nothing but a mask**—the real purpose was commercial: acquiring profitable concessions from the new Communist government while maintaining the cover of humanitarianism

> The purpose of a mask is to conceal. What was behind that mask? What were the true motives and goals of the masqueraders?

