- Angry mobs in Philadelphia streets threatening legislators, looting rampant, businesses bankrupt, drunkenness and lawlessness everywhere
- The "fruit of fiat money had ripened"

> "The wheels of government are clogged, and ... we are descending into the vale of confusion and darkness." — **George Washington**, October 1785

> "No day was ever more clouded than the present. We are fast verging to anarchy." — **Washington to James Madison**, one year later

> "If any person had told me that there would have been such formidable rebellion as exists, I would have thought him fit for a madhouse." — **Washington to Henry Knox**, February 1787

### Washington on Fiat Money

> "The necessity arising from a want of specie is represented as greater than it really is. I contend that it is by the substance, not the shadow of a thing, we are to be benefited. The wisdom of man, in my humble opinion, cannot at this time devise a plan by which the credit of paper money would be long supported; consequently, depreciation keeps pace with the quantity of the emission, and articles for which it is exchanged rise in a greater ratio than the sinking value of the money. Wherein, then, is the farmer, the planter, the artisan benefited?"

- Written three months before the Convention
- Fiat money opens doors for speculation by crafty speculators preying on the community

## THE CONSTITUTIONAL CONVENTION

- Delegates adamant in their resolve to prevent any state, especially the federal government, from ever issuing fiat money again

**Oliver Ellsworth** (Connecticut, later 3rd Chief Justice):
> "This is a favorable moment to shut and bar the door against paper money. The mischief of the various experiments which have been made are now fresh in the public mind and have excited the disgust of all the respectable parts of America."

**George Mason** (Virginia):
- "Mortal hatred to paper money"
- "Paper money is founded upon fraud and knavery"

**James Wilson** (Pennsylvania):
> "It will have the most salutary influence on the credit of the United States to remove the possibility of paper money."

**John Langdon** (New Hampshire):
- Would rather reject the whole plan of federation than grant the new government the right to issue fiat money

**George Reed** (Delaware):
> "Would be as alarming as the mark of the beast in Revelation"

**Thomas Paine**:
- Called fiat money "counterfeiting by the state"
- Especially abhorred legal tender laws forcing people to accept it
> "The punishment of a member [of a legislature] who should move for such a law ought to be death"

### The Constitutional Ban on Bills of Credit

- First draft copied from Articles of Confederation, initially including power "to borrow money and emit bills of credit"
- After lively discussion, provision **voted to be removed by overwhelming margin**

**Alexander Hamilton**:
> "To emit an unfunded paper as the sign of value ought not to continue a formal part of the Constitution, nor ever hereafter to be employed; being, in its nature, repugnant with abuses and liable to be made the engine of imposition and fraud"

- Convention journal (August 16): motion to strike "and emit bills of credit" **passed by margin of better than four to one**

### Tenth Amendment Clarification

- Powers not delegated to United States by Constitution, nor prohibited to it by States, are reserved to States or to the people
- Power to issue bills of credit: **NOT delegated to United States**, **specifically prohibited to States**
- Therefore, if any power to issue fiat money legally exists at all, it is reserved for the people
- Individuals and private institutions (banks) have right to issue IOUs, but **government at any level is clearly prohibited** by Constitution

### A Suggestion for Your Congressman

- Constitution has never been amended on this point
- Provision remains: only silver and gold can be used as lawful money
- Suggestion: send copies of this section to elected representatives; ask when they intend to begin upholding their oath
- Politicians have similar problem to judges: permissible to rock the boat but not to sink it
