- Would face wrath of Establishment and bewildered public
- Until public becomes better informed, cannot expect too much from courts or Congress
- But education has to start somewhere, and Washington is an excellent place to begin

### Constitutional Monetary Powers

- Federal government given "to coin money" and "regulate the value thereof"
- Since gold and silver coin specifically defined as only allowed money, "to coin money" meant **to mint precious-metal coins. Period.**
- "Regulate the value" tied to power to determine weights and measures — same as setting standard value of mile, pound, or quart
- Traced to Articles of Confederation:

> "The United States in congress assembled shall... have the sole and exclusive right and power of regulating the alloy and value of coin struck by their own authority, or by that of the respective states —fixing the Standard of Weights and Measures throughout the United States"

- Intent: for Congress to determine exact weight of precious metal that would constitute national monetary unit

## THE ORIGIN OF THE DOLLAR

- **Spanish silver coins** (pieces of eight) already de facto monetary unit when Constitution drafted
- Continental Congress had established commission to sample circulating coins, determine average value by weight and purity
- Charts published listing coins by comparative value
- Congress already "regulating the value of" nation's money

### Etymology of the Dollar

- **Count Schlick** began striking silver coins in 1519 in **Joachim's Thal, Bavaria** ("Joachimsthalers")
- Transliterated into "thalers," then "dollars"
- American colonies adopted dollar **from Spain, not England**
- Spain's **1497 monetary reform**: silver real became Spanish money-unit
- New coin of eight reales appeared: **pesos, duros, piezas de ocho** ("pieces of eight"), or **Spanish dollars**
- Achieved predominance in New World due to Spain's commercial and political position

### Thomas Jefferson's 1785 Proposal

> "Taking into our view all money transactions, great and small, I question if a common measure, of more convenient size than the dollar, could be proposed.... The unit or dollar is a known coin, and the most familiar of all to the minds of people. It is already adopted from south to north; has identified our currency, and therefore happily offers itself as an unit already introduced"

- **July 6, 1785**: Congress unanimously voted to adopt Spanish dollar as official monetary unit
- However, coin varied in content between issues — needed way to rate one coin against another
- Jefferson: "If we determine that a dollar shall be our unit, we must then say with precision what a dollar is"

### The Coinage Act of 1792

- After examining Spanish dollars in circulation, Congress defined the dollar
- After ratification: dollar would contain **371.25 grains of fine silver**
- All items in commerce measured in value against that standard

**Alexander Hamilton** (1791 report to Congress):
- As Spanish coins reduced silver content, pressure for predictable American dollar mounted
- Urged establishment of federal mint with inviolable standard

> "The dollar originally contemplated in the money transactions of this country, by successive diminutions of its weight and fineness, has sustained a depreciation of five per cent, and yet the new dollar has a currency in all payments in place of the old, with scarcely any attention to the difference between them. The operation of this in depreciating the value of property depending upon past contracts, and ... of all other property is apparent. Nor can it require argument to prove that a nation ought not to suffer the value of the property of its citizens to fluctuate with the fluctuations of a foreign mint, or to change with the changes in the regulations of a foreign sovereign"

> "The quantity of gold and silver in the national coins, corresponding with a given sum, cannot be made less than heretofore without disturbing the balance of intrinsic value, and making every acre of land, as well as every bushel of wheat, of less actual worth than in time past.... [This] could not fail to distract the ideas of the community, and would be apt to breed discontent as well among those who live on the income of their money as among the poorer classes of the people to whom the necessities of life would ... become dearer"

## BIMETALLISM

- Hamilton referred to both **gold and silver coins**, not merely silver
- Congress considering **bimetallic coinage** at this time
- Retrospectively, a mistake — pinmetallism never worked well very long
- Always led to confusion and disappearance as money of one metal
- Subtle shifting of relative values between gold and silver due to constantly changing supply and demand
- Metal growing in value over the other will be hoarded or melted down (brings higher price as metal than as money)

### The Coinage Act of 1792 (Implementation)

- Free-market value of gold approximately **15 times the value of silver**
- **Coinage Act set ratio at 15-to-1**
- Authorized federal mint to coin **Eagles** (gold coins) valued at ten dollars
- Gold coins equal in value to ten silver coins
- Ten silver coins (each 371.25 grains fine silver) = **3,712.5 grains total**
- Eagle content: **one-fifteenth that amount = 247.5 grains fine gold**

### What Congress Actually Did

- Did **NOT** create a "gold dollar" (didn't do that until 1849)
- Reaffirmed "money of account of United States shall be expressed in dollars or units" = coins containing 371.25 grains pure silver
- What Congress did: authorize minting of gold coin and **arbitrarily fix value of gold** in that coin at fifteen times the value of the dollar
- All silver and gold coins produced in federal mint were legal tender in accordance with their value, based on weight and purity, relative to silver dollar standard
- **Death penalty** for anyone who debases the nation's coinage (would wipe out House, Senate, Treasury management, and Presidency if enforced today)

## FREE COINAGE

- Most important provision: establishment of **free coinage**
- Any citizen may take raw silver or gold to mint and, for nominal fee, have it converted into coins
- Government merely performs technical function of creating coin and stamping insignia to certify correct weight and purity
- State's role: same as inspecting scales in grocery store or meter on gasoline pump
- Merely fulfilling Constitutional requirement to set standards and verify accuracy of weights and measures
- Free coinage lasted until **Gold Reserve Act of 1934**, which terminated it and made it illegal for citizens to possess gold

**Elgin Groseclose**:
> "The principle of free coinage has proved its practical worth as a deterrent to debasement and depreciation. Where coinage is on private account there is no profit to the state in tampering with the standard, and there is no opportunity for such practice by the individual. The circulation of coins of similar appearance and denomination but of uncertain standard, the arbitrary and unpredictable modifications in the standard by autocratic government, the temptations to profit which were constantly dangled before despotic rulers —these were evils which had perplexed and harassed society and hindered the natural growth of economy since the days when coined money first appeared. By a stroke they were swept away. At the same time, the institution of free coinage, by giving stability and character to one of the chief instruments of organized economy, made possible a more vigorous and healthy commercial life and gave prestige and increased substance to the government adopting it"

## SOUND MONEY AND ECONOMIC PROSPERITY

### Immediate Results

**Pennsylvania Gazette**, December 16, 1789:
> "Since the federal constitution has removed all danger of our having a paper tender, our trade is advanced fifty per cent"

- **Douglass North**: "The years 1793-1808, were years of unparalleled prosperity"
- **Louis Hacker**: "One of unexampled business expansion, one of the greatest, in fact, the United States has had.... The exports of the country mounted from $19 millions in 1791 to $93 millions in 1801"
- Federal deficit: 28% of expenditures in 1792, dropped to 21% in 1795
- By 1802, deficit disappeared altogether, replaced by surplus almost as large as government's total spending

### George Washington's Assessment

**To Catherine Macaulay Graham**:
> "The United States enjoys a sense of prosperity and tranquility under the new government that could hardly have been hoped for"

**To David Humphreys** (American poet and diplomat):
> "Our public credit stands on that high ground which three years ago it would have been considered as a species of madness to have foretold"

**On paper money without gold/silver backing**:
> "We may one day become a great commercial and flourishing nation. But if in the pursuit of the means we should unfortunately stumble again on unfunded paper money or any similar species of fraud, we shall assuredly give a fatal stab to our national credit in its infancy"

### The Monetary Blueprint

- Founders laid down monetary blueprint
- Only flaw: attempt to set fixed ratio between gold and silver value
- Rather than placing dollar value on gold coin, mint should have imprinted gold value in terms of weight and fineness
- Free market would have assigned exchange value in terms of goods and services, automatically determining correct monetary value as ratio to silver dollars bidding for same items
- Inevitable: soon after "ten-dollar" Eagle created, value of gold over silver began climbing higher than 15-to-1 ratio
- Eagles ceased to circulate
- With discovery of great gold fields in California and Australia, process reversed, and silver dollars disappeared from commerce
- **Bimetallism led to discrepancy** between actual conversion ratio and government-prescribed ratio
- Nevertheless, took place in open market and no one greatly injured
- Throughout it all, just one standard: **the defined silver content of a dollar**
- Both silver and gold coins were of intrinsic value and totally honest in their measure

## SUMMARY

- Constitution prohibits both states and federal government from issuing fiat money
- Deliberate intent of Founding Fathers who had bitter experience with fiat money before and during Revolutionary War
- In response to need for precisely defined national monetary unit, Congress adopted **Spanish dollar** then in use
- Defined content of dollar: **371.25 grains of pure silver**
- With establishment of federal mint, American silver dollars issued in accordance with that standard
- **Gold Eagles** produced, equal in value to ten silver dollars
- Most importantly, **free coinage** established: Americans able to convert raw silver and gold into national coins officially certified as to intrinsic value
- Product: **period of sound money and great economic prosperity**
- Period came to end only when next generation of Americans forgot to read their history and returned to paper money and "bills of credit"

### The Founding Fathers' Collective Genius

- Monetary plan laid down by Founding Fathers was product of **collective genius**
- Nowhere in history can one find so many men in one legislative body who understood:
  - The fraud inherent in fiat money
  - The hidden-taxation nature of inflation
- Never such assembly of scholars and statesmen determined to set safe course for the nation
- Literally handed us a **treasure map**
- All we had to do was follow it to economic security and national prosperity
- But map was discarded when lessons of history died out with those who had lived it

## Chapter Sixteen: THE CREATURE COMES TO AMERICA

### Bank of North America (First Central Bank)

- United States had first central bank **before Constitution was drafted**
- Chartered by Continental Congress, Spring 1781, opened following year
- Great expectations Canada would join rebel colonies to form union across entire North American continent
- Named in anticipation: **Bank of North America**

### Robert Morris and the Bank's Organization

- Organized by **Robert Morris**, member of Congress
- Leader of group of politicians and merchants wanting new nation to imitate **mercantilism of England**
- Wanted: high taxes, powerful centralized government, high tariffs to subsidize domestic industry, large army and navy, acquisition of colonial outposts
- Wealthy Philadelphia merchant who profited greatly from war contracts during Revolution
- Had carefully studied the secret science of money
- By 1781, widely considered **financial wizard of Congress**

### Modeled After Bank of England

- Closely modeled after Bank of England
- Following fractional reserve, allowed to issue paper promissory notes in excess of actual deposits
- Some gold and silver had to be held in vault, but definite limits to how far that could go
- Bank notes **not forced on people as legal tender** for all debts, public and private
- But government agreed to accept them at face value for payment of all taxes and duties (made them as good as gold for that purpose)
- Unlike central banks of today, **not given power to directly issue the nation's money**

### Functioned as a Central Bank

- Given **right of monopoly** in its field (no other bank notes allowed to circulate in competition)
- Accepted at face value for payment of all federal and state taxes
- Federal government had no functioning money of its own at that time
- Made bank notes attractive for use as circulating medium of exchange
- Intended result: Bank's paper would be accepted as money (for a while, it was)
- Made **official depository for all federal funds**
- Almost immediately loaned $1.2 million to government, much created out of nothing
- Despite limitations and being private institution, intended to be and did function as **central bank**

### Fraud from the Very Start

- Charter required private investors provide $400,000 for initial subscription
- When Morris unable to raise that money, used political influence to make up shortfall from government funds
- In maneuver nothing less than legalized embezzlement: took gold loaned to United States from France, deposited it in the Bank
- Using this as fractional-reserve base, **created the money needed for subscription and loaned it to himself and associates**
- Such is the power of the secret science

### Short Life

- Hard to reconcile that same men who adopted brilliant monetary restraints of Constitution few years later would have allowed Bank of North America to exist
- Must be remembered: war still in progress when charter issued
- Even wisest statesmen often obliged to follow expediency in such times
- Founding fathers wise on nature of fiat money created by government's printing press, but had not yet had extensive experience with same mechanism hidden behind obscurities of fractional-reserve banking

**Murray Rothbard** on the Bank's demise:
> "Despite the monopoly privileges conferred upon the Bank of North America and its nominal redeemability in specie, the market's lack of confidence in the inflated notes led to their depreciation outside the Bank's home base in Philadelphia. The Bank even tried to bolster the value of its notes by hiring people to urge redeemers of its notes not to insist on specie —a move scarcely calculated to improve the long-run confidence in the Bank"

- After year of operation, Morris's political power slipped
- Moved quickly to shift Bank of North America from central bank to purely commercial bank chartered by state of Pennsylvania
- By end of 1783, **first experiment with central bank in United States had ended**

### Epilogue

- Fitting epilogue: 1980, First Pennsylvania Bank of Philadelphia (oldest bank in the nation) was **bailed out by FDIC**

## AN END RUN AROUND THE CONSTITUTION

- After Bank of North America terminated and Constitutional Convention "closed the door on paper money," United States enjoyed **period of unparalleled economic growth and prosperity**
- But while door may have been closed, **window was still open**
- Congress denied power to print money, but **not denied power to borrow it**

### The Confusion of Banking Vocabulary

- In vocabulary of common man, to borrow is to accept loan of something that already exists
- Confused when banker issues money out of nothing and then says he is lending it
- Appears to be lending but, in reality, is **creating**
- Mysteries of banking vocabulary not revealed to average man
- Difficult to understand how privately-issued bank notes could serve precisely same purpose as printing-press money — with precisely same disastrous results
- Monetary and political scientists decided to end run the Constitution
- Plan: establish bank, give that bank power to create money, lend most of that money to government, then make sure IOUs are accepted as money by public
- Congress, therefore, would not be emitting bills of credit. The bank would do that

### First Bank of the United States Conceived

- Proposal submitted to Congress in 1790 by **Alexander Hamilton**, then Secretary of Treasury
- Hamilton incidentally was former aide to Robert Morris, founder of Bank of North America
- In that sense, his role not surprising
- **What is surprising**: Hamilton had been staunch supporter of sound currency during Constitutional Convention
- Hard to reconcile
- Must suspect even most well intentioned of men can become corrupted by temptations of wealth and power
- Possible that Hamilton, Morris, and other Federalist leaders hoped to keep government out of money-making business, not because constitutional, but because that would leave field clear for **central-bank mechanism** which, being further from public view and political control, could become their own private engine of profit
- Only other explanation: these men were fickle in their views and did not really understand implications of their acts
- In view of their brilliance in all other matters, difficult to muster enthusiasm for that interpretation

<!-- pp. 381-400 -->

## Chapter 16 (continued): The Creature Comes to Europe

### Structure of the First Bank of the United States

- Bank granted monopoly on issuing bank notes
- Notes not legal tender for private debts, but accepted for government taxes/duties
- Bank made official depository for all federal funds
- Required to redeem notes in gold/silver on demand, but not required to hold full specie reserves — mathematical impossibility
- 80% capitalized by private investors, 20% by federal government
- Federal "investment" was prearranged loan-back to government — **Robert Morris scheme** repeated
- **Jefferson**: This was "an outright gift," not a loan or investment
- Total capitalization $10 million, but **John Kenneth Galbraith** noted bank opened with only ~$675,000 in hard cash
- **Thomas Willing** (president) had voted against Declaration of Independence in Continental Congress

### The Rothschild Connection

- Private investors' names not published, but included Congressmen and Senators who engineered the charter
- **Galbraith** cryptic hint: "Foreigners could own shares but not vote them"
- **Rothschild banking dynasty** was dominant force financially and politically in formation of Bank of the United States
- **Derek Wilson** (biographer): Rothschilds bought cotton from Southern states, made loans to states, served as official European banker for US government, pledged support for Bank
- **Gustavus Myers** (*History of the Great American Fortunes*): "Law records show they were the power in the old Bank of the United States"
- The Creature from Jekyll Island descended from non-native species

### Inflation Under the First Bank

- Primary purpose: create money for federal government (private sector secondary)
- Maximum interest rate 6% made private lending impractical — only viable for government and prime borrowers
- Government "invested" $2 million, then borrowed $8.2 million within five years
- $6.2 million created specifically for government use
- **Fractional-reserve inflation**: new dollars pushed into economy through government spending
- Wholesale prices rose 72% in five years = **42% confiscation** of savings through hidden tax
- Same inflation pattern as colonial printing-press money, but now caused by fractional-reserve mechanism
- Federal debt linked printing press and fractional reserve into one system

> "I wish it were possible to obtain a single amendment to our Constitution. I would be willing to depend on that alone for the reduction of the administration of our government to the general principle of the Constitution; I mean an additional article, taking from the federal government their power of borrowing." — **Thomas Jefferson** to John Taylor, November 26, 1789

### Mixed Assessment of the First Bank

- Not all bad — state governments had destroyed purchasing power with paper money in colonial times
- Bank required to maintain some gold/specie reserves — provided boundary on money expansion
- Bank directors showed enlightened self-interest: wanted to keep economy productive enough to support the system
- Spoke language of restraint; sometimes acted with restraint
- Like Federal Reserve today: didn't want to kill the goose that laid the golden egg

### Wildcat Banks

- Flourished during this period
- Named for remote frontier locations ("only customers were wildcats"), not for being untamed
- Required to keep portion of deposits as gold/silver coin
- Kept vault door open with visible gold kegs during business hours to project confidence
- Some rushed gold from vault to vault ahead of state examiners
- **Bank of the United States restraint**: refused to accept notes from banks without reputation for specie redemption
- Public reacted accordingly — created indirect moderating force on all banks

### The "Lender of Last Resort" Fallacy

- **Galbraith** praised Bank for assisting "good state banks" besieged by creditors
- Author's counterpoint: If state banks were "good," why did they need rescue?
- "Lender of last resort" doctrine assumes entire banking system should be fraudulent
- Free market would force moderation: honest banks would gain reputation and prosperity
- Dishonest banks would have to reform or fail
- **Only politicians and bureaucrats** would believe only government can act with integrity

### An Instrument of Plutocracy

- Bank caused 42% value confiscation in five years
- Inflation selective: hit those unable to ride wave aboard tangible property
- Did not work against wealthy classes with tangible assets
- **Elite profited**: political and monetary scientists making huge gains
- Bank fulfilled **Hamilton's** vision: "unite the interest and credit of rich individuals with those of the state"

> "The rich will strive to establish their dominion and enslave the rest. They always did. They always will.... The result of the contest will be a violent aristocracy, or a more violent despotism." — **Governeur Morris** (Constitutional Convention delegate, assistant to Robert Morris), July 2, 1787

### Political Opposition to Charter Renewal

- **Jeffersonian Republicans**: opposed as unconstitutional, wanted gold/silver only
- **Wildcatters, land speculators, empire-building industrialists**: opposed any restraints, wanted unlimited fractional-reserve money creation
- Battle lines equal force — Congress deadlocked
- Charter renewal defeated by one vote in House, one vote in Senate (VP **George Clinton** tie-breaker)
- Bank closed January 24, 1811

### After the Bank Closed

- Wildcatters took over — banking passed to state-chartered corporations
- Numbers grew rapidly, money supply expanded
- Inflation followed, public dissatisfaction rose
- Free market could have weeded out wildcatters and restored balance, but **War of 1812** intervened

## Chapter 16 (continued): The War of 1812

### The Real Cause

- Official story: British impressment of American sailors
- Reality: French did same thing to assist war against England (ignored)
- British rescinded impressment policy before war began — cause already removed
- Peace could have been restored if Congress wanted
- **Conclusion**: pro-banking interests wanted war for profit potential
- Evidence: New England states (home of impressed seamen) opposed war; Western/Southern states (home of wildcat banks) supported war

### Government-Bank Alliance for War Funding

- War unpopular — impossible to fund through tax increases
- Government needed state banks to create money, banks needed government protection from market discipline
- **Unholy alliance**: cabal between political and monetary scientists
- **Murray Rothbard**: Government encouraged massive bank expansion to purchase war debt
- New inflationary banks (Middle Atlantic, Southern, Western states) printed enormous quantities to buy government bonds
- Federal government used these notes to buy arms and goods in New England

### The Suspension of Specie Payment (August 1814)

- Banks outside New England insolvent — could not pay in specie
- Rather than let banks fail, governments (state and federal) allowed suspension of specie redemption
- Banks allowed to refuse contractual obligations
- **Highly inflationary** and set precedent for all future financial crises
- Message to banks: inflate together, get bailed out together
- Federal debt rose from $45 million to $127 million
- Money supply tripled with no increase in goods
- Dollar shrank to one-third former purchasing power by 1814
- When depositors demanded gold, banks closed doors, hired guards to protect officials
- **66% confiscation** of money holdings during War of 1812 period (on top of earlier 42% from First Bank)

## Chapter 17: A Den of Vipers

### Post-War Chaos

- Monetary chaos caused by universal fraud in banking
- Depositors placed gold/silver in banks for safekeeping and paper convenience
- Banks promised specie redemption on demand
- Through fractional-reserve banking, created far more paper than coins in reserve
- When significant percentage requested withdrawal, promise could not be kept

### Jefferson's Retirement Lament

> "I have ever been the enemy of banks; not of those discounting for cash [charging interest on real money], but of those foisting their own paper into circulation, and thus banishing our cash. My zeal against those institutions was so warm and open at the establishment of the bank of the U.S. that I was derided as a Maniac by the tribe of bank-mongers, who were seeking to filch from the public their swindling and barren gains.... Shall we build an altar to the old paper money of the revolution, which ruined individuals but saved the republic, and burn on that all the bank charters present and future, and their notes with them? For these are to ruin both republic and individuals. This cannot be done. The Mania is too strong. It has seized by its delusions and corruptions all the members of our governments general, special, and individual." — **Thomas Jefferson** to John Adams

### Congress Protects the Banks (1816)

- Congress lacked wisdom and courage to let free market clean up mess
- If free market allowed: fraud would become understood, dishonest banks would fold, losses taken, suffering ended
- Instead: Congress moved to protect banks, organize fraud, perpetuate losses
- **Second Bank of the United States** chartered 1816 (twenty-year charter)

### The Second Bank of the United States

- Carbon copy of first Bank, including fraud
- Congress extracted $1.5 million bribe for "exclusive privileges and benefits"
- Bankers paid gladly — modest price for profitable enterprise
- Received immediate government deposit of one-fifth total capitalization
- Used as base for manufacturing remaining startup capital
- Charter required minimum $7 million in specie, but even in second year never rose above $2.5 million
- **Rothschild influence**: largest single block of stock (one-third) held by foreign investors rooted in Britain

### Early Troubles

- Promised moderation by refusing notes from banks not redeemable in specie
- When other banks demanded Bank pay out specie, frequently lost resolve
- Corruption: "So many influential people were interested [as stockholders] that it was not advisable to give offense by demanding payment in specie, and borrowers were anxious to keep the banks in the humor to lend"
- Loose monetary policy introduced first boom-bust cycle experience

### The 1816 Postwar Boom

- **Galbraith**: "In 1816, the postwar boom was full on; there was especially active speculation in western lands. The new Bank joyously participated"
- Federal charter plus government tax-payment acceptance gave Bank advantage
- State banks still created money through fractional-reserve banking, inflating currency
- Pennsylvania chartered 37 new banks in 1817
- Kentucky chartered 40 new banks same year
- Total banks grew 46% in first two years after central bank created
- Money supply expanded $27.4 million — **another 40%+ taxpayer fleecing**

### The First Boom-Bust Cycle

- Monetary scientists now controlled money machine
- **Gradualism replaced by catastrophism**: expansion then deliberate contraction
- "Why wait for apples to fall when harvest can be hastened by shaking the tree?"
- 1818: Bank suddenly tightened loan requirements, called in old loans
- Justified as necessary to brake inflation (same inflation Bank helped create)
- Many bankers and politicians acted in good faith but didn't understand the system
- Like Frankenstein: created monster without realizing they couldn't control it
- Whether innocence or malice, end result the same

### The Contraction and First Depression

- **Rothbard**: Starting July 1818, government and Bank saw dire straits
- Massive fraud put Bank in danger of failing to maintain specie payments
- Over next year: enormous contractions, forced curtailment of loans, contractions of credit in South and West
- Contraction of money and credit brought **first widespread economic and financial depression**
- **First nationwide "boom-bust" cycle** arrived in United States
- Result: defaults, bankruptcies, liquidation of unsound investments

### Government Interference Worsens Cycles

- Panics, boom-bust cycles, depressions caused by unbridled bank competition is widespread belief — justifies need for regulation
- **Truth is opposite**: disruptions result from government prevention of competition through monopolistic central bank
- Without monopoly: individual banks operate fraudulently only briefly before exposure by honest competitors
- Depositors injured by bankruptcy, but damage limited to relatively few
- Even geographical regions hard hit occasionally, but not national tragedy
- Overall economy absorbs losses, commerce continues
- Prosperity environment allows rapid recovery even for fraud victims
- **With central bank protecting fraudulent operators**: all banks function the same, competition forces eliminated
- Expansion universal and gigantic; contraction universal and gigantic
- Everyone injured simultaneously; depression everywhere; recovery long delayed

### The Panic of 1819

- **Herman Krooss**: Bank as largest creditor had two alternatives:
  1. Write off debts (wipe out stockholders, result in bankruptcy)
  2. Force state banks to meet obligations (wholesale bankruptcy among state banks)
- Pressure on state banks deflated economy drastically
- Money supply wilted, country sank into severe depression
- **William Gouge** (historian): "The Bank was saved, and the people were ruined"

### Political Competition Replaces Market Competition

- Competition moved from open free market to closed political arena
- Free-market competition replaced by government favoritism through charters
- Federal charter better than state charter
- States fought back: began taxing paper notes issued by any non-locally-chartered bank
- Intent: raise state revenue (pretense); reality: put federal Bank out of business

### McCulloch v. Maryland (1819)

- Bank refused to pay Maryland tax
- Case reached Supreme Court
- Chief Justice **John Marshall**: leading Federalist, advocate of strong centralized federal government
- Marshall Court tailored decision to support federal government's central bank
- Narrow issue: not whether Congress could directly/indirectly emit bills of credit or convert debt into money
- Court would have been hard pressed to uphold Bank on that question (expressly prohibited by Constitution)
- Instead focused on whether Bank was "necessary and proper" means for Congress to execute other constitutional powers
- Unanimously held Bank constitutional from that perspective
- **Technical distinction**: Bank's paper notes backed by Bank credit, not federal government
- Bank created money, most used by government
- Never mind government couldn't create money directly — Court approved indirect route

<!-- pp. 401-420 -->

## Chapter Seventeen (continued): Return of the Monster

### Constitutional Justifications for the Bank

- Supreme Court ruled Bank was constitutional in **McCulloch v. Maryland**, despite **Marshall's** circular logic
- Bank defenders argued it wasn't government money because Treasury didn't print it
- States couldn't tax the Bank because "the power to tax is the power to destroy" (Marshall)
- Author's view: constitutional end-run by men who should have defended the Constitution most

### The 1820s Shift Toward Sound Money

- Public opinion shifted back to **laissez-faire** and **sound-money principles** during 1820s
- **Jeffersonian Republicans** had abandoned these principles by then
- New coalition formed: **Martin Van Buren** and **Andrew Jackson** created the **Democratic Party**
- Primary platform: abolish the Bank of the United States
- After **Jackson's** 1828 election, he moved immediately to build Congressional support

### Nicholas Biddle

- **Nicholas Biddle** became Bank director — formidable adversary to Jackson
- Wealthy, arrogant, ruthless, brilliant
- Graduated **University of Pennsylvania** at age thirteen
- "Fully mastered the secret science of money" as young businessman
- Became one of America's most powerful men through control of nation's credit

> "Never. There are very few banks which might not have been destroyed by an exertion of the powers of the Bank. None has ever been injured." —Nicholas Biddle, testifying before Senate

- Admission that state banks existed at the pleasure of the Bank of the United States (and thus at Biddle's pleasure)

### Biddle's Strategic Move: Early Recharter

- Bank's charter good until 1836 (four more years)
- **Biddle** requested early renewal in 1832 to soften Jackson's reelection campaign
- Reasoning: Jackson would hesitate to oppose Bank renewal during campaign to avoid losing votes
- Bill backed by Republicans led by **Senator John Clay**, passed July 3, 1832

### Jackson Overrides Congress

- **Jackson** placed entire political career on the line for this issue
- Delivered one of most passionate veto messages ever sent to Congress
- **Robert Remini** (biographer): "The veto message hit the nation like a tornado"

> "The veto message hit the nation like a tornado. For it not only cited constitutional arguments against recharter—supposedly the only reason for resorting to a veto—but political, social, economic, and nationalistic reasons as well." —Robert Remini

### Jackson's Three Main Veto Arguments

**1. Injustice of Government-Sponsored Monopoly**
- Stock owned only by richest citizens
- Stock sale limited to chosen few with political influence
- Common man excluded from opportunity, forced to pay more than fair value for banking services
- **Eight million dollars** of Bank stock held by foreigners
- Only few hundred U.S. citizens (richest class) held the rest

> "More than eight millions of the stock of this bank are held by foreigners... It appears that more than a fourth part of the stock is held by foreigners and the residue is held by a few hundred of our own citizens, chiefly of the richest class." —Andrew Jackson

**2. Constitutionality Question**
- Jackson not bound by Supreme Court's previous decision
- President and Congress have equal right to decide constitutionality
- **Founding fathers** created government with power divided between executive, legislative, and judicial branches
- Purpose: balance branches against each other, not make government efficient but deliberately inefficient
- Each President and legislator morally bound by oath to uphold Constitution
- If they can't decide what's constitutional, taking oath has little meaning

**3. Foreign Control Danger**
- Major portion of stockholders were foreigners
- Foreign investors couldn't vote shares, but American investors were beholden to them
- Bank controlled currency, received public monies, held citizens in dependence

> "Is there no danger to our liberty and independence in a bank that in its nature has so little to bind it to our country?... Controlling our currency, receiving our public monies, and holding thousands of our citizens in dependence, it would be more formidable and dangerous than a naval and military power of the enemy." —Andrew Jackson

### Jackson's Populist Appeal

- Spoke directly to voters, not just Congress — unprecedented in American politics
- Declared war on "moneyed aristocracy" invading Congress halls
- Called Bank a "hydra-headed monster eating the flesh of the common man"
- Campaign message: "Bank and no Jackson, or no bank and Jackson!"
- Traveled making speeches, paid expenses in gold coins

> "No more paper money, you see, fellow citizens, if I can only put down this Nicholas Biddle and his monster bank." —Andrew Jackson (paying expenses in gold)

- Positioned gold as safe/sound currency vs. paper money as instrument of banks and swindlers
- **1832 election results**: Jackson won 55% popular vote (Clay 37%, Wirt 8%), 80% electoral college

### Jackson Removes Federal Deposits

- After election, Jackson ordered **William Duane** (Secretary of Treasury) to move federal deposits to state banks
- Pay current expenses from Bank funds until drained to zero
- Strategy: without federal money, the monster would perish
- **Duane** balked, believing it would disrupt economy
- **Duane** refused to resign (constitutional question: does dismissal require Senate approval?)
- Jackson fired him anyway: "Your further services as Secretary of the Treasury are no longer required" (October 1, 1833)

> "I have it chained. I am ready with the screws to draw every tooth and then the stumps. If I am not mistaken, we will have Mr. Biddle and his Bank as quiet and harmless as a lamb in six weeks." —Andrew Jackson

### Biddle Deliberately Creates Monetary Chaos

- **Biddle** responded by contracting money supply to create panic-depression
- Plan: blame economic chaos on Jackson's withdrawal of deposits
- Resulting backlash would force Congress to override veto
- **Biddle** initiated "general curtailment of loans throughout the entire banking system"
- Business had been expanding on Bank's easy credit, now dependent on it
- Tariff came due simultaneously, increasing cash demand
- Losses everywhere: wages/prices sagged, unemployment rose, companies bankrupted
- By December Congress reconvened, nation in uproar — newspapers editorialized alarm
- Public blamed Jackson for removing deposits; blamed **Duane's** dismissal

> "This worthy President thinks that because he has scalped Indians and imprisoned Judges, he is to have his way with the Bank. He is mistaken." —Nicholas Biddle

> "The ties of party allegiance can only be broken by the actual conviction of existing distress in the community... Nothing but widespread suffering will produce any effect on Congress... Our only safety is in pursuing a steady course of firm restriction—and I have no doubt that such a course will ultimately lead to restoration of the currency and the recharter of the Bank." —Nicholas Biddle

- **Biddle's** strategy: use American people as sacrificial pawns for Bank's survival
- Economic chaos executed at particularly vulnerable moment (business expansion dependent on credit, tariff due)

### Jackson Is Censured by the Senate

- For 100 days, "phalanx of orators" excoriated Jackson
- Resolution of censure introduced, passed March 28, 1834 (26 to 20)
- First time President ever censured by Congress
- Savage blow to Jackson's pride
- **Biddle** had the upper hand

> "You are a den of vipers. I intend to rout you out and by the Eternal God I will rout you out." —Andrew Jackson (to Bank supporters delegation)

- Censure not indicative of popular sentiment
- Even in Senate (pro-Bank hotbed), swing of only three votes would have defeated measure

### Public Turns Against Biddle

- Public gradually learned the truth about **Biddle's** deliberate economic disruption
- **Biddle's** ego so large he boasted publicly about plan to disrupt economy
- Turning point: **Governor George Wolf** of Pennsylvania (Bank's home state) publicly denounced both Bank and **Biddle**
- With Pennsylvania turned against it, no one left to defend Bank
- Mood of country and Congress changed within days

### House Resolutions Support Jackson

- Democrats tested strength April 4, 1834 with House votes
- Three resolutions aimed at nullifying Senate censure:
  1. Bank "ought not to be rechartered" (134 to 82)
  2. Deposits "ought not to be restored" (118 to 103)
  3. Establish committee to investigate whether Bank deliberately instigated crisis (175 to 42)
- Overwhelming victory for Jackson

### Biddle Defies Congress

- Investigating committee arrived at Bank in Philadelphia with subpoena
- **Biddle** flatly refused to open books or allow inspection of correspondence with Congressmen about personal loans
- Steadfastly refused to testify before committee in Washington
- Lesser mortals would face contempt citations, fines, imprisonment
- Not **Nicholas Biddle**

### Bank's Final Years

- Bank mortally wounded by this time
- Jackson had completely paid off **War of 1812** national debt, even ran surplus
- Treasury returned $35+ million to states for public works construction
- Victory over Bank earned Jackson "undying hatred of monetary scientists"
- **January 30, 1835**: assassination attempt on Jackson (both pistols misfired)
- First assassination attempt on U.S. President
- Would-be assassin **Richard Lawrence** found not guilty by insanity (later boasted of European connections promising protection)

### Bank's Demise

- Bank's charter expired 1836, restructured as state bank by **Commonwealth of Pennsylvania**
- After speculation in cotton, lavish advances to officers, suspension of specie payment, **Biddle** arrested and charged with fraud
- Not convicted, but undergoing civil litigation when he died
- Within five years, establishment forced to close doors
- America's third central banking experience ended

### Some Bad Mixed in With the Good

- Author acknowledges Jackson's coalition included groups opposing Bank for less admirable reasons
- State banks and frontier business interests also opposed Constitutional money — wanted opposite
- Viewed federal Bank's modest restraints as excessive
- With federal Bank gone, anticipated no restraints at all
- Ironic: this group (not hard-money Jacksonians) ultimately got what it wanted

### Jackson's Transformation of American Politics

- Jackson changed American politics more than any President before him (rivaled by few since)
- Led nation away from **founding fathers'** concept of diffused powers toward Old-World concentration and monarchy
- Challenged states' right to secede, setting motion concept leading to Civil War
- Ended states' ability to check expanding federal power
- Union no longer based on consent of governed, but on force of arms
- Manipulated voter passion on Bank issue, changing President's role from public servant to national leader

### The Electoral College System

- Jackson declared "The President is the direct representative of the people"
- Original Constitution: President elected indirectly by state legislatures, not voters
- **Founding fathers** wanted no kings after fighting **King George III**
- Realized elected ruler, unless power limited and diffused, can become despotic as unelected one
- **Article 2, Section 1**: established **electoral college** to select President
- College members appointed by states
- Congressmen, Senators, federal officers specifically excluded
- College selects President based on integrity and executive ability, not party/politics/charisma
- Intended President would have different constituency from Congress
- Difference important to ensure balance of power
- Truly brilliant political engineering to keep government under control

### 1832 Election Changed Everything

- Jackson's fight against Bank was good cause that established bad precedent
- One of history's sad facts: good causes often establish bad precedents

### Summary

- Government encouraged banking fraud during **War of 1812**, leaving nation in monetary chaos
- Instead of letting fraudulent banks fail and free market heal damage, Congress protected banks, organized fraud, perpetuated losses
- Created nation's third central bank: **Second Bank of the United States**
- Nearly exact copy of previous bank
- Authorized to create money for federal government and regulate state banks
- Influenced larger amounts of capital, better organized across state lines
- Greater impact on money supply creation/extinguishing
- First time effects ricocheted across entire country at once (age of boom-bust cycle arrived in America)

### Return to Sound Money Movement

- 1820 public opinion swung toward sound-money principles (Jeffersonian Republicans)
- Republican Party had abandoned those principles
- New coalition formed: **Martin Van Buren** and **Andrew Jackson** (Democratic Party)
- Primary platform: abolish the Bank
- After Jackson's 1828 election, began in earnest

### The Battle

- Bank head: **Nicholas Biddle** (formidable adversary)
- Great personal abilities, many Congressmen indebted to him for business favors
- Bank had many political friends
- As Jackson's first term neared end, **Biddle** requested early charter renewal
- Hoped Jackson wouldn't risk controversy in reelection year
- Bill easily passed, Jackson vetoed
- Bank's future became primary presidential campaign issue
- Jackson reelected by large margin
- First acts: remove federal deposits, place in private regional banks
- **Biddle** counterattacked by contracting credit and calling in loans
- Calculated to shrink money supply and trigger national panic-depression
- Blamed downturn on Jackson's deposit removal
- Plan almost worked
- **Biddle's** political allies succeeded in having Jackson officially censured in Senate
- When truth about **Biddle's** strategy leaked, it backfired
- Called before Congressional investigative committee to explain
- Censure against Jackson rescinded
- Nation's third central bank passed into oblivion

## Chapter Eighteen: Loaves and Fishes and Civil War

### Post-Bank Monetary Reforms (1836)

- April 1836: Administration pushed monetary reforms through Congress
- Required all banks to cease issuing paper notes under five dollars (later increased to twenty dollars)
- Purpose: compel return to gold and silver coin for everyday use
- Bank notes reserved for large commercial transactions
- White House announced future federal land sales require "lawful money" (precious-metal coins)

### Banking Still Alive Despite Bank's Death

- Bank of United States dead, but banking very much alive
- Jackson's enemies also alive
- Hard-money measures insufficient to usher in millennium
- Inadequate by themselves
- Soon circumvented by new banking techniques
- Eventually dismantled by fickle Congress

### The Problem with Restricting Bank Notes

- Excellent concept but legislators misunderstood (or pretended not to understand) reality
- Banks increasingly dealing with **checkbook money** (technically **demand deposits**)
- People gradually became accustomed to transferring funds via checks
- Importance of bank notes declined
- Placing limit on bank note issuance without restricting demand deposit creation was futile

### The Boom of 1837

- 1837: nation at tail end of economic boom
- **Professor Rothbard**: expansion and accompanying inflation "fueled by the central bank"
- Total money in circulation risen 84% in just four years
- Then fractional-reserve banking portion (backed by nothing) began to contract
- 16% of nation's money totally disappeared in first year
- Men out of work, businesses bankrupt, homes and savings lost
- Many banks folded, operators walked away with spoils
- Only depositors left holding empty bag

### Proposals for Banking Stability

- Numerous proposals advanced for infusing banking stability
- None dealt with real problem: fractional-reserve banking itself
- **Groseclose** observed: proposals were "each according to a particular theory of how to multiply loaves and fishes, or how to make candy wool"
- Proposals presented then identical to ones offered today
- Each was actually tried, appropriate to inquire into actual results

### Four Schools of Thought on Monetary Stability

**1. Base Money on Bank Assets**
- Creation of money limited to ratio of bank's assets
- Formula tried in New England states
- Massachusetts example: bank notes limited to 2x capital actually held in vault
- Must be strictly gold or silver coin (not paper money, bonds, securities, debt instruments)
- Banks limited in small-denomination notes
- Massachusetts served as model for Jackson's attempted reform
- By previous standards and today's standards, exceptionally conservative policy
- During War of 1812 stress, Massachusetts banks (and most New England banks) maintained full payment in specie

**Limitations of Asset-Based System**
- Over time, limit on bank notes became less important (checkbook money instead)
- Paper notes may have been limited to 200% capital, but no effective limit on checkbook entries
- "Fraction" in fractional-reserve banking began to shrink again
- 1837 monetary contraction "was like a scythe over the crop"
- 32 Massachusetts banks collapsed between 1837 and 1844
- State attempted patches: bank examiners, increased stockholder liability
- Underlying problem still ignored
- New crop of banks sprang into existence, new speculative mania swept economy
- By 1862: law still limited bank notes to 2x capital, but banks created $73,685,000 total money including checkbook money
- Supported by base of only $9,595,000 specie (reserve of only 13%)
- Massachusetts had not solved the problem

**2. Protect Deposits with a Safety Fund**
- Create "safety fund" to aid any bank member needing emergency loan to cover reserve drain
- Forerunner of today's **Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation** and related agencies
- First safety fund: New York, 1829
- Law required each bank contribute 0.5% to 1% of capital stock until total reached 3%
- First tested during 1837 crisis, almost swamped
- Only thing that saved it: state agreed to accept worthless notes of defunct banks as payment for canal tolls
- Taxpayers compelled to make up difference
- When fund exhausted, solvent banks punished by being forced to pay for insolvent ones' deficits

**Result of Safety Fund System**
- Impelled all banks to act more recklessly
- Upside: profits would be higher (for a time)
- Downside: if recklessness caused trouble, safety fund would bail them out
- System provided penalty for prudence and incentive for recklessness
- Perfect parallel to banking system today
- **Groseclose**: "The conservatively managed institutions, lending upon the safer risks, upon which naturally the margins of profit were smaller, found the assessments burdensome, and were compelled to embark upon the more speculative business in order to carry the charges"
- Gradually all banks sank into quagmire
- 1857: Massachusetts safety-fund abandoned
- Michigan: established 1836, completely blown away 1837 during panic

**3. Base Money on Securities**
- Third proposal: base money supply on government securities (paper certificates of government debt)
- Scheme adopted in 1850s by Illinois, Indiana, Wisconsin and other Midwestern states
- Set precedent for **Federal Reserve System** sixty years later
- Note-issue mania so rampant, notes called "red dog" and "wild cat" currency
- Rising banks created fictitious demand and rising market for securities (to be used as capital stock)
- Consequent stimulus to public debt creation by issuing securities
- Followed by more bank notes being

<!-- pp. 421-440 -->

## Chapter 18: Greenbacks and Other Crimes

### State Banking Proposals and Their Failures

- Fourth proposal: backing money issuance with **state credit** instead of creating gold/silver reserves
- **Alabama (1835)**: created state bank funded by $13.8M public bond issue
- Immediate inflation flooded the economy; legislators abolished direct taxation and funded government through bank money instead
- **Result**: scheme burst in Panic of 1837; bank assets worth $6M were completely worthless
- Citizens lost real money while paying through inflation

- **Mississippi (1838)**: issued $15M in bonds backing state bank notes
- Bank collapsed within four years; state completely repudiated bond obligations
- Infuriated **British financiers** who held large portion of bonds
- Per **Henry Poor** (*Money and Man*): $48M in loans never paid; $23M in notes/deposits never redeemed
- Land became worthless; debtors faced legal action ("G.T.T." — "Gone to Texas" — was common escape route

- **Illinois (1825)**: all "full-faith" bank notes ceremoniously burned at public square after collapse
- Constitution of 1848 stipulated state should never create or own banking stock again
- **Arkansas**: subscribers pledged real estate as collateral instead of cash
- Bank notes plummeted to 25¢ on the dollar; bank failed within four years

### The Mirage of Free Banking

- **"Free banking"** was a semantic fraud — converted banks from corporations to private associations
- Retained all government controls, regulations, supports, and restrictions against free market
- **George Selgin** notes: "permission to set up a bank was usually accompanied by numerous restrictions, including especially required loans to the state"

- Free banks replicated fraudulent practices: gold coins rushed from one bank to another ahead of examiners
- **Massachusetts case**: $500K bank note circulation backed by only $86.48 in specie
- Old custom of "putting a ballast of lead, broken glass and ten-penny nails in the box under a thinner covering of gold coins"

- **Hans Sennholz** analysis: economists celebrate Free Banking Era (1838-1860) as proof government intervention was needed
- **Reality**: instability came from extensive political intervention, not lack of it
- Free banking acts did NOT repeal statutory provisions and regulatory directives — they added more restrictions
- For truly free banking, states needed only two actions: (1) enforce banking contracts like any other contract, (2) step out of the picture
- **If banks failed to redeem in specie, their executives would be imprisoned** — this alone would halt currency overissue
- Instead, banks continued enjoying special privilege of suspending payment without punishment

### Industrial Expansion Despite Dishonest Banking

- **Paradox**: Western frontier expansion and infrastructure boomed despite fraudulent money
- Canals dug, railroads pushed frontier, boom towns sprang up, prairies became agricultural land
- **Galbraith** (p. 85): "the [banking] anarchy served the frontier far better than a more orderly system that kept a tight hand on credit could have done"
- **William Greider** extended rationalization: "Reckless, booming anarchy" produced fundamental progress through energetic, inventive economic growth that endured after froth blew away

- **Griffin's critique**: classic failure of **liberal economics** — focuses on one beneficial consequence (frontier prosperity) while ignoring multitude of harmful effects
- If we add financial losses to all victimized people, the **net product is zero or deeply negative** morally
- Galbraith and Greider assume West could not have been won with honest banking — **logic does not support this**
- More likely: fewer business starts but greater number would have finished; fewer destructive convulsions; West would have been won even faster

> "It's too bad the theory has never been tried." — Griffin's challenge to free-banking apologetics

