## Chapter 19 (cont.): The Union in Jeopardy

### Economic Conflict as Root Cause of Civil War

- **Conventional myth**: Civil War fought over slavery (compared to Bolshevik Revolution as "spontaneous mass uprising")
- **Half-truth**: slavery was AN issue, but primary force was economic conflict between North and South
- **North**: prosperity derived from heavy machines and industrial production
- **South**: agricultural economy dependent on vast labor forces; slavery was **economic question**, not primarily moral one

- **Lincoln's own position**: during 1860 campaign, repeatedly emphasized he had NO PURPOSE to interfere with slavery where it existed
- First inaugural: "I have no lawful right to do so, and I have no inclination to do so"
- Even after war outbreak (1861): "If I could save the Union without freeing any slave, I would do it"
- Lincoln was **white supremacist** — in debates with Stephen Douglas, stated opposition to social/political equality of races, physical differences, and voter/office qualification for Black people

- Lincoln believed slavery would gradually disappear if left alone through natural enlightenment forces
- Feared immediate abolition would destroy Union and cause massive bloodshed worse than slavery itself
- Yet **strategic pivot**: preservation of Union was not enough to fire men's enthusiasm for war
- **Only freedom could do that** — converted war into anti-slavery crusade, which was actually **tactical maneuver** to gain "Rich-man's war and the poor-man's fight" support

### Legal Plunder, Not Slavery, the Economic Cause

- **South was predominantly agricultural region** importing manufactured goods from North and Europe
- European textiles/manufactured items were considerably cheaper than Northern products (even after shipping)
- South found advantage in purchasing European goods — put competitive pressure on Northern manufacturers
- **Republicans used federal power to tip scales**: stiff import duties on European goods also manufactured in North
- **No duty applied to cotton** (Southern export) — classic **legalized plunder**
- **European retaliation**: stopped purchasing U.S. cotton, further hurting South
- Northern manufacturers could charge higher prices without competition; South forced to pay more for practically all necessities

- **Cost of slavery**: slave averaged ~$1,500 each (massive capital investment)
- Modest plantation with 40-50 slaves represented millions in today's purchasing power
- **Abolition meant not just loss of production ability but total destruction of enormous capital base**
- Many Southern plantation owners were working toward converting to more profitable industrial production (as North had done)
- But stuck with current system; felt complete/sudden abolition would destroy economy and starve former slaves (which happened)

- Southern secession question: **Why did Union need preserving?** — Lincoln dependent on Northern industrialists who controlled Party
- Could not reverse trend of economic favoritism and protectionism even if he wanted to

### Mexico and the Monroe Doctrine

- **European powers** (especially France, Spain, England) wanted control of Latin American markets
- **Mexico was prime target** for colonial expansion
- **Monroe Doctrine (38 years prior)**: American continents no longer available for colonization; U.S. would not tolerate European interference
- European ruling classes knew if U.S. remained unified and strong, they could not expand in Latin America
- **Strategy**: split America into two hostile nations, each feeble and burdened with war debt

- European ruling classes sympathized strongly with Confederacy
- **Otto von Bismarck** (German Chancellor, deeply obligated to international finance): "The division of the United States into federations of equal force was decided long before the Civil War by the high financial powers of Europe. These bankers were afraid that the United States, if they remained in one block and as one nation, would attain economic and financial independence, which would upset their financial domination over the Europe and the world."

> "The Rothschild voice prevailed. They saw an opportunity for prodigious booty if they could substitute two feeble democracies, burdened with debt to the financiers, in place of a vigorous Republic sufficient unto herself."

- **Bismarck continued**: "Therefore, they sent their emissaries into the field to exploit the question of slavery and drive a wedge between the two parts of the Union."
- Within months after war outbreak, France landed troops in Mexico
- By 1864, Mexicans subdued; **Ferdinand Maximilian** installed as puppet emperor
- Confederacy found natural ally in Maximilian
- Anticipated post-war combination of Confederate South + Mexican empire under financial control of **Rothschild**
- England moved 11,000 troops into Canada simultaneously as strategic show of strength
- Union faced apparent **checkmate from European powers**

### Russia's Unexpected Alignment with the North

- **Masterful intervention**: Tsar Alexander II — who had never allowed central bank in Russia — notified Lincoln he stood ready to militarily align with North
- **Key motivation**: NOT emancipation, but geopolitical: England and France had been maneuvering to break up Russian empire (splitting Finland, Estonia, Latvia, Poland, Crimea, Georgia)
- Russia proposed Great Britain and Austria declare war on Russia to hasten dismemberment
- Tsar decided to play geopolitical chess: **September 1863**, dispatched Baltic Fleet to Alexandria, Virginia and Asiatic Fleet to San Francisco

- **Carl Wrangell-Rokassowsky** explanation: mutual interest unified Russia and Union; threat of war to both made critical alliance
- No formal treaty signed, but mutual interest and war threat unified them
- **Instructions to Russian fleets**: in case of war, attack enemies' commercial shipping and colonies to cause maximum damage
- **Effect on war outcome**: prevented France/England from risking overt military intervention
- Neither France nor England wanted war with both Union AND Russia
- Russian fleet's mere presence made European powers extremely cautious with overt military aid to South
- No record of Russian ships firing on English/French vessels — **point was intimidation itself**
- Without inhibiting effect of Russian fleet, course of war could have been significantly different

### The Emancipation Proclamation

- To get people to fight, decided to convert war into anti-slavery crusade
- **Emancipation Proclamation**: primarily move by Lincoln to fan dying embers of support for "Rich-man's war and poor-man's fight"
- **Not constitutional amendment** nor act of Congress — issued solely on Lincoln's authority as Commander-in-Chief
- Virtually unprecedented constitutional violation

- Preservation of Union alone insufficient to fire men's enthusiasm
- **Only freedom could do that** — reframed war as moral crusade
- After emphasizing slavery was not reason for war, Lincoln later explained why he changed tactics: "Things had gone from bad to worse until I felt we had reached the end of our rope on the plan we were pursuing; that we had about played our last card, and must change our tactics or lose the game. I now determined upon the adoption of the emancipation policy."

- **Technical absurdity**: Proclamation freed slaves only in areas where U.S. could not make authority effective, while allowing slavery to continue in Federal-controlled slave states
- **But strategic brilliance**: changed whole character of war; **doomed Confederacy to defeat more than any other single thing** per **Bruce Catton** (*American Heritage Pictorial History of Civil War*)
- Had profound impact on European powers: no government dared anger subjects by taking sides against country trying to destroy slavery
- After 1862, European military intervention on behalf of Confederacy became politically impossible
- South maneuvered into position that could not be defended in modern world

### Raising Armies on Both Sides

- Men willing to defend families/homes when threatened by foreign foe; not for abstract cause or cash bounty alone
- Both sides used bounties AND **conscription** to keep armies in field
- Only Congress can declare war and raise army per Constitution; **Lincoln did so entirely on his own authority**

- **North**: gave states quota to fill with volunteers before conscription began
- By 1864, bounty system developed: man could receive $1,000+ (equivalent to $50K+ today) for enlisting
- Wealthy could avoid draft by paying commutation fee or hiring substitute
- **South**: even bolder — immediately gathered powers of centralized government to Richmond
- 1862 conscription law: exclusive control over every male citizen age 18-35
- **Owner of 20+ slaves exempt** from military service — loophole allowing wealthy to avoid service

- **Lincoln faced rebellion in North** (1863 conscription): thousands protested in torch parades, anti-Lincoln rallies in Madison Square
- Historian James Horan: "When caricatures of the President were lifted above the speaker's stand, hisses rose to fill the night with the noise of a million angry bees"
- Federal troops called in; antidraft riots suppressed in New York City
- Draft names published July 12; mobs stormed draft offices, set fire to buildings
- Over thousand civilians killed or wounded when **Army of the Potomac ordered to fire into crowds**
- Lincoln had insurrection on his hands in North as well as South

- Suspension of habeas corpus allowed government to imprison critics without formal charges or trial
- **Free men were enslaved so slaves could be made free** — bad exchange

- War expenses: 1861 fiscal year = $67M; first year of conflict = $475M; by 1865 = $1.3B
- Taxes covered only 11% of expenses; deficit rose to $2.61B by war's end

