## Funding the War: Income Tax and War Bonds

### First Income Tax and Rothschild's Role

- Nation's first **income tax** experiment tried during Civil War (another constitutional violation)
- By modern standards, still unpopular measure; Congress knew additional taxes would inflame rebellion
- Traditional war funding: banks created money under pretense of loaning it
- **But Bank of U.S. was dead** — state banks had already defaulted on specie promises and could not manufacture acceptable money

- **Rothschild consortium** stepped in: both able and willing to finance war
- **August Belmont** (Rothschild agent in U.S.) placed large amounts into bonds of **state-sponsored banks in South**
- Those bonds fell to near-zero value as war favored North
- Belmont began buying additional Southern bonds at pennies on dollar, planning postwar North Carolina would honor pre-war debt in full
- Strategy: **gigantic speculative profit** after Union victory when Southern states forced to honor bonds
- Also became chief agent for sale of Union bonds in England and France
- (Rumor: offered Lincoln Rothschild money at 27½% interest; if true, rudely rejected)

- **Sale of government bonds** was only measure that seemed to work for raising funds
- Even with compound interest, failed to raise more than about half needed amount
- **Union faced dilemma**: (1) terminate war OR (2) print fiat money

<!-- pp. 441-460 -->

## The Greenbacks (continued)

### War of 1812 Precedent
- **Albert Gallatin**, Secretary of Treasury during War of 1812, had already set the precedent by abrogating the Constitutional ban on "bills of credit" by printing Treasury notes
- Notes paid 5.4% interest, were never declared legal tender — likely the basis for defending them as constitutional
- By Civil War, all pretense at constitutionality had been dropped

### The Greenback System (1862)
- Congress authorized Treasury to print **$150 million** in bills of credit, put them into circulation as money to pay government expenses
- Declared **legal tender** for all private debts but not for government duties or taxes
- Printed with green ink, became known as **"greenbacks"**
- Promised as one-time emergency measure — promise soon broken
- By war's end, total of **$432 million in greenbacks** issued

### Salmon P. Chase's Reversal
- As Secretary of Treasury, **strongly endorsed** greenbacks as "indispensable necessity"
- Eight years later as **Chief Justice of Supreme Court**, declared them unconstitutional
- Author's interpretation: Not a change of mind, but situational pragmatism
- When endorsed: nation at war. When declared unconstitutional: nation at peace
- Example of **Rothschild Formula**: "The sanctity of its laws, the prosperity of its citizens, and the solvency of its treasury will be quickly sacrificed by any government in its primal act of self-survival"

## Lincoln's Mixed View of Banking

### Lincoln's Quote on Money Creation
> "Government, possessing power to create and issue currency and credit as money and enjoying the right to withdraw currency and credit from circulation by taxation and otherwise, need not and should not borrow capital at interest.... The privilege of creating and issuing money is not only the supreme prerogative of the government but it is the government's greatest creative opportunity."

- Lincoln objected to government paying interest to banks for money created from nothing
- Argued government can create money from nothing just as easily without paying interest
- Both schemes forbidden by Constitution — if one tolerates plunder-by-inflation, there's "appealing logic" to the argument
- Politicians get fiat money, but at least banks denied a free ride

### Lincoln's Banking Inconsistency
- Early political career: **friend of banking industry** and advocate of easy credit
- As Whig in 1830s (before becoming Republican): supported **Biddle's Second Bank of the United States**
- During debates with Stephen Douglas: defended the Bank and advocated its reestablishment
- As President: took initiative requesting Congress to **reestablish central banking**
- Appears inconsistent — in effort to finance unpopular war, sometimes anesthetized personal convictions to meet governmental survival exigencies

### Bankers' Opposition to Greenbacks
- Greenbacks not pleasing to bankers — denied their customary override on government debt
- Bankers wanted **federal fiat money replaced by bank fiat money**
- Required creating whole new monetary system with government bonds as backing for bank notes — return to **central banking**
- This was precisely what **Secretary Chase** was preparing to establish

## The Hazard Circular (1862)

### Bankers' Strategic Memo
- Basic position outlined in memo called **The Hazard Circular**
- Prepared by American agent of British financiers, circulated among country's wealthy businessmen

> "The great debt that capitalists will see to it is made out of the war must be used as a means to control the volume of money. To accomplish this the bonds must be used as a banking basis. We are now waiting for the Secretary of the Treasury to make this recommendation to Congress. It will not do to allow the greenback, as it is called, to circulate as money any length of time, as we cannot control that. But we can control the bonds and through them the bank issues."

## The National Banking Act

### Structure of the Act (February 25, 1863)
- Established new system of **nationally-chartered banks**
- Similar to Bank of United States **except**: instead of one central bank with power to influence others, now many national banks with control from Washington
- Promoted honestly as wartime emergency scheme to:
  1. Raise money for military expenses
  2. Create market for government bonds
  3. Transform bonds into circulating money

### How the System Worked
- National bank purchased government bonds, did not hold them
- Turned bonds back to Treasury, which exchanged them for equal amount of **"United States Bank Notes"** with bank's name engraved
- Government declared these **legal tender for taxes and duties** — status caused public to generally accept as money
- Bank's net cost: **zero** (got money back immediately)
- Technically bank still owned bonds and collected interest, but also had use of equal amount of newly created bank-note money which could be loaned at interest
- Result: **monetary and political scientists had converted government debt into money**, bankers collecting substantial fee at both ends

### Reserve Requirements and Leverage
- Banks required to keep percentage of notes and deposits in **lawful money (gold coins)** as reserve
- Percentage varied by size/location, averaged about **12%**
- Bank with $1 million in coin deposits could use ~$880,000 ($1M less 12%) to:
  1. Purchase government bonds
  2. Exchange bonds for bank notes
  3. Lend out bank notes
  4. Collect interest on both bonds and loans
- Bank could earn interest on **$880,000 loaned to government** (in coins) plus **$880,000 loaned to customers** (in bank notes)
- **Doubled income** without increasing capital
- Bonds gobbled up as fast as printed — problem of funding war solved

### System's Shortcomings (from manipulators' view)
- Bank notes widely circulated but not classified as **"lawful" money**
- Legal tender only for taxes and duties, not for all debts
- Precious-metal coins and greenbacks still the country's official money
- Would take **50 years** until Federal Reserve System for government debt in bank notes to be mandated as nation's official money for all transactions under penalty of law

### Perpetual Debt Trap Created
- National Banking Act made it **impossible for federal government to ever get out of debt**
- Even friends of central banking forced to admit this reality
- **Galbraith** quote:

> "Rarely has economic circumstance managed more successfully to confound the most prudent in economic foresight. In numerous years following the war the Federal government ran a heavy surplus. It could not pay off its debt, retire its securities, because to do so meant there would be no bonds to back the national bank notes. To pay off the debt was to destroy the money supply."

- Author's analysis: Essentially same situation today
- Every dollar of currency and checkbook money created by act of lending
- If all debt repaid, entire money supply would vanish
- **National debt is principal foundation** upon which money is created for private debt
- To pay off or greatly reduce national debt would cripple monetary system
- No politician would dare advocate, even if surplus funds available
- **Federal Reserve System has locked nation into perpetual debt**

## The Hidden Cost of War

### Inflation's Impact in the North
- During war: greenbacks' purchasing power fell **65%**
- Money supply increased **138%**
- Prices more than doubled, wages rose less than half
- Americans surrendered to government and banks **more than half of all money they earned or held** during period — in addition to taxes

### The South's Hyperinflation
- Financial conditions even worse in South
- Exception: seizure of ~$400,000 in gold from Federal mint at New Orleans
- Almost all war funded by **printing fiat money**
- Confederate notes increased in volume **214% per year**
- Total volume of all money (including bank notes and check-book money) rose **over 300% per year**
- Each Southern state issued its own fiat money
- By war's end, total of all notes: about **$1 billion**
- Within four-year period, prices shot up **9,100%**
- After Appomattox, Confederate notes and bonds totally worthless

### Public Ignorance of the Hidden Tax
- Average citizen did not understand newly created money represented **hidden tax** paid through higher prices
- Northern voters would not have tolerated open, honest tax increase of that magnitude
- Even in South (where cause perceived as self-defense), might not have supported if they knew true dimension of assessment
- Because they did not understand "secret science of money," Americans not only **paid the hidden tax but applauded Congress for creating it**

## Lincoln's Concern for the Future

### Rothschild Communique (June 25, 1863)
- Four months after National Bank Act signed, confidential communique sent from **Rothschild investment house in London** to associate banking firm in New York:

> "The few who understand the system [bank loans earning interest and also serving as money] will either be so interested in its profits or so dependent upon its favors that there will be no opposition from that class while, on the other hand, the great body of people, mentally incapable of comprehending,... will bear its burdens without complaint."

### Lincoln's Private Apprehension
- Privately apprehensive about Bank Act
- Loyalty to Party and need to maintain unity in time of war compelled him to withhold veto
- Personal view was unequivocal
- In letter to **William Elkins** (following year):

> "The money power preys upon the nation in times of peace and conspires against it in times of adversity. It is more despotic than monarchy, more insolent than autocracy, more selfish than bureaucracy. I see in the near future a crisis approaching that unnerves me and causes me to tremble for the safety of my country. Corporations have been enthroned, an era of corruption will follow, and the money power of the country will endeavor to prolong its reign by working upon the prejudices of the people, until the wealth is aggregated in a few hands, and the republic destroyed."

## Reviewing Lincoln's Role

### Ambivalence Toward Lincoln
- Author expresses mixed feelings about Lincoln's role

**Negative actions:**
- Declared war without Congress
- Suspended writ of habeas corpus
- Issued **Emancipation Proclamation** not as administrative executive but as Commander-in-Chief
- Proclamation not issued from humanitarian motives but as maneuver to generate popular support for war
- By participating in greenbacks issuance: violated clearly written Constitutional section
- By failing to veto National Bank Act: **acquiesced in delivery of American people back into hands of international Cabal** — similar to forcible return of captured runaway slaves

**Positive considerations:**
- No question of Lincoln's **patriotism**
- Concern was preserving Union, preserving Constitution, refusing to let European powers split America into warring nation-states
- Lincoln believed he had to violate part of Constitution to save the whole
- **Dangerous reasoning** — can be used in almost any national crisis as excuse for expansion of totalitarian power
- Author's counterfactual: No reason to believe only way to save Union was to scrap Constitution
- If Constitution meticulously observed from beginning, Southern minority could never have been legally plundered by Northern majority
- Likely would have been no movement for secession in first place
- Even if there had been, strict Constitutional reading could have led to honorable, peaceful settlement
- Result: preservation of Union without war, Americans enjoying far less government intervention today

## With Malice Toward None

### Lincoln's Stand Against Economic Vengeance
- Political compatriots howling for **economic vengeance against South**
- Lincoln stood firmly against it
- **"With malice toward none"** was more than slogan — willing to risk political survival on that issue

### Wade-Davis Emancipation Bill
- Lincoln vetoed because it would have:
  1. Applied lien against Southern cotton at war's end to benefit New England textile manufactures
  2. Cotton taken as security to pay off Southern debt contracted before war
  3. Provided funds to buy back at face value all bonds purchased at discount by **Rothschild's agent, August Belmont**
- Such defiance of financiers and speculators required great courage

### Lincoln's Amnesty vs. Republican Reconstruction
- **Lincoln's offer**: General amnesty to any Southern citizen who would take loyalty oath to Union
- When 10% of voters took oath, proposed they could elect Congressmen, Senators, state government recognized as part of Union again

- **Republicans' Wade-Davis bill provision**: Each seceded state treated like conquered country
- Political representation denied until **51% (not 10%)** had taken oath
- Former slaves given right to vote (though women not given that right even in North)
- Because of lack of education and political awareness, no one expected them to play meaningful role for many years
- Those taking oath had to swear **they had never taken up arms against Union**
- Since almost every able-bodied white male had done so, effect would deny South political representation **for at least two generations**

### Political Consequences
- Under Lincoln's amnesty: Republicans would soon be overwhelmed in Congress by large majority of Democrats
- Democrats in North already gaining strength on their own
- Once joined by solid block from reunited South, Republicans' political and economic power would be lost
- When Lincoln vetoed bill, **his own Party bitterly turned against him**

## Cross-Currents and the Knights of the Golden Circle

