## Chapter Twenty: THE LONDON CONNECTION

### National Banking System (1863-1913)

- Post-Civil War period saw great economic volatility and chaos
- **National Banking Act (1863-65)** established federally chartered banks with extraordinary privilege:
  - Monopoly on bank note issuance
  - Government accepted their notes for tax payments
  - Could back notes 90% with government bonds instead of gold
  - All banks forced to accept each other's notes at face value regardless of solvency
- Result: U.S. banking after Civil War was "literally a halfway house to central banking," not free/unregulated as historians claim

### The Midas Complex Era

- Second half of 19th century saw nation "gone mad with the Midas complex"
- Politicians and businessmen obsessed with creating prosperity by creating more money through banking magic
- Personal checks became accepted as readily as bank notes
- Banks entered tiny numbers in passbooks as readily as they "borrowed"

> "The manna of cheap money became the universal cry, and as with the Israelites, the easier the manna was acquired, the louder became the complaint, the less willing the people to struggle for it." — Elmer Dean Groseclose

### Jay Cooke's Philosophy

- **Jay Cooke**: famous financier who marketed Civil War loans, raised $100 million for Northern Pacific Railroad
- Published pamphlet: *How Our National Debt May Be a National Blessing*
- Argued debt was "Public Wealth, Political Union, Protection of Industry, Secure Basis for National Currency"

> "Should this Grand and Glorious country be stunted and dwarfed—its activities chilled and its very life blood curdled by these miserable 'hard coin' theories—the musty theories of a bygone age." — Jay Cooke

- Northern Pacific went bankrupt, Cooke's giant investment firm disappeared, triggering **Panic of 1873**

### The Panic of 1873

- **Matthew Josephson** described: "All about the failure of Jay Cooke!" newsboys hawked
- Largest, most pious bank in Western world fallen "with the effect of a thunderclap"
- Allied brokers, national banks, and 5,000 commercial houses followed into bankruptcy
- Wall Street suspensions cascading; railroads failed; stocks lost 30-40 points (half their value) within hours
- Exchanges closed; "the stampede, the 'greatest' crisis in American history, was on"

### Four Major Panics (1873-1907)

- Four major contractions: panics of **1873, 1884, 1893, and 1907**
- Each characterized by inadequate bank reserves and suspension of specie payment
- Congress response: **NOT** requiring increased reserves (which would improve safety)
- Instead: **allowed decrease** in reserves
- **June 1874 legislation**: permitted banks to back notes entirely with government bonds
  - Eliminated even 10% specie backing
  - Released over $20 million from bank reserves for pyramiding more checkbook money

### The Seasonal Demand Myth

- Accepted mythology: panics caused by seasonal farm loan demands at harvest
- Country banks drew down city bank reserves, thinning reserves and making system vulnerable
- **Questions the legend raises**: Why not panic every Autumn? Why didn't all banks maintain adequate reserves? Why would saying no to some loans cause hundreds of banks to fail?
- **Truth**: If not seasonal agriculture, money magicians would have found another scapegoat
- Real problem always was **fractional-reserve banking itself**
- Elaborate regional bank schemes to pool reserves failed — "loaves and fishes stubbornly refused to multiply"

### Morgan Prospers When Others Fail

- Monetary expansions/contractions were "large waves that capsized thousands of investment ships"
- **J.P. Morgan's vessel** bobbed through surges, salvaged abandoned cargoes, kept riches under "rules of the high sea"
- Morgan was no small player in World War I chess match
- French and British governments chose Morgan as official U.S. war bond sales agent
- When war went badly, Morgan interests agitated for American entry "calculated to save the loans"
- Morgan was official U.S. trade agent for Britain — handled purchase/shipping of all war material including munitions on the **Lusitana**

### The Council on Foreign Relations

- Close Morgan-Britain relationship was no accident
- **J.P. Morgan, Jr.** drove the **Council on Foreign Relations** — American branch of secret society established by **Cecil Rhodes** for British empire expansion
- Morgans were "more British than American"

### Origins of the Morgan Dynasty

- Began with **George Peabody**, American merchant from Danvers, Massachusetts
- In 1835, Peabody traveled to England as bond salesman for Chesapeake and Ohio Canal
- Seeking British investors to replace missing Americans (due to recession)
- Routinely rejected by London investment houses, but persistence paid off

> "When the panic [in the U.S.] at last started to subside, he called time and again on the big City barons [in London] to assure them that Maryland and other states would honor their bonds. He also continued backing American securities with his personal funds. Buying at almost giveaway levels, he later reaped a rich harvest." — **Stanley Jackson**

- Unloaded Chesapeake and Ohio Canal bonds, won acclaim, returned with $60,000 commission intact to Maryland treasury
- During this trip: opened import-export business at 22 Old Broad Street in London
- Provided loans and letters of credit to shippers, moving into investment business specializing in Britain-U.S. transactions
- Fortunate timing: beginning of rapid U.S. expansion with insatiable need for investment capital
- Bond issues offered tantalizing returns substantially higher than European offerings
- Peabody's firm uniquely positioned to exploit expanding market

### Selecting a Successor

- Peabody never married, sought successor with specific qualifications:
  1. American by birth (appear authentic as U.S. investments representative)
  2. British by instinct and preference (well educated, good breeding, accepted by London financial aristocracy)
  3. Knowledge of Anglo-American finance
  4. Peabody had to like him

### Junius Morgan Selected

- Boston merchant **Junius Morgan** met **George Peabody** at London dinner party (1850)
- Elder financier took immediate liking, began discreet inquiries
- Extended period of business and social contact
- 1854: Junius moved family to London, became full partner in firm (eventually **Peabody, Morgan & Company**)
- Partnership became chief fiscal agent for Union government during Civil War
- Firm's great profits pushed it into top echelons of London's financial fraternity
- 1864: Peabody retired, Junius immediately changed name to **J.S. Morgan and Company**

### J.P. Morgan, Jr. (John Pierpont)

- Attended English High School in Boston but enrolled in European schools, became engulfed in British tradition
- Born in U.S. — ideally suited to carry on Anglo-American role
- Inevitable he'd be trained in international finance and groomed for father's shoes
- First move: 1857 employment at New York investment firm **Duncan, Sherman & Company**
- Seven years later: Junius acquired competitor, set son up as partner in **Dabney, Morgan & Company** (New York branch of London firm)
- 1871: addition of third partner **Anthony Drexel** from Philadelphia → **Drexel, Morgan & Company**
- 1895: after Drexel's death, final name change to **J.P. Morgan & Company**
- Paris branch became **Morgan, Harjes & Company**

### Americanizing the New York Branch

- After Junius's unexpected death in carriage accident, **Pierpont** reshaped London firm's image as more British operation
- Allowed New York branch to represent American side with less suspicion of being essentially same firm
- Son **J.P. Morgan, Jr. (Jack)** already brought in as partner
- Biographer **John Forbes**: J.P. Morgan, Jr. became partner in London house of J.S. Morgan & Co. on January 1, 1898
- Fortnight later: left New York, took up residence in England for next eight years

### Morgan's Two London Objectives

1. Learn firsthand how British conducted banking under central banking system dominated by **Bank of England**
   - Morgan, Sr. anticipated Federal Reserve establishment in U.S.
   - Wanted someone with authority in Morgan firms to know how such system worked
2. Quietly look about City, select British partners to convert elder Morgan's privately owned J.S. Morgan & Co. into British concern

- Eventually accomplished by adding **Edward Grenfell** (long-time Bank of England director) as new senior partner
- Became **Morgan, Grenfell & Company**
- Window dressing didn't alter reality: J.P. Morgan & Co. in New York "remained more British in orientation than American"

### Relationship with Rothschilds

- Casual reading suggests Peabody and Morgan were fierce Rothschild competitors
- True they bid against each other, BUT:
  - Almost every biographer told how American newcomers were in awe of Rothschild power
  - Purposely cultivated Rothschild friendship
  - Friendship became so intimate Americans received as personal house guests
  - Morgan firm worked closely with Rothschilds on large joint ventures
- Common practice among large investment houses
- In light of subsequent events: appropriate to consider possibility **Peabody/Morgan firm became secret Rothschild agent**

### Evidence of Concealed Alliance

- Some writers suggest clandestine relationship began almost from beginning
- **Eustace Mullins**: Soon after arriving in London, George Peabody summoned to audience with gruff **Baron Nathan Mayer Rothschild**
  - Rothschild revealed much of London aristocracy openly disliked him, refused invitations
  - Proposed: Peabody (man of modest means) be established as lavish host whose entertainments would become talk of London
  - Rothschild would pay all bills
  - Peabody accepted; became known as most popular host in London
  - Annual Fourth-of-July dinner celebrating American Independence became extremely popular with English aristocracy
  - "many of whom, while drinking Peabody's wine, regaled each other with jokes about Rothschild's crudities and bad manners"

- 1991 *Business Week* noted: CEO of J.P. Morgan & Co., **Dennis Weatherstone** (lives in Connecticut), knighted by Queen Elizabeth II

> "without realizing that every drop they drank had been paid for by Rothschild." — Mullins

- Mullins gives no source reference; one cannot help being skeptical such details could be proved
- BUT: secret arrangement not as absurd as may sound
  - Rothschilds quite capable of such clandestine relationship (exactly deception for which they'd become famous)
  - Ample reason to do so: strong anti-Semitic and anti-Rothschild sentiment in Europe and U.S.
  - Family often found advantageous to work through agents rather than deal directly
  - **Derek Wilson**: "The name 'Rothschild' was, thus, beginning to be heard in places far removed from sophisticated London and Paris. But the connection with the great bankers was sometimes tenuous."

### August Belmont — Known Rothschild Agent

- Tenuous connection precisely the role to be played by **August Belmont** in United States
- Anti-Semitism undoubtedly why he changed name from Schoenberg to Belmont upon landing in New York (1837)
- Prior to that: Rothschild agent had been **J.L. and S.I. Joseph & Company** (as American sounding as one can get)
- Not long before Belmont-Rothschild connection became common knowledge, ploy ceased to be effective

### Alphonse Rothschild's 1848 Assessment

- 1848: family sent **Alphonse Rothschild** to U.S. to check on Belmont's operations, evaluate possibility of replacing with direct Rothschild representative (perhaps Alphonse himself)
- After extended visit, wrote home:

> "In a few years from now America will have attracted to itself the greater part of trade with China and the Indies and will be enthroned between the two oceans.... The country possesses such elements of prosperity that one would have to be blind not to recognize them.... I have no hesitation in saying that a Rothschild house, and not just an agency, should be established in America.... Today we are presented with a fine opportunity. Later on, difficulties will of necessity arise as a result of competition from all sides."

### Why Rothschilds Didn't Establish Direct Presence

- Some historians expressed amazement recommendation never acted upon
- **Derek Wilson**: "This was the greatest opportunity the Rothschilds ever lost."
- Those with skeptical bent tempted to wonder: was opportunity really lost or merely taken in more indirect fashion?
- Significant: precisely at this time, George Peabody making name for himself in London, established close relationship with Nathan Rothschild
- Possible Peabody firm given nod from Rothschild consortium to represent them in America?
- Possible plan included allowing Belmont to operate as known Rothschild agent while using Peabody & Company as unknown agent, providing own competition?

### Multiple Historians Support Morgan-Rothschild Alliance

- **John Moody**: "The Rothschilds were content to remain a close ally of Morgan rather than a competitor as far as the American field was concerned."
- **Gabriel Kolko**: "Morgan's activities in 1895-1896 in selling U.S. gold bonds in Europe were based on his alliance with the House of Rothschild."
- **Sereno Pratt**: "These houses may, like J.P. Morgan & Company ... represent here the great firms and institutions of Europe, just as August Belmont & Company have long represented the Rothschilds."
- **George Wheeler**: "Part of the reality of the day was an ugly resurgence of anti-Semitism.... Someone was needed as a cover. Who better than J. Pierpont Morgan, a solid, Protestant exemplar of capitalism able to trace his family back to pre-Revolutionary times?"

### Rise of the House of Morgan

- With these considerations as background, meteoric rise of Morgan's star readily understood
- No longer surprising: **Peabody & Company** sole American investment firm to receive gigantic loan from Bank of England during U.S. panic of 1857
- Loan not only saved firm from sinking but made it possible to "seize and salvage many other ships then capsized on Wall Street"

### Discounting Acceptances Business

- Peabody active in business of **discounting acceptances** (banker language for insuring commercial loans for goods purchase)
- How it works:
  - Seller issues bill with stipulation for payment at future date (usually 90 days)
  - Buyer receives bill, bank writes "accepted" across face, adds officer signature (legally binding contract)
  - Bank becomes co-signer on buyer's credit, guarantees payment even if buyer defaults
- Price for guarantee: percentage of total bill, added to amount paid by buyer or deducted from amount received by seller
- Fee paid at both ends: one to seller's bank (receives acceptance, pays out money), one to issuing bank (assumes liability of guaranteeing payment)
- Sale said to be "discounted" by amount paid to banks
- Peabody & Company active in discounting acceptances primarily between English sellers and U.S. buyers

### Morgan and the Panic of 1857

- In 1857 Wall Street panic: many U.S. buyers unable to pay bills
- Peabody and Morgan expected to make good on guarantees
- Naturally didn't have the money; facing certain bankruptcy unless obtained from somewhere
- **Stanley Jackson** details: slump catastrophic for Peabody & Co.
  - Suddenly found itself committed to acceptances of £2 million with no hope of discharging even part of depreciating bonds stockpile
  - New York brokers and bankers desperately short of ready funds
  - Firm soon paying out thousands of pounds daily
  - Without raising large temporary loan, partners forced to suspend business altogether

- **Ron Chernow** (*The House of Morgan*): "Rumors raced through London that George Peabody and Company was about to fail, a prospect heartily relished by rivals.... The major London houses told Morgan they would bail out the firm—but only if Peabody shut down the bank within a year."

- Clouds lifted dramatically when **Bank of England** announced loan to Peabody's of £800,000 at very reasonable interest, promise of further funds up to £1 million when required
- Remarkable vote of confidence as **Thomas Hankey** (Bank of England governor) had already rejected similar appeals from various American firms "who did not measure up to his standards"
- Peabody & Company recovered almost overnight, hoisted turnover above pre-slump levels

### Significance of Bank of England Rescue

- Event reveals great deal about relationships
- If Rothschilds truly been competitors, they'd have seized upon opportunity, used great influence within Bank of England and other investment houses to squeeze out Peabody, not assist
- Barings in particular already trying to accomplish exactly that
- **Rothschilds must have believed successful Peabody firm ultimately would be in their own best interest**

### Anti-Semitism Was Profitable

- Later years: **Jack Morgan (J.P., Jr.)** assumed role of staunch anti-Semite
- Undoubtedly strengthened hand dealing with American investors/borrowers loath to have anything to do with Jewish bankers
- Particularly helpful during **1896 rescue of federal government** from decline in gold reserves
- Fearing couldn't honor promise to exchange paper money for gold coins, government forced to borrow $62 million in gold
- House of Rothschild obvious source, but Treasury wanted to avoid anti-Semitic backlash
- Everything fell into place when **Morgan and Company became primary lender**, with Rothschild apparently demoted to mere participant

> "The consummate politicians of the Cleveland administration ... were certainly aware of the dangers inherent in promoting a rescue effort for the United States Treasury that would be financed by those archetypes of 'international Jewish financiers,' the Rothschilds...." — **George Wheeler**

### Pierpont Morgan's Financial Backwaters

- During these developments, Pierpont Morgan took no direct part in salvage effort
- At this point (would be fifty-eight in two months), looked like aging financier merely one among many
- Whatever subsequent financial arrangements seemed as though he'd move into old age with little more than obituary mentions:
  - Awkward attempt to profiteer on rifle sales at Civil War start
  - Minor shorting of Union in gold trading toward close
  - Bold but largely unsuccessful 1880s move to impose eastern capitalist cease-fire on country's warring railroads

- Steps being taken to bring him out of financial backwaters — NOT by Pierpont Morgan himself
- **First suggestion of his name for role in recharging reserve originated with London branch of House of Rothschild**

### J.P. Morgan, Jr.'s Profitable Anti-Semitism During WWI

- Apparent anti-Semitism again extremely profitable during World War 1
- Widely publicized Kaiser funded by German-Jew bankers
- Dealing with Morgan group (as opposed to Kuhn Loeb) in some circles "almost a point of national patriotism"

### The Small Estates Mystery

- When J.P. Morgan, Sr. died (1913): estate valued at only $68 million (paltry compared to Vanderbilts, Astors, Rockefellers)
- Even more unbelievable: Jack Morgan died (1943), left estate valued at only $16 million
- Small amount transferred to family members prior to deaths, but didn't account for vast fortunes visibly controlled during lives
- Surely bookkeeping sleight-of-hand — may have been true
- When **Alphonse Rothschild** died in Paris (1905): estate contained $60 million in American securities
- Rothschilds in Britain undoubtedly held equally large bloc
- Many securities handled through House of Morgan
- **Possibilities obvious**: major portion of wealth/power of Morgan firm was (and always had been) merely wealth/power of Rothschilds who raised it up initially and sustained it throughout existence

### Final Analysis

- How much of Morgan's apparent anti-Semitism was real vs. pragmatic guise: in final analysis, little importance
- Should not give unwarranted emphasis here
- **Regardless of interpretation of nature of relationship between Houses of Morgan and Rothschild**:
  - Fact remains: relationship was close
  - Was ongoing
  - Was profitable to both
- If Morgan truly harbored feelings of anti-Semitism, neither he nor Rothschilds allowed it to get in way of business

## England Faces a Dilemma (1924)

- Narrative jumps ahead to 1924 (before allowing characters to act out Federal Reserve creation drama)
- End of World War I: Britain faced economic dilemma
- Had abandoned gold standard early in war to remove all limits from fiat money creation (result: extreme inflation)
- Now wanted to regain former position of power and prestige in world's financial markets
- Decided necessary to return to gold standard
- Further decided: set exchange value of **pound sterling** at exactly **$4.86 in U.S. currency** (approximately pre-war value)

### Not a Pure Gold Standard

- To say "return to gold standard" actually misleading
- NOT pure standard where every money unit totally backed by stated weight of gold
- Rather: a
<!-- pp. 481-500 -->

## Fractional Gold Standard Benefits

- **Fractional gold standard** (only portion backed by gold) offered three advantages over pure fiat:
  - Greater consumer confidence — implied promise of gold redemption (even if broken in practice)
  - Efficient international settlements — gold remained the medium of choice between nations
  - Applied braking action to fiat money production — some restraint on inflation and boom-bust cycles

### Problems with Britain's Return to Gold

- Exchange value of gold **cannot be set by political decree** — determined by supply/demand
- Trying to fix dollar-pound exchange rate like "legislating how many baseball cards a schoolboy will give for a purple agate"
- International currency market functions like auction — if opening bid too high, no takers
- Britain's welfare state and strong labor unions made competitive pound devaluation politically impossible
- **Politicians unwilling to cut welfare or wages** — continued bidding for votes with socialism promises
- Government limited gold availability to **bars only** (not coins) — ensured gold used for large international transactions, not domestic circulation

## England in Depression

### Export Collapse from Overvalued Pound

- Artificially high pound sustained prices, wages, and profit levels
- **British exports became uncompetitive** in world markets
- Exports declined → money inflow declined → **England became debtor nation**
- When spending exceeds income, must: increase income, dip into savings, sell assets, counterfeit, or borrow

### Gold Drain Crisis

- England exhausted borrowing capacity and savings buying foreign goods
- Couldn't counterfeit because payments settled in gold
- **Gold supply moved out of country** as national savings spent
- "The handwriting was on the wall. If this process continued, the nation soon would be broke."

> "Situation was amazingly parallel to what has plagued the United States since the end of Word War II, and for mostly the same reasons."

### Currency Collapse 1919

- **March 1919**: England forced to let pound "float" (seek market level)
- Within one year: pound dropped to **$3.21 (34% loss)**
- American dollar was defacto world standard — fewer dollars per pound meant pound devalued globally
- British imports became more expensive, exports became cheaper
- Economy experienced **"monetary hangover from vast inflation of World War I"**
- Painful but healthy recovery and return to reality

## Monetary Scientists' Emergency Therapies

### Gold Exchange Standard via League of Nations

- **Financial Committee of League of Nations** (England-dominated) imposed coordinated inflation
- Required all European nations to follow **inflationary monetary policies**
- Created **"gold exchange standard"** — currencies based on pound sterling (not gold directly)
- All countries could inflate together without disruptive gold flows between them
- **England as regulator and guarantor** of system
- **Bank of England became master central bank** for all European central banks
- Prototype for **Federal Reserve/World Bank system within UN framework**

## Problem of American Prosperity

- Europe under control, but **U.S. remained independent threat**
- America inflated during war but not as much as Europe
- America had fractional gold standard with **large, growing gold stockpile**
- As long as U.S. produced commodities England needed for import, and dollar remained strong, **pound sterling anemia continued**

### Monetary Transfusion Strategy

- **Most ingenious method**: have one nation deliberately inflate its currency faster than another
- Real purchasing power moves from more-inflating to less-inflating nation via international trade
- "So subtle and sophisticated that not one in a thousand would even think of it, much less object to it"
- Ideal method chosen in 1925 to benefit England at America's expense

> "The American public was nominated to suffer the burdens of inflation and subsequent collapse [the crash of 1929] in order to maintain the British government and the British trade union movement in the style to which they insisted on becoming accustomed." — **Murray Rothbard**

## Benjamin Strong — Morgan's Man at the Fed

### Strong's Qualifications and Alliance

- **Benjamin Strong** won power struggle to become **first Governor of Federal Reserve Bank of New York**
- Previously head of **Morgan's Bankers Trust Company**
- One of seven participants at Jekyll Island secret meeting
- Joint nominee of **Morgan and Kuhn, Loeb and Company**

> "Strong owed his career to the favor of the Morgan bank.... He became Governor of the Federal Reserve Bank of New York as the joint nominee of Morgan and Kuhn, Loeb and Company." — **Professor Carroll Quigley**

### Strong-Norman Partnership (1920-1928)

- **Montagu Norman** made Governor of Bank of England in 1920
- **Close personal relationship** developed between Strong and Norman until Strong's death (1928)
- Norman considered eccentric, possibly mentally unbalanced

> "Norman was a strange man whose mental outlook was one of successfully suppressed hysteria or even paranoia. He had no use for government and feared democracy. Both of these seemed to him to be threats to private banking, and thus to all that was proper and precious in human life." — **Quigley**

- Norman rebuilt Bank of England as **"fortress prepared to defend itself against any popular revolt"**
- Gold reserves hidden in deep vaults below underground waters (could flood them by pressing button)
- Norman traveled incognito worldwide as **"Professor Skinner"** (black slouch hat, long black cloak)

### Their Shared Vision

- Determined to use **financial power of Britain and U.S.** to force gold standard worldwide
- Gold standard with **artificial value set for England's benefit**
- Central banks free from political control
- International finance settled by central bank agreements without government interference

### Frequent Secret Meetings

- Spent holidays together in Bar Harbor, Maine and Southern France
- Crossed Atlantic frequently to consult on world economy control plan
- **Lester Chandler**: "Their associations were so frequent and prolonged and their collaboration so close that it is still impossible to determine accurately their relative roles"
- Bank of England provided Strong with **office and private secretary** during visits
- Weekly exchange of private cables
- Meetings kept in **strict secrecy**
- Standard reply to press inquiries: just friends meeting for recreation

> "More secret than any ever held by Royal Arch Masons or by any Rosicrucian Order." — Norman's biographer **John Hargrave**

- By 1926: heads of **central banks of France and Germany** occasionally included in meetings

## Secret Meeting of 1927

### The Mauretania Arrival (July 1, 1927)

- **Montagu Norman** (Bank of England Governor) arrived in New York
- **Hjalmar Schacht** (German Reichsbank head) accompanied him
- Secrecy extreme — names didn't appear on passenger list, didn't meet with press
- Met with **Charles Rist** (Deputy Governor Banque de France)
- All conferred with **Benjamin Strong** (Federal Reserve Bank of New York Governor)

### Purpose: Prop Up Bank of England

- Weak reserve position of Bank of England was core problem
- Plan: Fed would **ease interest rates, encourage lending**
- Gold holders would seek higher returns in London
- Higher U.S. prices would ease competitive position of British industry and labor

### Galbraith's Translation

- Purpose: **Governor of Fed to deliberately create inflation in U.S.**
- Make American prices rise, U.S. goods less competitive, causing **American gold to move to Bank of England**
- Strong needed little convincing — already planned this with Norman
- Germans and French invited to enlist agreement to create inflation in their countries too
- Schacht and Rist had no real say — left early, leaving Strong and Norman to finalize details

### Strong's Priority: British Fortunes Over American

- Letter to Secretary of Treasury **Andrew Mellon** (May 1924): discussed lowering American interest rates for money expansion to raise American prices relative to Britain
- Goal: protect England from cutting wages, profits, and welfare

> "At the present time it is probably true that British prices for goods internationally dealt in are as a whole, roughly, in the neighborhood of 10 percent above our prices, and one of the preliminaries to the re-establishment of gold payment by Great Britain will be to facilitate a gradual readjustment of these price levels VCJOTC monetary reform is undertaken. In other words, this means some small advance in prices here and possibly some small decline in their prices...-"

> "The burden of this readjustment must fall more largely upon us than upon them. It will be difficult politically and socially for the British Government and the Bank of England to face a price liquidation in England ... in face of the fact that trade is poor and they have over a million unemployed people receiving government aid."

## Bringing Down the Dollar

### Mandrake Mechanism Goes Into High Gear (1924-1927)

**First surge (1924)**:
- Monetization of **$492 million in bonds** + nearly twice as much in banker's acceptances
- Total: ~**$1.3 billion** created

**Second surge (latter half 1927)** — immediately after Strong-Norman-Schacht-Rist meeting:
- Funding of **$225 million in government bonds** + **$220 million in banker's acceptances**
- Total increase in bank reserves: **$445 million**
- **Rediscount rate lowered from 4% to 3.5%** — easier for banks to borrow from Fed
- Banks create ~**5.5x what Fed creates** via fractional reserve
- **Total money flood: over $10 billion in six years**

### Results of the Inflation

- System demand for bonds pushed **interest rates down**
- People with gold sent it to London for higher yield — **America's gold supply began moving abroad**
- Inflation ate into dollar purchasing power
- **U.S. goods prices rose** in world markets → less competitive
- **U.S. exports declined**
- **Unemployment rose**
- **Low interest rates and easy credit → speculation in securities markets**
- System lunged full speed toward **Great Crash of 1929**

## H. Parker Willis Reflects

- Willis drafted the original Federal Reserve Act
- Appointed as **First Secretary of Board of Governors**
- By 1929: disillusioned with cartel

> "In the autumn of 1926 a group of bankers, among whom was one with a world famous name, were sitting at a table in a Washington hotel. One of them raised the question whether the low discount rates of the System were not likely to encourage speculation. 'Yes,' replied the conspicuous figure referred to, 'they will, but that cannot be helped. It is the price we must pay for helping Europe.'" — **Willis**, The North American Review, May 1929

### The Conspicuous Figure: J.P. Morgan Jr.

- **Jack Morgan** imbued with English tradition from earliest age
- Financial empire had roots in London, family business saved by Bank of England
- Spent **six months out of every year as resident of England**
- Insisted junior partners demonstrate **"loyalty to Britain"**
- Directed **Council on Foreign Relations** — American branch of secret society dedicated to British supremacy

> "It is only with that background that one can fully appreciate the willingness to sacrifice American interests. Indeed, 'it is the price we must pay for helping Europe.'"

### Strong's 1929 Letter to Parker Gilbert

- Strong pleased with accomplishment
- Letter written in 1929 to **Parker Gilbert** (American Agent for Reparations):

> "Our policy of the last four years, up to this January, has been effective in accomplishing the purpose for which it was designed. It has enabled monetary reorganization to be completed in Europe, which otherwise would haVe been impossible. It was undertaken with the well recognized hazard that we were liable to encounter a big speculation and some expansion of credit.. . Our course was perfectly obvious. We had to undertake it. The conditions permitted it, and the possibility of damage abroad was at a minimum."

- Damage abroad? "What about damage at home?"
- **Strong saw little difference** — forerunner of internationalists operating Fed ever since
- Viewed U.S. as one piece in complex world financial structure
- **"What was good for England was good for the world!"**

## The British-American Union

### One-World Government Strategy

- Many prominent American political/financial figures willing to **sacrifice U.S. interests for one-world government**
- Strategy unchanged since **Cecil Rhodes' society** and offspring **Round Table Groups**
- Merge English-speaking nations into single political entity
- Create similar groupings for other geopolitical regions
- Amalgamate all groupings into **global government** — the **"Parliament of Man"**
- Guess who plans to control that government from behind the scenes

### Andrew Carnegie's Vision

- Expressed in book **Triumphant Democracy**
- Concerned England was in decline as world power

> "Reunion with her American children is the only sure way to prevent continued decline.... Whatever obstructs reunion I oppose; whatever promotes reunion I favor. I judge all political questions from this standpoint...."

> "The Parliament of Man and the Federation of the World have already been hailed by the poet, and these mean a step much farther in advance of the proposed reunion of Britain and America.... I say that as surely as the sun in the heavens once shone upon Britain and America united, so surely is it one morning to rise, shine upon, and greet again the reunited state, 'The British-American Union.'" — **Andrew Carnegie**, Triumphant Democracy (1893)

## Summary — Chapter 20 Recap

### Post-Civil War Banking Chaos

- America experienced boom-bust cycles from fiat money creation
- **Half-way house to central banking** — not free/competitive, not full central bank
- **House of Morgan** prospered from others' failures
- Morgan had close ties to England's financial structure — **more British than American**
- Evidence suggests Morgan-Rothschild partnership throughout this period

### Benjamin Strong's Alliance with England

- **Strong** = Morgan man, first Governor of Federal Reserve Bank of New York
- Immediately allied with **Montagu Norman** (Bank of England Governor)
- Mission: **save English economy from depression**
- Accomplished by **deliberately creating inflation in U.S.**:
  - Gold outflow to London
  - Loss of foreign markets
  - Unemployment
  - Stock market speculation
- All factors propelled America into **crash of 1929 and Great Depression of the 30s**

### Connection to World Wars

- Same forces responsible for American involvement in **both world wars**
- Provided economic and military resources England needed to survive
- Key players part of **Cecil Rhodes secret society network** for British empire expansion

## Chapter Twenty-One: Competition Is a Sin

### Return to Jekyll Island

- Story of how **New York investment bankers formed cartel** to avoid competition
- Drafting of legislation to legalize cartel
- Strategy to camouflage true nature
- Failure of deception and defeat of bill

### Half-Way House to Central Banking (Revisited)

- Post-Civil War boom-busts blamed on "free and competitive banking"
- Actually result of **fiat money creation through federally chartered national banks**
- Dominated by handful of Wall Street firms = **half-way house to central banking**
- None truly free of state control nor competitive in traditional sense
- Government subsidized with monopolistic privileges

### What Wall Street Wanted

- America still lacked **"lender of last resort"**
- Lender of last resort = full central bank with power to create unlimited fiat money
- Can rush to aid of any bank under siege from depositors
- Only way bank can create money from nothing and be protected from "run"
- **Hidden tax of inflation** covers shortfall of fractional-reserve banking
- "So-called virtue of lender of last resort taught with great reverence today in virtually all academic institutions"

### Growing Dangers for Wall Street

- Banks could inflate more radically in unison than before
- When pushed too far, bank-generated booms still collapsed into recessions
- Highly profitable but also precarious
- Growing dread next collapse might overwhelm even Morgan & Company
- Many **state banks** (mostly in South and West) had escaped Wall-Street-Washington control
- By 1896: **61% non-national banks**, holding **54% of deposits**
- By 1913: **71% non-national banks**, holding **57% of deposits**
- Competition from state banks had to be stopped

### Industry Financing Itself

- Between 1900-1910: **70% of corporate growth funded internally** from profits (not borrowed capital)
- Industry increasingly independent of banks
- Bankers and businessmen wanted **"flexible" or "elastic" money supply**
- Would allow them to create money at will, driving interest rates down
- Make loans so attractive businessmen would have little choice but return to bankers' stable

## Trusts and Cartels Replace Competition

### Wall Street Consolidation

- Biggest investment houses (Morgan, Kuhn Loeb) remained competitors but were now **so large they ceased serious battle**
- Concept of **trusts and cartels** had dawned in America
- Joint ventures, market sharing, price fixing, mergers **more profitable than free-enterprise competition**

> "Wall Street was snowballing into one big, Morgan-dominated institution." — **Ron Chernow**

**December 1909 examples**:
- **Pierpont** bought majority stake in Equitable Life Assurance from **Thomas Fortune Ryan**
- Gave him influence over America's three biggest insurance companies (Mutual Life, Equitable, New York Life)
- **Bankers Trust** had taken over three other banks
- 1909: gained control of **Guaranty Trust** → converted into America's largest trust
- Core **Money Trust group** included J.P. Morgan and Company, First National Bank, National City Bank

### Interlocking Directorates

- Wall Street bankers incestuously swapped board seats
- Some banks had so many overlapping directors hard to separate them
- Banks shared large equity stakes in each other
- Why not merge? **Traditional American antipathy against concentrated financial power**
- Morgan-First National-National City trio feared public retribution if openly declared allegiance

### Birth of the Cartel Concept

- Interlocking directorates safer than open consolidation but had limitations
- Couldn't penetrate barriers of similar competitive groupings
- Ways sought to bring combines together at top rather than capture corporate entities
- Thus born: **cartel** = "community of interest" among businessmen in same field
- Mechanism for partnering at high level to reduce/eliminate competition

### Cartel Self-Destruct Mechanism

- Cartels have internal self-destruct mechanism
- Eventually one member becomes dissatisfied with agreed-upon share
- Decides to compete for greater market share
- Only way to prevent: **use police power of government to enforce cartel agreement**
- Laws disguised as consumer protection but actually worked to ensure elimination of competition

**Henry P. Davison** (Morgan partner) to Congressional committee (1912):
> "I would rather have regulation and control than free competition."

**John D. Rockefeller**:
> "Competition is a sin."

### Progressivism = Compulsory Cartelization

- After 1896-1900: America entered **progressive, predominantly Republican era**
- **"Progressivism"** began invading every aspect of American economic life
- Railroads led with formation of **ICC (1880s)**
- Field after field centralized and cartelized in name of "efficiency," "stability," "progress," "general welfare"
- **J.P. Morgan interests** gathered in National Civic Federation and think tanks
- Saw voluntary cartels and industrial mergers of late 1890s failed to achieve monopoly prices
- Decided to turn to governments (state and federal) to curb competition and establish **compulsory cartels** disguised as "curbing big business monopoly"

### Challenge: Keeping New Competitors Out

- No longer how to overcome adversaries, but **how to keep new ones from entering**
- When **John D. Rockefeller** used Standard Oil profits to control Chase National Bank and **William Rockefeller** bought National City Bank of New York, **Morgan** had to allow them into the club
- Once in, all agreed **influx of competitors had to be stopped**
- Hidden purpose of federal legislation and government control

> "The sheer magnitude of many of the mergers, culminating in U.S. Steel, soon forced him [Morgan] to modify his stand, though at times he would have preferred total control. More important, by 1898 he could not ignore the massive power of new financial competitors and had to treat them with deference. Standard Oil Company, utilizing National City Bank for its investments, had fixed resources substantially larger than Morgan's, and by 1899 was ready to move into the general economy." — **Gabriel Kolko**

### Northern Securities Battle

- Test came in **Northern Securities battle** (expensive draw)
- Morgan and Standard paid deference to each other thereafter
- Mutual toleration among bankers increased sharply
- **"Benign armed neutrality, rather than positive affection"** explains interlocks among five major New York banking houses

> "This remarkable welding together of great corporate interests could not, of course, have been accomplished if the 'masters of capital' in Wall Street had not themselves during the same period become more closely allied. The rivalry of interests which was so characteristic during the reorganization period a few years before had very largely disappeared. Although the two great groups of financiers, represented on the one hand by Morgan and his allies and on the other by the Standard Oil forces, were still distinguishable, they were now working in practical harmony on the basis of a sort of mutual 'community of interest' of their own. Thus the control of capital and credit through banking resources tended to become concentrated in the hands of fewer and fewer men. Before long it could be said, indeed, that two rival banking groups no longer existed, but that one vast and harmonious banking power had taken their place." — **John Moody** (1919)

## The Aldrich-Vreeland Act

### Crisis of 1907 Changes Everything

- Monetary contractions of 1879 and 1893 handled fairly easily by Wall Street without government
- **Crisis of 1907** pushed resources to abyss
- Two changes needed:
  - **All remnants of banking competition eliminated** and replaced by national cartel
  - Far greater sums of fiat money available to protect from future depositor runs
- No question Congress would have to be partner to use government power

> "The crisis of 1907, on the other hand, found the combined banking structure of New York inadequate to meet the challenge, and chastened any obstreperous financial powers who thought they might build their fortunes independently of the entire banking community.... The nation had grown too large, banking had become too complex. Wall Street, humbled and almost alone, turned from its own resources to the national government." — **Kolko**

### Aldrich-Vreeland Act (1908)

**Two main objectives**:

1. **Authorized national banks to issue emergency currency (script)** to substitute for regular money when unable to pay depositors
   - Script used during 1907 panic with partial success but no legal foundation
   - Now Congress made it legal
   - "New legislation regularized these arrangements. This could be done against the security of sundry bonds and commercial loans—these could, in effect, be turned into cash without being sold."

2. **Created National Monetary Commission** to study American banking problems and make recommendations to Congress
   - Nine senators and nine representatives
   - Vice-Chairman: **Representative Edward Vreeland** (banker from Buffalo)
   - Chairman: **Senator Nelson Aldrich**

### Aldrich Commission Sham

- Obvious from start: Commission was sham
- **Aldrich conducted virtually a one-man show**
- No official meetings for almost two years
- Aldrich toured Europe consulting with **top central bankers of England, France, and Germany**
- **$300,000 tax dollars** spent on junkets
- Only tangible product: **38 massive volumes** of history of European banking
- **None of Commission members consulted** regarding official recommendations issued by Aldrich in their name
- Actually work of **Aldrich and six men who were not even members of Commission**
- Report drafted in **plush private hunting resort in Georgia** (not Congressional conference room in Washington)

### Return to Jekyll Island

- Cold, blustery night at New Jersey railway station
- **Seven men** representing one-fourth of wealth of world boarded Aldrich private car
- Clandestine journey to Jekyll Island

## The Jekyll Island Plan

### Five Primary Objectives

1. **Stop growing influence of small, rival banks** and insure control over nation's financial resources would remain in hands of those present

2. **Make money supply more elastic** to reverse trend of private capital formation and recapture industrial loan market

3. **Pool meager reserves of all nation's banks** into one large reserve to protect from depositor runs

(Note: Pages end mid-sentence describing the Jekyll Island meeting objectives)

<!-- pp. 501-520 -->

## Chapter 21: Competition Is a Sin (continued)

### Jekyll Island Strategy: Five Objectives

The Jekyll Island group had five objectives:
- Stop bank runs by creating large reserve pools
- Create a lender of last resort with unlimited fiat money creation
- Pool reserves to prevent currency drains
- Shift inevitable losses from bank owners to taxpayers
- Convince Congress the scheme protected the public

First two objectives: achieved through proper drafting and vocabulary manipulation
Third and fourth: achieved by establishing a lender of last resort (central bank with unlimited fiat money creation)
Fifth objective (convincing Congress): required careful planning and execution

**Paul Warburg** emerged as the group's chief theoretician. Most technical matters followed his advice with minor disagreements.

### The Public Relations Plan

Eight-step strategy to sell the cartel to Congress and the public:
1. Don't call it a cartel or central bank
2. Make it appear to be a government agency
3. Create regional branches to suggest decentralization (not Wall Street domination)
4. Start with conservative structure, knowing provisions could be altered later
5. Use public anger from recent panics to create demand for reform
6. Present Jekyll Island plan as the response to that demand
7. Employ university professors for academic credibility
8. Publicly oppose the plan to suggest Wall Street doesn't want it

> "Competition is a sin." — **John D. Rockefeller** (implied philosophy)

### Naming Strategy: Avoiding "Central Bank"

**Public opposition to central banks was fierce.** Congressman **Everis Hayes** (California): "Our people have set their faces like steel against a central bank." Senator **John Shafroth** (Colorado): "The Democratic Party is opposed to a central bank."

Solution: avoid the word "bank" entirely, create image of federal government itself.

**Nathaniel Wright Stephenson** (Senator Aldrich's biographer): Aldrich wanted to transplant the Bank of England system to America but knew opposition required semantic camouflage. "It was his thought to outflank the opposition by having not one central bank but many. And the word bank would itself be avoided."

**Frank Vanderlip**: "The law as enacted provided for twelve banks instead of one... but the intent of the law was to coordinate the twelve through the Federal Reserve Board in Washington, so that in effect they would operate as a central bank."

The cartel nature was obvious to insiders. **Aldrich** admitted: "The organization proposed is not a bank, but a cooperative union of all the banks of the country for definite purposes."

**A. Barton Hepburn** (Chase National Bank), two years later: "The measure recognizes and adopts the principles of a central bank. Indeed, if it works out as the sponsors of the law hope, it will make all incorporated banks together joint owners of a central dominating power."

### Paul Warburg's Master Plan

**Professor Edwin Seligman** (J&W Seligman family, head of Economics at Columbia University) praised Warburg's role:

> "It was in my study that Mr. Warburg first conceived the idea of presenting his views to the public... In its fundamental features the Federal Reserve Act is the work of Mr. Warburg more than any other man in the country.... The existence of a Federal Reserve Board creates, in everything but in name, a real central bank."

Warburg's strategy: present plan conservatively, break down public prejudice gradually, include elaborate safeguards knowing they could be eliminated over time. His goal was practical implementation with gradual education of the public.

### The Aldrich Bill

First draft submitted by **Nelson Aldrich** but actually written by **Frank Vanderlip** and **Benjamin Strong**. Though co-authored by Congressman **Vreeland**, it became known as the **Aldrich Bill**.

**Edward B. Vreeland** wrote in *The Independent* (August 25, 1910): "The bank I propose... is an ideal method of fighting monopoly. It could not possibly itself become a monopoly and it would prevent other banks combining into monopolies. With earnings limited to four and one-half per cent, there could not be a monopoly."

**This statement is brilliantly insidious through half-truths:**
- True: monopolies can't operate at 4.5% interest
- Untrue: Federal Reserve banks weren't limited to that low rate
- True: 4% was stated stock dividend
- Also true: real profits came from harvesting interest on fiat money, operating on smaller safety margins while protected from bankruptcy, and insider access to money-making data before competitors
- Profits from such advantages would equal or exceed the Mandrake Mechanism

The Aldrich Bill was **NOT about government disappearance from banking** — it marked government's appearance as partner with private bankers, enforcer of their cartel.

### Aldrich Bill Structure

Similar to old Bank of the United States in many ways:
- Convert federal debt into money
- Loan that money to government
- Control regional banks
- Be depository of government funds

**Critical difference: much greater power than the old central bank.**

For the first time, a banking institution's paper notes would become **legal tender** — mandatory acceptance for public and private debts. Refusing these notes = prison.

Notes would display "The United States of America" and the Treasury seal, with the Treasurer's signature prominently placed — all designed to convince the public this was a government agency.

### Turning Opposition Against Itself

Genuine opposition existed to Wall Street financial concentration. Leading critics: **Senator Robert LaFollette** (Wisconsin) and **Congressman Charles Lindbergh** (Minnesota).

When LaFollette publicly charged the country was controlled by just fifty men, the monetary scientists didn't deny it. **George F. Baker** (J.P. Morgan partner), when asked by reporters, replied it was absurd — he knew personally the number was not more than eight.

**The bankers' counter-strategy:**
1. Set up Congressional committee to investigate the money trust
2. Staff committee with friends of the trust
3. Conceal full scope while revealing enough to intensify public clamor for reform
4. Once political climate was hot enough, put forward Aldrich Bill as the answer

**Congressman Lindbergh** explained the pattern:

> "Ever since the Civil War, Congress has allowed the bankers to completely control financial legislation. The membership of the Finance Committee in the Senate and the Committee on Banking and Currency in the House, has been made up of bankers, their agents and attorneys. These committees have controlled the nature of the bills to be reported, the extent of them, and the debates that were to be held on them when they were being considered in the Senate and the House. No one, not on the committee, is recognized... unless someone favorable to the committee has been arranged for."

### The Pujo Committee

Subcommittee of House Committee on Banking and Currency, conducted the "Money Trust" investigation of 1912. Chairman: **Arsene Pujo** (Louisiana), regarded by many as Oil Trust spokesman.

Eight months of hearings produced volumes of statistics and Wall Street banker testimony. **No questions asked about:**
- Foreign investment houses
- Response to competition from new banks
- Plans to protect speculative banks from currency drains
- Motives for wanting artificially low interest rates
- Formula for passing losses to taxpayers

Public given impression of serious investigation; reality was "fireside chat between old friends."

**Lindbergh and LaFollette were denied access to testify.** Only witnesses: bankers themselves and their friends.

**Gabriel Kolko**: "Fortunately for the reformers, the Pujo Committee swung into high gear in its investigation of the Money Trust during the summer of 1912 and for eight months frightened the nation with its awesome, if inconclusive, statistics on the power of Wall Street over the nation's economy."

**Key finding: Five banking firms held 341 directorships in 112 corporations with aggregate capitalization over $22 billion.**

The spectacle made banking reform a serious topic, but ironically the biggest advocates of reform were the bankers themselves — just with a different agenda.

**Paul Warburg** of Kuhn, Loeb & Company spent seven years before the Federal Reserve Act traveling the country giving reform speeches and writing scholarly articles, including an eleven-part series for *The New York Times*. Representatives from Morgan and Rockefeller houses joined in, making regular appearances. Yet no one questioned this obvious conflict of interest.

### Enlisting Academia

Big-name banker speeches served to establish technical arguments. To reach voters with credibility, academia was recruited.

Banks contributed **$5 million** to an "educational" fund, which flowed into Princeton, Harvard, and University of Chicago — all recipients of large endowments from industry/finance captains.

Economics was becoming a respectable new field. Talented but hungry professors were eager to expound Jekyll Island virtues for grants or prestigious appointments — and gain national recognition as pioneers in the new field.

**J.K. Galbraith**:

> "Under Aldrich's direction a score or more of studies of monetary institutions in the United States and, more particularly, in other countries were commissioned from the emergent economics profession. It is at least possible that the reverence in which the Federal Reserve System has since been held by economists owes something to the circumstance that so many who pioneered in the profession participated also in its [the System's] birth."

### The National Citizens' League

Principal accomplishment of the bank's educational fund: creating the **National Citizens' League**.

Entirely financed and controlled by banks under Paul Warburg's personal guidance, it presented itself as concerned citizens seeking banking reform. Function: disseminate hundreds of thousands of pamphlets, organize letter-writing campaigns to Congressmen, supply quotable material to news media, create illusion of grass-roots support for Jekyll Island plan.

**Nathaniel Stephenson**: "The league was non-partisan. It was careful to abstain from emphasizing Senator Aldrich.... First and last, hundreds of thousands of dollars were spent by the league in popularizing financial science."

**J. Laurence Laughlin** chosen to head the effort — economics professor at University of Chicago (endowed by Rockefeller with nearly $50 million). **Kolko**: "Laughlin, nominally very orthodox in his commitment to laissez faire theory, was nevertheless a leading academic advocate of banking legislation... and was sensitive to the needs of banking as well as the realities of politics."

**Stephenson**: "Professor Laughlin of the University of Chicago was given charge of the League's propaganda."

**Congressman Lindbergh** added: "The reader knows that the University of Chicago is an institution endowed by John D. Rockefeller with nearly fifty million dollars. It may truly be said to be the Rockefeller University."

Laughlin undoubtedly believed in the Jekyll Island plan's virtue and pursued his assignment with enthusiasm. But he was selected precisely because he supported a partnership between banking and government as substitute for "destructive" competition — if he didn't honestly agree with Rockefeller that competition was a sin, he probably never would have received a professorship.

### Wilson and Wall Street

**Woodrow Wilson** brought into national spotlight through his banking reform views. Previously noted: Wilson's presidential nomination at 1912 Democratic convention was largely due to **Col. Edward Mandell House**'s influence.

Ten years earlier (1902), Wilson elected president of Princeton University — position impossible without University benefactor concurrence among Wall Street bankers. Particularly close with **Andrew Carnegie**, became Carnegie Foundation trustee.

Two most generous donors: **Cleveland H. Dodge** and **Cyrus McCormick** (directors of Rockefeller's National City Bank), part of Wall Street elite the Pujo Committee described as the "Money Trust." Both had been Wilson's classmates at Princeton.

When Wilson returned to Princeton as professor (1890), Dodge and McCormick (by reason of their wealth, University trustees) personally advanced his career.

**Ferdinand Lundberg** (*America's Sixty Families*):

> "For nearly twenty years before his nomination Woodrow Wilson had moved in the shadow of Wall Street.... In 1898 Wilson, his salary unsatisfactory, besieged with offers of many university presidencies threatened to resign. Dodge and McCormick thereupon constituted themselves his financial guardians, and agreed to raise the additional informal stipendium that kept him at Princeton. The contributors to this private fund were Dodge, McCormick, and Moses Taylor Pyne and Percy R. Pyne, of the family that founded the National City Bank. In 1902 this same group arranged Wilson's election as president of the university."

Wilson often spoke glowingly of vast corporations' rise and praised J.P. Morgan as great American leader. He accepted conclusions about controlled economy value:

> "The old time of individual competition is probably gone by... It may come back; I don't know; it will not come back within our time, I dare say."

**H.S. Kenan**: "Woodrow Wilson, President of Princeton University was the first prominent educator to speak in favor of the Aldrich Plan a gesture which immediately brought him the Governorship of New Jersey and later the Presidency of the United States. During the panic of 1907, Wilson declared that: 'all this trouble could be averted if we appointed a committee of six or seven public-spirited men like J.I. Morgan to handle the affairs of our country.'"

### Opposition to the Aldrich Bill

Disagreement at Jekyll Island over naming. **Warburg** (master psychologist) wanted "National Reserve Bill" or "Federal Reserve Bill" to conjure dual images of government and reserves (both subconsciously appealing).

**Aldrich** (personal ego) insisted his name be attached. **Warburg** pointed out Aldrich's name was associated with Wall Street interests in public mind — unnecessary obstacle.

Long heated debate. Politician's ego won over banker's logic.

**Warburg was right.** Aldrich well known as Republican spokesman for big business and banking. Loyal ties publicized by recently sponsored tariff bills protecting tobacco and rubber trusts. The Aldrich name made the bill an easy target.

**December 15, 1911**, Congressman Lindbergh rose before the House:

> "The Aldrich Plan is the Wall Street Plan. It is a broad challenge to the government by the champion of the money trust. It means another pank, if necessary, to intimidate the people. Aldrich, paid by the government to represent the people, proposes a plan for the trust."

The Aldrich Bill never came to vote. Republicans lost House control (1910), then Senate and Presidency (1912). Aldrich voted out by constituents. The ball was now in Democrats' court — and their new president, Woodrow Wilson.

## Chapter 22: The Creature Swallows Congress

### The 1912 Election

The election of 1912 was a textbook example of power politics and voter deception.

Republican President **William Howard Taft** up for reelection. Political power based on big-business and banking support in industrial regions. Elected first term expecting to continue predecessor **Teddy Roosevelt's** protectionist policies (cartel markets for sugar, coffee, fruit from Latin America). In office, he became more restrained, earning animosity from powerful Republicans.

**Ultimate breach: Taft refused to support the Aldrich Plan.** He objected not because it created a central bank imposing government control, but because it didn't offer enough government control. He recognized Jekyll Island formula placed bankers in driver's seat with only nominal government participation. He wanted greater share for political side.

Bankers not adverse to negotiating balance of power, but needed a man in White House who would champion the plan and use presidential influence to garner Congressional support. From that moment, Taft marked for political extinction.

### The Bull Moose Candidate

**Teddy Roosevelt** persuaded by Morgan's deputies (**George Perkins** and **Frank Munsey**) to challenge Taft for Party nomination. When that failed, persuaded to run as "Bull Moose" candidate on Progressive Party ticket.

Unclear what motivated Roosevelt, but **intent of backers was clear: they didn't expect Roosevelt to win** — as former Republican President, they knew he would split the Party and pull votes from Taft, putting Wilson in White House.

Presidential campaigns need money. Republican Party well financed by same individuals who wanted to see its candidate defeated. Solution: provide financial resources for all three candidates, with special attention to Wilson and Roosevelt.

**Ron Chernow**: "By 1924, the House of Morgan was so influential in American politics that conspiracy buffs couldn't tell which presidential candidate was more beholden to the bank."

**Ferdinand Lundberg**:

> "J.P. Morgan and Company played the leading role in the national election of 1912.... Roosevelt's preconvention backers were George W. Perkins and Frank Munsey. These two, indeed, encouraged Roosevelt to contest Taft's nomination. Munsey functioned in the newspaper field for J.P. Morgan and Company — buying, selling, creating, and suppressing newspapers in consonance with J.P. Morgan's shifting needs. Perkins resigned from J.P. Morgan and Company on January 1, 1911, to assume a larger political role.... Throughout the three-cornered fight, Roosevelt had Munsey and George Perkins constantly at his heels, supplying money, going over his speeches, bringing people from Wall Street in to help, and, in general, carrying the entire burden of the campaign against Taft.... Perkins and J.P. Morgan and Company were the substance of the Progressive Party; everything else was trimming.... Munsey's cash contribution to the Progressive Party brought his total political outlay for 1912 to $229,255.72. Perkins made their joint contribution more than $500,000, and Munsey expended $1,000,000 in cash additionally to acquire from Henry Einstein the New York PfeSS so that Roosevelt would have a New York City morning newspaper. Perkins and Munsey, as the Clapp [Senate Privileges and Election] Committee learned from Roosevelt himself, also underwrote the heavy expense of Roosevelt's campaign train. In short, most of Roosevelt's campaign fund was supplied by the two Morgan hatchet men who were seeking Taft's scalp."

Within Kuhn, Loeb & Company: **Felix Warburg** dutifully putting money into Republican campaign as expected, but brother **Paul Warburg** and **Jacob Schiff** backed Wilson, while another partner **Otto Kahn** supported Roosevelt. Other prominent Republicans contributing to Democratic campaign: **Bernard Baruch**, **Henry Morganthau**, and **Thomas Fortune Ryan**. The Rockefeller component equally involved.

**William McAdoo** (Wilson's national campaign vice chairman): **Cleveland Dodge** of Rockefeller's National City Bank personally contributed $51,300 — more than one-fourth total raised from all other sources. McAdoo: "He was a Godsend."

**Ferdinand Lundberg** describes Dodge as "the financial genius behind Woodrow Wilson":

> "Wilson's nomination represented a personal triumph for Cleveland H. Dodge, director of the National City Bank, scion of the Dodge copper and munitions fortune.... The nomination represented no less a triumph for Ryan, Harvey, and J.P. Morgan and Company. Sitting with Dodge as co-directors of the National City Bank at the time were the younger J.P. Morgan, now the head of the [Morgan] firm, Jacob Schiff, William Rockefeller, J. Ogden Armour, and James Stillman. In short, except for George F. Baker, everyone whom the Pujo Committee had termed rulers of the 'Money Trust' was in this bank."

Monetary scientists carefully selected their candidate and cleared the way for victory. Maneuver was brilliant. Who would suspect Wall Street would support a Democrat, especially when Party platform contained: "We oppose the so-called Aldrich Bill or the establishment of a central bank; and... what is known as the money trust."

**Irony:** Party of working man, Party of Thomas Jefferson (formed generations earlier specifically to oppose a central bank) now cheering a new leader who was political captive of Wall Street bankers and who had agreed to hidden agenda of establishing the Federal Reserve System.

**George Harvey** later boasted financiers "felt no animosity toward Mr. Wilson for such of his utterances as they regarded as radical and menacing to their interests. He had simply played the political game."

**William McAdoo** (destined to become Secretary of Treasury) saw what was happening from ringside seat:

> "The major contributions to any candidate's campaign fund are made by men who have axes to grind — and the campaign chest is the grindstone.... The fact is that there is a serious danger of this country becoming a pluto-democracy; that is, a sham republic with the real government in the hands of a small clique of enormously wealthy men, who speak through their money, and whose influence, even today, radiates to every corner of the United States. Experience has shown that the most practicable method of getting hold of a political party is to furnish it with money in large quantities. This brings the big money-giver or givers into close communion with the party leaders. Contact and influence do the rest."

### The Money Trust They Love to Hate

Roosevelt actually had very little interest in banking issue, probably because he didn't understand it. Furthermore, in unlikely event the blustery "trust buster" would actually win, financiers had little to fear. Despite well-publicized stance opposing big business, his true convictions were quite acceptable to Wall Street.

**Chernow** observed: [Roosevelt's views were aligned with accepting consolidation and controlled economy]

> "The old time of individual competition is probably gone by... It may come back; I don't know; it will not come back within our time, I dare say."


<!-- pp. 521-540 -->

## The Roosevelt-Morgan Alliance

- **TR and Morgan relationship** was complex, not simple "trust buster vs trust king"
- Roosevelt saw trusts as "natural, organic outgrowths of economic development" — stopping them was "like trying to dam the Mississippi River"
- Both disliked 19th-century rugged individualism and favored big business
- Public wrangling between them was "shadow play, a pretense of greater animosity than actually existed"

> "Roosevelt and Morgan were secret blood brothers." — Author characterization

- **Paul Warburg noted in January 1912** (ten months before election) that Teddy had been "fairly won over to a favorable consideration of the Aldrich Plan"
- Wilson and Roosevelt both **privately financed by Wall Street's most powerful bankers**, publicly campaigned against "Money Trust"
- Roosevelt: currency issue should be "lodged with the government and be protected from domination and manipulation by Wall Street"
- Roosevelt repeatedly quoted **Bull Moose platform**: "We are opposed to the so-called Aldrich Currency Bill because its provisions would place our currency and credit system in private hands"
- Wilson declared: "There has come about an extraordinary and very sinister concentration in the control of business in the country"

### 1912 Election Outcome

- Wilson won with only **42% of popular vote** — 58% voted against him
- Had Roosevelt not entered race, Taft would have won and Wilson "would have become a footnote"
- **Colonel House later confirmed**: "Wilson was elected by Teddy Roosevelt"

## The Role of Colonel House

### House's Background and Power

- Educated in England, father represented England's merchant interests in American South
- Came through **London Connection**
- Key role: maneuvered US into WWI on Britain's side, rescued Morgan loans to Britain and France
- Responsible for Wilson's nomination at Democratic convention
- Became **Wilson's constant companion, personal adviser, political superior**
- House guided Wilson on all foreign and economic policy

**Arthur Smith (1918)**: House "holds a power never wielded before in this country by any man out of office, a power greater than that of any political boss or Cabinet member"

**George Viereck**: House was "Chief Magistracy of the Republic," "Super-ambassador," "The pilot who guided the ship"

> "For six years two rooms were at his disposal in the North Wing of the White House. In work and play their thoughts were one. House was the double of Wilson. It was House who made the slate for the Cabinet, formulated the first policies of the Administration and practically directed the foreign affairs of the United States. We had, indeed, two Presidents for one!" — George Viereck

### House's Journal Entries (Command Post Evidence)

- **December 19, 1912**: Talked with Paul Warburg about currency reform, told of Washington trip to get it in working order
- **March 24, 1913**: Met with Carter Glass, advised Wilson that McAdoo and House would "whip the Glass measure into final shape, which he could endorse and take to Owen as his own"
- **March 27, 1913**: J.P. Morgan Jr. and Mr. Denny came with currency plan already formulated and printed — House suggested it be typewritten "so it would not seem too prearranged"
- **October 19, 1913**: Saw Senator Reed, discussed currency; Paul Warburg first caller; Senator Murray Crane followed
- **November 17, 1913**: Paul Warburg disturbed about currency situation, requested interview with Schiff and Dodge
- **January 21, 1914**: After dinner Wilson and House went to President's study, began work on Federal Reserve Board appointments

### House as the Real President

- Wilson admitted: "The greatest embarrassment of my political life has been that active duties seem to deprive me of time for careful investigation. I seem almost obliged to form conclusions from impressions instead of from study"
- **Charles Seymour**: "Colonel House was indefatigable in providing for the President the knowledge that he sought.... The Colonel was the unseen guardian angel of the bill"

## Death of the Aldrich Plan

- Warburg and **Professor Laughlin** agreed: inadvisable to have Aldrich's name on any banking bill now that Democrats controlled Congress and White House
- **Laughlin in Banking Reform periodical**: "It is progress that the Aldrich plan came and went. It is progress that the people have been aroused and interested" — now free to help get "a proper bill adopted by the Democrats" that "in non-essentials... could be made different from the old plan"

### Carter Glass and the New Bill

- Democrats began new proposal even before 1912 election
- Most outspoken Aldrich critic: **Congressman Carter Glass** (Virginia), Democratic Chairman of House Banking and Currency Committee
- Glass objected to Aldrich Bill: lacked government control, concentrated power in larger NY banks, opened door to inflation, dishonest cost estimates, established banking monopoly
- Glass hired **Henry Parker Willis** (economics teacher from Washington and Lee University) to write the bill
- Willis was **former student and protege of Professor Laughlin**, retained by National Citizens' League as technical writer
- Throughout spring 1912, Willis wrote Laughlin about work for Glass Committee, relationship to superior, Washington gossip
- Laughlin, House, and Glass consulted with major bankers about reform
- House met with **Frick, Otto Kahn, Vanderlip, J.P. Morgan Jr.** and others
- Steady communications with Glass, House, and Wilson throughout February-March 1913
- Wilson and Glass both admitted they "knew nothing" about banking theory or practice
- **The entire banking reform movement, at all crucial stages, was centralized in hands of a few men** linked ideologically and personally

## The Glass-Owen Bill Emerges

### Glass's Official Objections to Aldrich Bill

In 1913 Committee House Report, Glass listed problems:
- Lacked government control
- Concentrated power in larger New York banks
- Opened door to inflation
- Dishonest cost estimates
- Established banking monopoly

### The Bill's True Nature

- Glass brought forth bill drafted by **Willis and inspired by Laughlin**
- In every important detail: "merely the old corpse of the Aldrich Bill pulled from its casket, freshly perfumed, and dressed in a new suit"
- Reconciled with **Senator Robert L. Owen** as co-sponsor → became **Glass-Owen Bill**
- Owen was president of Oklahoma bank, made trips to Europe to study central banks of England and Germany
- **Warburg published side-by-side comparison** of Aldrich and Glass proposals showing they agreed on all essential provisions, even contained identical wording in entire sections
- Warburg: "Brushing aside, then, the external differences affecting the 'shells,' we find the 'kernels' of the two systems very closely resembling and related to one another"

### Staged Public Hearings

- Glass staged public hearings "for announced purpose of giving everyone a chance for input"
- **Complete sham** — first draft already completed in secret months before hearings
- Congressman Lindbergh and other Jekyll Island plan opponents **not allowed to speak**
- Hearings widely reported; public given impression favorable testimony was representative
- **Kolko**: "Although they were careful to keep the contents of their work confidential... The public assumption of the hearing was that no bills had been drafted, and Willis 1 draft was never mentioned, much less revealed.... The hearings of Glass 1 subcommittee in January and February, 1913, were nothing less than a love feast"

## Bankers Become Divided

- Lesser bankers were also targeted for deception
- **February 1911**: 22 of country's most powerful bankers met three days in Atlantic City behind closed doors
- Strategy: get smaller banks to support using government to authorize and maintain cartel
- Objective discussed: proposed cartel would bring smaller banks under control of larger ones, "but that this fact had to be obscured when presenting it to them for endorsement"

### American Bankers Association Vote

- Annual meeting held months later, resolution endorsing Aldrich Bill steam-rolled through
- Many present dismayed, including **Andrew Frame** (Western banker)
- Frame testified at Glass subcommittee hearings: when monetary bill given to country before ABA meeting in New Orleans 1911, "not one banker in a hundred who had read that bill"
- **General Hamby of Austin, Texas** wrote President Watts asking for hearing against bill — "did not get a very courteous answer"
- Frame: "They would not allow anyone on the program who was not in favor of the bill"
- Glass refrained from commenting on unfairness of allowing only one side — "exactly what he was then doing with his own agenda"

### Public Opposition Theater

- As Glass-Owen Bill moved closer to birth, **Aldrich and Vanderlip** threw themselves into "great public display of opposition"
- Every opportunity used to express "eternal animosity to this monstrous legislation"
- Vanderlip: warned against evils of fiat money and rampant inflation
- Aldrich: Glass-Owen Bill was inimical to sound banking and good government
- Vanderlip: predicted speculation and instability
- Aldrich: bill was "revolutionary in its character" (implying Bolshevistic), "will be the first and most important step toward changing our form of government from a democracy to an autocracy"

## The Pretense Is Dropped

### Vanderlip's Debate Before New York Economic Society (Nov 13, 1913)

- 1,100 bankers and businessmen present
- Vanderlip under pressure before impressive group
- In moment of desperation, **finally dropped the pretense**: "For years, bankers have been almost the sole advocates of just this sort of legislation that it is now hoped we will have, and it is unfair to accuse them of being in opposition to sound legislation"
- **22 years later, Vanderlip wrote in Saturday Evening Post**: "Although the Aldrich Federal Reserve Plan was defeated when it bore the name Aldrich, nevertheless its essential points were all contained in the plan that finally was adopted"

### McAdoo's Revelation

**Treasury Secretary William McAdoo**:
> "Bankers fought the Federal Reserve legislation—and every provision of the Federal Reserve Act—with the tireless energy of men fighting a forest fire. They said it was populistic, socialistic, half-baked, destructive, infantile, badly conceived, and unworkable.... These interviews with bankers led me to an interesting conclusion. 1 perceived gradually, through all the haze and smoke of controversy, that the banking world was not really as opposed to the bill as it pretended to be."

### Mass Psychology Strategy

- **Key to entire episode: mass psychology**
- Since Aldrich associated with Morgan interests and Vanderlip was President of Rockefeller's National City Bank, public skillfully led to believe "Money Trust" was afraid of proposed Federal Reserve Act
- **The Nation** was only prominent publication pointing out every horror described by Aldrich and Vanderlip "could have been equally ascribed to the Aldrich Bill as well"
- Voice easily drowned by "great cacophony of deception and propaganda"

### Designed Flexibility

- Glass Bill was **flexible document designed to be altered in non-essential matters** to appear as though compromises being made
- Strategy: focus debate on relatively unimportant items (number of regional banks, governing board structure, board selection process)
- When crucial matters couldn't be avoided: agree to almost anything but **write provisions in vague language**
- Goal: "get the bill passed and perfect it later"

## Bryan Makes an Ultimatum

- **William Jennings Bryan** — most influential Democrat in Congress
- Federal Reserve Act could not be passed without his approval and support
- **Charles Seymour**: "The Commoner's sense of loyalty [to the Party] had kept him from an attack upon the Federal Reserve Act which, it would appear, he never entirely understood.... With his influence in the Party, he could have destroyed the measure which failed to accord with his personal doctrines"

### Bryan's Two Demands

Bryan would not support any bill resulting in private money being issued by private banks. When shown actual draft (midsummer 1913), dismayed to find:

1. Money to be privately issued
2. Entire governing body of central bank to be composed of private bankers

**His ultimatum**:
1. Federal-Reserve notes must be **Treasury currency, issued and guaranteed by government**
2. Governing body must be **appointed by President and approved by Senate**

### Strategic Deception

- House and Warburg feared if they waited for everything, would get nothing or opponents would pass real reform bill
- **Willis** agreed: "It is much better to take a half a loaf rather than to be absolutely deprived of a chance of getting any bread whatsoever.... The so-called 'progressive' element—such as Lindbergh and his supporters—will be encouraged to enact dangerous legislation"
- **Glass** echoed: "Unless the conservative bankers of the country are willing to yield something and get behind the bill, we shall get legislation very much less to be desired, or have nothing done at all"

## An Amazing Revelation

### Carter Glass's Admission

Years later in **Adventures in Constructive Finance**, Glass revealed deception:

After Bryan delivered ultimatum, Glass summoned to White House. Wilson told him decision made to make Federal Reserve notes obligations of US government.

> "I was for an instant speechless!" — Glass

Glass reminded Wilson only backing for new currency would be: small amount of gold, large amount of government and commercial debt, and private assets of individual banks themselves.

> "It would be a pretense on its face. Was there ever a government note based primarily on the property of banking institutions? Was there ever a government issue not one dollar of which could be put out except by demand of a bank? The suggested government obligation is so remote it could never be discovered."

**Wilson replied**:
> "Exactly so, Glass. Every word you say is true; the government liability is a mere thought. And so, if we can hold the substance of the thing and give the other fellow the shadow, why not do it, if thereby we may save our bill?"

### Warburg's Confirmation

**Paul Warburg later explained**:
> "While technically and legally the Federal Reserve note is an obligation of the United States Government, in reality it is an obligation, the sole actual responsibility for which rests on the reserve banks.... The government could only be called upon to take them up after the reserve banks had failed."

**Author's analysis**: "The man who masterminded the Federal Reserve System is telling us that Federal Reserve notes constitute privately issued money with the taxpayers standing by to cover the potential losses of those banks which issue it."

This confirms: one objective set forth at Jekyll Island meeting was **shifting cartel's losses from bank owners to taxpayers**. Warburg himself confirmed it.

### Second Compromise

Bryan's second demand (political control over System, not banker control) met with "equally beguiling 'compromise'":
- In addition to governing board of regional bankers previously proposed
- Now would be **central regulatory commission: Federal Reserve Board**, appointed by President with advice and consent of Senate

**Wilson**: "the banks may be instruments, not the masters, of business and of individual enterprise and initiative"

### Reality of the Arrangement

- Heralded as "bold, new experiment in representative government"
- Reality: **return of ancient partnership between monetary and political scientists**
- Only thing new: power now shared openly in public view
- But most deliberations and decisions behind closed doors
- Division of power and responsibility between groups left **deliberately vague**
- Without detailed line of command or clear concept of function, inevitable that real power would gravitate to those with "technical" knowledge and Wall Street connections
- To monetary scientists drafting bill and engineering compromises, "the eventual concentration of effective control into their hands was never in serious doubt"

## Bryan Endorses the Bill

Bryan accepted "compromises" at face value. Lingering doubts swept away by gratitude for appointment as Wilson's Secretary of State.

> "I appreciate so profoundly the service rendered by the President to the people in the stand he has taken on the fundamental principles involved in currency reform, that I am with him in all the details.... The right of the government to issue money is not surrendered to the banks; the control over the money so issued is not relinquished by the government.... I am glad to endorse earnestly and unreservedly the currency bill as a much better measure than I supposed it possible to secure at this time.... Conflicting opinions have been reconciled with a success hardly to have been expected."

### Final Passage

- With Bryan's conversion, no doubt about final outcome
- Federal Reserve Act released from joint House and Senate conference committee **December 22, 1913**
- Congress preoccupied with departure for Christmas recess, in no mood for debate
- **Passed 282 to 60 in House, 43 to 23 in Senate**
- President signed into law next day

**"The Creature had swallowed Congress."**

## Summary

- President Taft refused to champion Aldrich Bill → marked for political extinction
- Money Trust wanted President who would aggressively promote bill: **Woodrow Wilson** (already publicly declared allegiance)
- Wilson's nomination at Democratic convention secured by **Colonel House** (close associate of Morgan and Warburg)
- To prevent Taft reelection, Money Trust encouraged former Republican President **Teddy Roosevelt** to run on Progressive ticket
- Result: Roosevelt pulled away Republican support, Wilson won with less than majority vote
- Wilson and Roosevelt campaigned vigorously against evils of Money Trust while dependent upon that same Trust for campaign funding
- When Wilson elected, **Colonel House literally moved into White House**, became unseen President
- Under House's guidance, Aldrich Bill given cosmetic surgery → emerged as **Glass-Owen Bill**
- Sponsored by Democrats, in all essential features still the Jekyll Island plan
- Aldrich, Vanderlip, others identified with Wall Street: **pretense of opposing** Glass-Owen Bill to convince Congress and public that big bankers were fearful
- Final bill written with many sound features included to make palatable during Congressional debate but **predesigned to be dropped in later years**
- To win support of Populists under **William Jennings Bryan**, Jekyll Island team engineered compromises that were "mere 'shadows'" while "substance" remained
- Congress was outflanked, outfoxed, and outclassed by **deceptive, but brilliant, psycho-political attack**
- Result: **December 23, 1913, America once again had a central bank**

<!-- pp. 541-560 -->

### Benjamin Strong's International Operations

- **Benjamin Strong** directed both gold shipments to England and WWI bailout operations through the Federal Reserve
- President **Herbert Hoover** described Strong as "a mental annex to Europe"
- Before becoming Fed Chairman under Reagan in 1987, **Alan Greenspan** had served on **J.P. Morgan** board
- Greenspan was formerly an outspoken champion of the gold standard and critic of the System's banking cartel subservience
- In 1966 Greenspan wrote about the 1927 mild contraction response:

> "When business in the United States underwent a mild contraction in 1927, the Federal Reserve created more paper reserves in the hope of forestalling any possible bank reserve shortage. More disastrous, however, was the Federal Reserve's attempt to assist Great Britain who had been losing gold to us.... The 'Fed' succeeded in stopped the gold loss, but it nearly destroyed the economies of the world in the process. The excess credit which the Fed pumped into the economy spilled over into the stock market—triggering a fantastic speculative boom. As a result, the American economy collapsed."

- After his Fed appointment, Greenspan became silent on these issues and did nothing to anger the Creature he now served

### Agents of a Higher Power

- International money managers may be citizens of particular countries, but nationality is a "meaningless accident of birth"
- They consider themselves "citizens of the world first," loyal to themselves and their profession
- Central bank governors (Bank of England, Federal Reserve) were "tied to strings which were pulled by others above them"
- Their loyalties were to men, not concepts of nationalism or internationalism
- **Professor Quigley** explains:

> "It must not be felt that these heads of the world's chief central banks were themselves substantive powers in world finance. They were not. Rather, they were the technicians and agents of the dominant investment bankers of their own countries, who had raised them up and were perfectly capable of throwing them down. The substantive financial powers of the world were in the hands of these investment bankers (also called 'international' or 'merchant' bankers) who remained largely behind the scenes in their own unincorporated private banks. These formed a system of international cooperation and national dominance which was more private, more powerful, and more secret than that of their agents in the central banks."

- Not dealing with men who perceive themselves as betraying their nation, but **technicians loyal to the monetary scientists and political scientists who raised them up**
- Of the two groups, the financiers are dominant; politicians come and go, but those who wield the power of money remain to pick their successors

### Farmers Become Duck Dinner

- During WWI, prices for agricultural products rose to all-time high, profits soared
- Farmers placed money into war bonds and savings accounts at banks within farming communities (mostly Midwest and South)
- This was unacceptable to **New York banks** which saw their share of nation's deposits declining
- Federal Reserve System (captive of NY banks by then) was pressed into service to reclaim that money
- Few country banks had chosen to become Fed members; this provided excuse for Fed to wage economic war against them
- The plan was simple and not original: (1) extend easy credit to farmers to lure them into heavy debt, then (2) create recession to decrease their income so they cannot make payments
- Country banks would hold non-performing loans and foreclosed property which they could not sell without tremendous losses
- In the end, both farmers and banks would be wiped out; banks were the target, too bad about the farmers
- **Congressman Charles Lindbergh, Sr.** (father of transatlantic flight pioneer) explained:

> "Under the Federal Reserve Act, panics are scientifically created; the present panic is the first scientifically created one, worked out as we figure a mathematical problem."

- Details explained in 1939 by **Senator Robert Owen**, Chairman of Senate Banking and Currency Committee
- Owen, a banker himself, had been coauthor of Federal Reserve Act, a role he later regretted
- Owen described the **May 1920 secret meeting**:

> "In May 1920 ... the farmers were exceedingly prosperous.... They were paying off their mortgages. They had bought a lot of new land, at the instance of the government— had borrowed money to do it —and then they were bankrupted by a sudden contraction of credit and currency, which took place in 1920.... The Federal Reserve Board met in a meeting which was not disclosed to the public —they met on the 18th of May 1920; it was a secret meeting —and they spent all day; the minutes made 60 printed pages, and it appears in Senate Document 310 of February 10,1923. .. Under action taken by the Reserve Board on May 18, 1920, there resulted a violent contraction of credit.... This contraction of credit and currency had the effect, the next year, of diminishing the national production $15,000,000,000; it had the effect of throwing millions of people out of employment; it had the effect of reducing the value of lands and ranches $20,000,000,000"

- Credit contraction disastrous for nation as a whole, but farmers more deeply involved because recently created Federal Farm Loan Board lured them with easy credit "like ducks at the pond" into extreme debt ratios
- Large-city banks (System members) received Fed support during summer 1920 to extend credit to manufacturers and merchants, enabling many to ride out the slump
- No such support for farmers or country banks which, by 1921, were falling like dominoes
- History books refer to this as **Agricultural Depression of 1920-21**; better name: **Country-Duck Dinner in New York**

### Building the Mandrake Mechanism

- Three methods for Fed to create/extinguish money: reserve ratios, discount window, open-market operations
- Of the three, **purchase and sale of debt-related securities in the open market** provides greatest effect on money supply
- Fed purchase of securities (with checks backed by nothing) creates money; sale extinguishes money
- Fed authorized to buy/sell almost any security, but obligated to show preference for bonds and notes of federal government
- This is how the monetary scientists discharge their commitment to create money for their partners, the political scientists
- Without that service, the partnership would dissolve and Congress would abolish the Fed

#### Reserve Ratios and the Discount Window

- When System created in 1913, anticipated primary manipulation method would be controlling "reserve ratios" and "discount window"
- **Reserve ratio**: banker language for setting level of mandatory bank reserves (as percentage of deposits)
- **Discount window**: interest rate on loans made by Fed to banks themselves
- Reserve ratio under old National Bank Act: 25%
- Federal Reserve Act of 1913 reduced it to 18% for large New York banks (28% drop)
- 1917 (four years later): reserve requirements for Central Reserve-City Banks further dropped from 18% to 13% (additional 28% cut)
- Setting reserve ratios proved inefficient tool—latitude of control too small, public attention too great
- Second method (influencing interest rate on commercial loans) more useful

#### Fractional-Reserve Banking Mechanics

- Under fractional-reserve system, bank can create new money merely by issuing a loan
- Amount of new money limited by reserve ratio or "fraction" required to maintain to cover cash-flow needs
- If reserve ratio is 10%, then each $10 it lends includes $9 that never existed before
- Commercial bank can create sizable amount of money by making loans
- Once bank is "loaned up" (has already loaned $9 for every $1 in reserve), must stop and wait for old loans to be paid back before issuing new ones
- Only way to expand: (1) use bank's profits, (2) sell additional stock to investors, or (3) borrow money from the Fed

#### When Banks Borrow from the Fed

- Third option most popular, called going to the "discount window"
- Banks put up collateral (almost any debt contract held by bank, including government bonds, commonly commercial loans)
- Fed grants credit to bank in amount equal to those contracts, allowing bank to convert old loans into new "reserves"
- Every dollar of new reserves can be basis for lending nine more dollars in checkbook money
- Process doesn't stop there—new loans can be used as collateral at Fed for still more reserves
- Music goes 'round and 'round, with each new level of debt becoming "reserves" for yet higher level of loans, finally playing out at about **twenty-eight times**
- This process is commonly called **"discounting commercial paper"**
- One of the means by which Fed flooded nation with new money prior to Great Dam Rupture of 1929
- **Problem with discount window method**: even with low interest rates, some country bank "hicks" resist temptation, no way to force banks to participate
- Banks dependent on customer whims—if customers stop borrowing, banks have no new loans to convert into reserves
- By 1980, statutory limits on reserve ratios eliminated altogether; **Federal Reserve Board now has option to lower ratio to zero** = power to create unlimited quantities of money (ultimate dream of central bankers)

#### The Open Market Alternative

- Third mechanism as preferred option: **purchase and sale of bonds and other debt obligations in the open market**
- Discount window requires banks to borrow money which must be repaid
- Open market: Fed writes a fiat check to pay for securities; when check cashed, new money moves directly into economy without any concurrence from banks
- **Problem before WWI**: few government bonds available on open market; even after war, supply limited
- Vast inflation preceding Crash of 1929 was NOT caused by deficit spending
- 1920-1930: surplus of government revenue over expenses every year
- On eve of depression, America was getting out of debt
- Few government bonds for Fed to buy = open-market engine constantly running out of gas

### Banker's Acceptances—The Solution

- Solution: create new market tailor-made to Fed's needs, halfway between discount window and open market
- Called the **"acceptance window"**—System purchased unique debt-related security called **banker's acceptances**
- **Banker's acceptances**: contracts promising payment for commercial goods scheduled for later delivery
- Usually involve international trade with 3-6 month delays
- Means by which seller in one country can ship goods to unknown buyer in another country with confidence of payment upon delivery
- Accomplished through bank guarantees:
  - Buyer's bank issues letter of credit guaranteeing payment for goods, even if buyer defaults
  - Seller's bank receives this, writes "accepted" on contract, pays seller the amount of sale
  - Accepting bank advances money to seller in expectation of receiving future payment from buyer's bank
  - Both banks charge fee expressed as percentage of contract
  - Buyer pays a little more than sales contract amount, seller receives a little less
- Historically safe because banks guarantee payment only for financially sound firms
- During economic panic, even sound firms may be unable to honor contracts
- **This kind of underwriting nearly bankrupted George Peabody and J.P. Morgan in London during panic of 1857**, would have done so without Bank of England bailout
- Acceptances are **negotiable instruments** that can be traded in securities market
- Accepting banks can hold until maturity or sell them
- If sold, they are "rediscounted" when sold by original discounter (the underwriter)
- Sale price always less than value of underlying contracts; difference represents potential profit to buyer (the "rate" of rediscount)

#### Creating the Acceptance Market in America

- Although banker's acceptances commonly traded in Europe, not popular in United States before Federal Reserve Act
- National banks had been prohibited from purchasing them; market had to be created
- Fed accomplished this by setting discount rate on acceptances so low that underwriters would have been foolish not to take advantage
- At very low discount, underwriters could acquire short-term funds which could be invested at higher rate of return
- Acceptances quickly became plentiful on open market in United States
- But who would buy them at low return? No one
- So Fed not only set discount rate artificially low, also **pledged to buy all of the acceptances that were offered**
- Fed became the principal buyer of these securities
- Banks came into market as buyers, but only because they knew that at any time they wanted to sell, the Fed was pledged to buy
- Since money was being created out of nothing, cost didn't matter, nor did low profit potential
- Fed's goal was not to make profit on investment but to **increase the nation's money supply**

### Warburg and Friends Make a Little Profit

- Man who benefited most from this artificially created market: **Paul Warburg**, partner with Kuhn, Loeb and Co.
- Warburg attended Jekyll Island meeting at which Federal Reserve System was conceived
- Considered by all to have been the master theoretician who led others in deliberations
- One of most influential voices in public debates that followed
- Appointed as one of first members of Federal Reserve Board, later became Vice Governor until outbreak of war (resigned because of publicity regarding his connections with German banking)
- Director of **American I.G. Chemical Corp.** and **Agfa Ansco, Inc.** (firms later controlled by **I.G. Farben**, the infamous German cartel that would sponsor rise of **Adolf Hitler**)
- Also director of **CFR (Council on Foreign Relations)**
- Not surprising he positioned himself at center of huge cash flow from Fed's purchase of acceptances

#### Warburg's Acceptance Empire

- Warburg was founder and Chairman of **International Acceptance Bank of New York**, world's largest acceptance bank
- Also director of several smaller "competitors," including prestigious **Westinghouse Acceptance Bank**
- Founder and Chairman of **American Acceptance Council**
- **Warburg was the acceptance market in America**
- Not without friends who also swam in river of money
- Men who controlled America's largest financial institutions became directors or officers of various acceptance banks
- Interlocking directorate included: **Kuhn, Loeb and Co.; New York Trust Co.; Bank of Manhattan Trust Co.; American Trust Co.; New York Title and Mortgage Co.; Chase National Bank; Metropolitan Life Insurance Co.; American Express Co.; Carnegie Corp.; Guaranty Trust Co.; Mutual Life Insurance Co.; Equitable Life Assurance Society of New York; First National Banks of Boston, St. Louis, and Los Angeles**
- **The world of acceptance banking was the private domain of the financial elite of Wall Street**

#### European Partnership

- Behind American image: full partnership with investors from Europe
- Total capital of IAB's American shareholders: **$276 million** compared with **$271 million from foreign investors**
- Significant portion divided between **the Warburgs in Germany** and **the Rothschilds in England**
- By 1929, acceptance river was **1.7 trillion dollars wide**
- Throughout 1920s, acceptances were over half of all new money created by Federal Reserve—greater than all other open-market purchases combined
- In 1929 alone, acceptance purchases exceeded $1.7 trillion plus all loans to banks at discount window

### Congress Suspicious but Afraid to Tinker

- By 1920, suspicions and resentment growing in halls of Congress
- Politicians not getting their share; possibly many failed to realize as partners they were entitled to share
- Nevertheless, dazzled by banker language and accounting tricks, afraid to tinker with System lest they accidentally push wrong button
- Watching with amusement from London: **Fabian Socialist John Maynard Keynes**
- Speaking of Fed's manipulation of dollar value, Keynes wrote:

> "That is the way by which a rich country is able to combine new wisdom with old prejudice. It can enjoy the latest scientific improvements, devised in the economic laboratory of Harvard, whilst leaving Congress to believe that no rash departure will be permitted.... But there is in all such fictions a certain instability.... The suspicions of Congressmen may be aroused. One cannot be quite certain that some Senator might not read and understand this book."

- Not much danger of that by then
- American politicians had acquired taste for heady wine of war funding, stopped asking questions
- WWI had created enormous demands for money, Fed provided it
- By end of war, Congressional hostility to Federal Reserve became history

### Paying for World War I

- Much war debt absorbed by public which purchased war bonds out of patriotic instincts
- Treasury launched massive publicity campaign for "Liberty Loans" to reinforce sentiment
- These small-denomination bonds did not expand money supply, did not cause inflation (money came from savings)
- However, many people who thought it was patriotic duty went to banks and borrowed money to buy bonds
- Bank created most of that money out of nothing, drawing upon credits and bookkeeping entries from Federal Reserve
- Those purchases did inflate money supply
- Same result could have been obtained more simply and less expensively by getting money directly from Fed, but government encouraged the trend because of its **psychological value in generating popular support for the war**
- When people make sacrifices for an endeavor, it reinforces their belief that it must be worthy
- Although war financed partly by taxes and partly by Liberty Bonds purchased by public, **significant portion covered by sale of Treasury bonds to Federal Reserve in open market**
- **Benjamin Strong's biographer, Lester Chandler**, explains:

> "The Federal Reserve System became an integral part of the war financing machinery. The System's overriding objective, both as a creator of money and as fiscal agent, was to insure that the Treasury would be supplied with all the money it needed, and on terms fixed by Congress and the Treasury.... A grateful nation now hailed it as a major contributor to the winning of the war, an efficient fiscal agent for the Treasury, a great source of currency and reserve funds, and a permanent and indispensable part of the banking system."

### The Emergence of Government Debt

- War years largely a period of testing new strategies and consolidating power
- Not until after war—when no longer justification for deficit spending—that government debt became plentiful
- Up until WWI, annual federal expenses had been running about **$750 million**
- By end of war: running **$18.5 billion** (increase of 2,466%)
- Approximately **70% of war cost financed by debt**
- **Murray Rothbard** reminds us: on eve of depression in 1928, ten years after end of war, banking system held more government bonds than during war itself
- This means **government did not pay off those bonds when they came due**; instead, rolled them over by offering new bonds to replace old
- Why? Not because Congress needed more money
- **Bonds had become the basis for money in circulation**; if redeemed, money supply would have decreased
- A decrease in money supply viewed by politicians and central bankers as threat to economic stability
- Government found itself unable to get out of debt even when it had the money to do so
- **A dilemma that continues to this day**

#### The Debt Paradox

- Apparent contradiction: **Robert Patterson** says in *The Great Boom and Panic*, on eve of depression, America was getting out of debt
- Yet **Rothbard** tells us there were more government bonds held by banking system than during war
- Both statements can be true if there were more bonds outstanding during war but held by public, not banking system
- Would make it possible for fewer total bonds in 1928 yet System could still hold more than previously
- Expected result of Fed's growing role in open market
- As publicly-held bonds matured, treasury rolled them over, and Fed picked them up
- **Bonds purchased by public do not increase money supply; those purchased by banks do**
- Therefore, conditions in 1928 would have been far more inflationary than during war—even though government was getting out of debt

#### Fed's Bond-Buying Motives Before 1922

- Before 1922, Fed bought Treasury bonds primarily for three purposes:
  1. Income to operate the system
  2. To pay for newly issued Federal Reserve Notes replacing silver certificates
  3. To push down interest rates
- Motive for manipulating interest rates: to encourage borrowing from abroad in United States (where rates were low) and encourage investment from United States into Europe (where rates were higher)
- By making it possible to borrow American dollars at one rate and invest them elsewhere at higher rate, **Fed was deliberately moving money out of United States, with gold reserves following behind**
- As President Kennedy said in his 1963 address at IMF: outflow of American gold "did not come about by chance"

### The "Discovery" of the Open Market

- Commonly asserted by writers that power of open-market mechanism to manipulate money supply was "discovered" by Fed in early 1920s, came as total surprise
- **Martin Mayer** in *The Bankers* writes: "Now, through an accident as startling as those which produced the discovery of X-Rays or penicillin, the central bank learned that 'open market operations' could have a significant effect on the behavior of the banks."
- Difficult to believe that **Benjamin Strong, Paul Warburg, Montagu Norman**, and other monetary scientists pulling levers were taken by surprise
- These men could not possibly have been ignorant of effect of creating money out of nothing and pouring it into economy
- Open market was merely a different funnel
- If any element of surprise, likely only in ease with which mechanism could be activated
- Not important whether fact or fiction, except that it perpetuates the "accidental" view of history
- **The myth that no one is responsible for political or economic chaos: Things just happen. There was no master plan. No one is to blame. Everything is under control. Relax, pay your taxes, and go back to sleep!**

#### Institutionalization of Deficit Spending

- By end of war, Congress had awakened to fact it could use Federal Reserve System to obtain revenue without taxes
- From that point forward, **deficit spending became institutionalized**
- Gradually increasing issuance of Treasury bonds encouraging to Fed because it provided still one more source of debt to convert into money
- Source that eventually would become far more reliable than either bank loans or banker's acceptances
- Best of all: now that Congress was becoming dependent on free corn, little chance it would find its wings and fly away
- **The more dependent it became, the more secure the System itself became**

### Benjamin Strong Takes Control (1921-1923)

- In 1921, twelve regional Reserve banks separately buying and selling in open market, but motives varied
- Some merely needed income to cover operating overhead, while others (notably **New York branch under Benjamin Strong**) more interested in sending American gold to England
- Strong began immediately to gather control of all open-market operations into hands of his own bank
- June 1922: **"Open-Market Committee"** formed to coordinate activities among regional Governors
- April next year: national board in Washington replaced Governor's group with one of its own creation, the **"Open-Market Investment Committee"**
- **Benjamin Strong was its chairman**
- Powers enhanced ten years later by legislation making it mandatory for regional branches to follow Open-Market Committee's directives (mere formality, die had been cast much earlier)
- From 1923 forward, **Fed's open-market operations have been carried out by New York Federal Reserve Bank**
- **The money trust has always been in control**

### Drowning in Credit

- One consequence of purchasing Treasury bonds and other debt-related securities in open market: **money created to purchase them eventually ends up in commercial banks where used for expansion of bank credit**
- "Credit" is weasely word with different meanings to different people
- In banker language: expansion of credit means banks have "excess reserves" (bookkeeping entries) which can be multiplied by nine and earn interest for them—**if only someone would be kind enough to borrow**
- Money waiting to be created; message is: "Come on to the bank, folks. Don't be bashful. We've got plenty of money to lend. You have credit you didn't even know you had."
- In 1920s, greater share of bank credit bestowed upon business firms, wealthy investors, and other high rollers, but little man not ignored
- In 1910: consumer credit accounted for only 10% of nation's retail sales
- By 1929: credit transactions responsible for half of $60 billion retail market
- **Elgin Groseclose** in *Money and Man*: "By 1929 the United States was overwhelmed by a flood of credit. It had covered the land. It was pouring into every nook and cranny of the national economy."

#### The Credit Expansion of 1921-1929

- Impact of expanding credit compounded by artificially low interest rates (intended to help governments of Europe)
- But they also stimulated borrowing here at home
- Since borrowing is what causes money to be created under fractional-reserve banking, money supply in America began to expand
- From 1921 through June 1929: quantity of dollars increased by **61.8%**, substantially more than increase in national product
- During same time, amount of currency in circulation remained virtually unchanged
- **That means expansion was comprised entirely of money substitutes, such as bonds and loan contracts**

### Booms and Busts Made Worse

- Forces of free market amazingly flexible, manage to exert themselves in unexpected ways in spite of political decree
- Prior to creation of Federal Reserve, banking had been coddled and hobbled by government
- Banks chartered by government, protected by government, regulated by government, forced to serve political agendas of those in power
- Consequently, landscape strewn with tombstones of dead banks which had taken to their graves life savings of hapless depositors
- But these were mostly regional tragedies offset by growth and prosperity in other areas
- Even within communities most severely affected, recovery was swift
- **Now that cartel had firm control over nation's money supply, pattern began to change**
- Corrective forces of free market more firmly straight-jacketed than ever
- All banks in entire country in lock step with each other
- What happened in one region is what happened in all regions
- **Banks were not allowed to die, so there could be no adjustments after their demise**
- Their illness was sustained and carried like a deadly virus to the others
- Expansion of money supply in 1920s clearly shows that effect
- Not a steady advance but **a series of convulsions**
- Each cycle at higher level than previous one because busts that followed booms not allowed to play themselves out
- Monetary scientists now had so many mechanisms at their command they were able to initiate new expansions to cancel out downward adjustments
- **Like prescribing increasing doses of narcotics to postpone awareness of an advancing disease**
- It increased prestige of the doctor, but it did not bode well for the patient

### The Roller Coaster (1920-1929)

Between 1920 and 1929, three distinct business cycles with several minor ones within them:

**UP!** Fed inflated money supply to pay for WWI. Resulting boom caused prices to rise.

**DOWN!** In 1920, Fed raised interest rates to cool off inflation. That caused recession, and prices tumbled. Farmers hit hardest, hundreds of country banks closed.

**UP!** In 1921, Fed lowered interest rates to stop recession and to help governments of Europe. Inflation and expanding debt resulted.

**DOWN!** In 1923, Fed tightened credit to put brakes on inflation.

**UP!** But that was offset by simultaneous policy of lowering rate at discount window, thus encouraging banks to borrow new reserves to expand money supply.

**UP!** In 1924, Fed suddenly created **$500 million dollars** in new money. Within one year, commercial banks parlayed that into more than **$4 billion** (expansion of eight-to-one). Boom that followed took on character of speculation rather than investment. Prices in stock market rose drastically.

**DOWN!** In 1926, Florida land boom collapsed, and economy began to contract once again.

**UP!** In 1927, **Montagu Norman of Bank of England** visited United States to consult with **Benjamin Strong**. Shortly after his visit, Fed pumped new money into system, and boom returned.

**down!** In spring of 1928, Fed contracted credit to halt the boom.

**up!** But banks shifted their reserves into time deposits (where customers agree to wait before withdrawing their money). Since time deposits require smaller reserve ratio than demand deposits, banks were able to issue more loans than before. That offset Fed's contraction of credit.

**up!** By that time, British government had consumed its previous subsidy which was used to maintain its welfare state. In spring of 1928, pound sterling again sagging on international market, and gold began to flow back into United States. Once again, fledgling Creature came to aid of Bank of England, its ailing parent. **Fed bought huge volume of banker's acceptances to depress interest rates and halt flow of gold.** Money supply suddenly increased by almost **$2 billion**.

**down!** In August, Fed reversed its expansionist policy by selling Treasury bonds in open market and raising interest rates. Money supply began to contract.

**It was the fined bubble.**

### Sixth Reason to Abolish the Fed

- One of myths about Federal Reserve: that it is needed to stabilize the economy
- Yet, it has achieved just the opposite
- **Destabilization is dramatically clear in years prior to the Crash**, but same cause-and-effect continues to this day
- As long as men given power to tinker with money supply, they will strive to circumvent natural laws of supply and demand
- No matter how high their intentions or pure their motives, they will cause disruptions in natural flow
- When disruptions perceived, they will try to compensate by causing opposite disruptions
- But long before they act, there will already be new forces at work which they cannot perceive until already manifest
- **Height of egotistical folly for "experts" to think they can outsmart or do better than combined, interactive decisions of hundreds of millions of people** all acting in response to their own best judgment
- Thus, **Fed is doomed to failure by its nature and its mission**
- **That is the sixth reason it should be abolished: It destabilizes the economy**

### Tulipomanta

- Easy credit not the only problem; equally important was effect on behavior patterns of populace
- Responding to herd instinct and belief in possibility of something-for-nothing, men driven to most bizarre form of investment speculation
- Not first time such hysteria seized population
- One of most graphic examples: **Holland between 1634 and 1636**
- New, rare flower called the **tulip** discovered in gardens of wealthy inhabitants of Constantinople (now Istanbul)
- When root bulbs brought into Holland, rapidly became status symbol among wealthy (like race horses or rare breeds of dogs today)
- Those with surplus funds found that investment in tulips brought them significant social recognition
- Price of tulip bulbs climbed steadily until they became not merely symbols of status, but speculative investments
- At one point, prices doubled every few days
- Speculators seen everywhere amassing great fortunes with no input of either labor or service
- Many otherwise prudent people found themselves infected by hysteria
- Borrowed against homes, invested life savings to get in on anticipated windfall
- This pushed up prices even further, tended to create fulfillment of its own prophecy
- Contracts for future delivery
<!-- pp. 561-580 -->

## Tulipmania and the 1920s Speculation

### Tulipmania: The Prototype Bubble

- **Tulip bulbs** became more precious than gemstones in 17th century Holland
- Markets grew complex, requiring experts to certify origin and grade
- One **Admiral Liefken bulb** valued at 4,400 florins; **Semper Augustus** at 5,500 florins
- A single **Viceroy bulb** traded for: two lasts of wheat, four lasts of rye, four fat oxen, eight fat swine, twelve fat sheep, two hogsheads of wine, four casks of butter, 1,000 pounds of cheese, a bed and mattress, a suit of clothes, and a silver drinking cup
- In 1636, everyone knew prices bore no relationship to value, but fear of missing profits kept them speculating
- **Overnight collapse**: no buyers at any price. Thousands lost fortunes and life savings
- Source: **Charles Mackay**, *Extraordinary Popular Delusions and the Madness of Crowds* (1841)

> "Everyone was confident they would sell out precisely at the top of the market. In any herd, however, there are always a few who will take the lead and, by 1636, all it was or two prominent merchants to sell out their stock. Overnight, there were no buyers whatsoever, at any price."

### Tulips in the Stock Market (1920s)

- During 1920s credit expansion, stock market rise was entirely speculative
- Buyers didn't care about price-to-dividend ratios
- Common stocks sold for **20 to 50 times earnings**; some at 100x
- **"Greater-Fool" strategy**: buy high, sell higher to the next fool
- **Buying on margin**: investors put up as little as 10% deposit, borrowed the rest from stockbrokers (who got funds from the Fed)
- Average stock yielded 3% dividend, but speculators paid over **12% interest** on margin loans — needed 9% annual appreciation just to break even
- **Call loans**: brokers could demand repayment on 24 hours' notice
- From August 1921 to September 1929: **Dow-Jones rose from 63.9 to 381.17** — a 597% increase

### Banks Become Speculators

- Commercial banks functioned more like speculators than clearing houses
- Loans for production declined; loans for stock market speculation surged
- Between 1921–1929: total bank loans increased from $24.1B to $35.7B
- **Nearly $8 billion** in loans for securities and real estate — **70% of increase was speculative**
- **New York banks** loaned over $7 billion to brokers for margin accounts
- Number of securities dealers grew from 250 before WWI to **6,500 by 1929**
- Banks purchased high-yield bonds of dubious quality, borrowing short-term and investing long-term — a precarious position

### Did the Fed Cause the Speculation?

> "The Fed undoubtedly had other objects in mind, but that did not cancel its responsibility. It was acutely aware of the psychological effect of easy credit and had consciously used that knowledge to manipulate public behavior on numerous occasions. Behavioral psychology is a necessary tool of the trade. So it could claim neither ignorance nor innocence. In the unfolding of this tragedy, it was about as innocent as a spider whose web 'accidentally' caught the fly."

- Fed was aware of easy credit's psychological effects and used it to manipulate behavior
- The banking cartel was "as innocent as a spider whose web 'accidentally' caught the fly"

### The Final Bubble

- **Spring 1928**: Fed expressed concern over speculation, raised interest rates to curb credit expansion
- Money supply growth slowed, stock prices became conceivable for "soft landing"
- But **other agendas intervened**: helping British economy and European governments
- **Professor Quigley's observation**: central bankers were marionettes whose strings were pulled by others

### The London Connection

- Despite seven years of Fed subsidy, British economy was sagging under socialism
- Gold was moving back to the U.S.
- Fed **reversed policy at the brink of success** and purchased over **$300 million of banker's acceptances** in late 1928
- This caused almost **$2 billion increase in money supply**

> "Europe, as we have noted, had found the benefits from the 1927 inflation dissipated, and European opinion now clamored against any tighter money in the U.S. The easing in late 1928 prevented gold inflows into the U.S. from getting very large. Great Britain was again losing gold, and sterling was weak once more. The United States bowed once again to its overriding wish to see Europe avoid the inevitable consequences of its own inflationary policies." — **Professor Rothbard**

- Prior to Fed's reversal, stock prices had declined 5%
- After reversal: prices rose **20% from July to December**

### Montagu Norman's Secret Visit (February 1929)

- **Montagu Norman** traveled to U.S. to meet privately with Federal Reserve officers and **Andrew Mellon**, Secretary of the Treasury
- No public record of meeting details, but three things certain:
  1. It was important
  2. It concerned economies of America and Great Britain
  3. Best not to tell the public

> "How much better, as seen from the Federal Reserve, to let nature take its course and thus allow nature to take the blame." — **Galbraith**

### Andrew Mellon's Philosophy

> "Mr. Mellon had only one formula: 'liquidate labor, liquidate stocks, liquidate the farmers, liquidate real estate.' He insisted that, when the people get an inflation brainstorm, the only way to get it out of their blood is to let it collapse. He held that even a panic was not altogether a bad thing. He said: 'It will purge the rottenness out of the system. High costs of living and high living will come down. People will work harder, live a moral life. Values will be adjusted, and enterprising people will pick up the wrecks from less competent people.'" — **Herbert Hoover** describing Mellon's views

- Meetings likely coordinated to direct the implosion to their advantage
- Events that followed strongly support this view

### Advance Warning for Members Only

- **February 6, 1929**: Fed issued advisory to member banks to liquidate stock market holdings
- **Paul Warburg** gave same advice in annual report to stockholders of **International Acceptance Bank**:

> "If the orgies of unrestrained speculation are permitted to spread, the ultimate collapse is certain not only to affect the speculators themselves, but to bring about a general depression involving the entire country."

- **Warburg** was partner at **Kuhn, Loeb & Co.**, which maintained preferred customer lists
- Similar lists at **J.P. Morgan Co.**
- Custom: give advance notice on stock issues, opportunity to purchase 2–15 points below public price
- This was how investment bankers maintained influence over world affairs
- **The men on these lists were notified of the coming crash**

### Who Got Out in Time

- Virtually all Wall Street giants got out before the crash:
  - **John D. Rockefeller**
  - **J.P. Morgan**
  - **Joseph P. Kennedy**
  - **Bernard Baruch**
  - **Henry Morganthau**
  - **Douglas Dillon**
- No record of any member of the interlocking directorate between Fed, major NY banks, and prime customers being caught by surprise
- "Wisdom, apparently, was greatly affected by whose list one was on"

### A Message of Comfort to the Public

- While insiders abandoned ship, public was told it was a lovely cruise
- **President Coolidge** and **Treasury Secretary Mellon**: economy in better shape than ever
- **John Maynard Keynes** (socialist economist from London): Fed's dollar management was a "triumph" of man over money
- **Benjamin Strong** (NY Federal Reserve Bank):

> "The very existence of the Federal Reserve System is a safeguard against anything like a calamity growing out of money rates.... In former days the psychology was different, because the facts of the banking situation were different. Mob panic, and consequently mob disaster, is less likely to arise."

### Reserve Council Confers in Haste (April 19, 1929)

- **New York Times headline**: "Atmosphere of Mystery Is Thrown about Its Meeting in Washington"
- Emergency meeting under "cloak of great secrecy"
- No advance announcement; members seen entering Treasury Department
- Evasive replies given to press
- Newspaper correspondents asked to leave the corridor

### Montagu Norman's Disguise

- Norman traveled to U.S. in disguise: long black cloak, broad-brimmed hat
- Used pseudonym **"Professor Skinner"**
- **W.C. Wentworth** (Oxford/Cambridge athlete) encountered Norman on ship in July 1929:

> "A fellow passenger was 'Mr. Skinner,' and a member of our team recognized him. He was Montagu Norman, returning to London, after a secret visit to the US Central Bank, travelling incognito. When we told him we knew who he was, he asked us not to blow his cover, because if the details of his movement were made public, it could have serious financial consequences. Naturally, we agreed, and on the days following, as we crossed the Atlantic, he talked to us very frankly. He said, 'In the next few months there is going to be a shake-out But don't worry —it won't last for long.'"

### The Pin Enters the Bubble

- **August 9, 1929**: Fed reversed easy-credit policy, raised discount rate to **6%**
- Bank of England raised rates also
- Bank reserves in both countries shrank, along with money supply
- System began selling securities in open market (contracts money supply)
- **Call rates on margin loans jumped to 15%, then 20%**
- The pin had been inserted

### The Duck Dinner Begins

- Securities market peaked **September 19, 1929**
- Public bought heavily for five more weeks on the way down
- More than a million shares traded during that period
- **October 24**: like a giant school of fish, thousands stampeded to sell
- Ticker tape hopelessly overloaded; prices tumbled
- **13 million shares** exchanged hands
- "Everyone said the bottom had dropped out of the market. They were wrong. Five days later, it did."

### Black Tuesday (October 29, 1929)

- Exchanges crushed by avalanche of selling
- At times, no buyers at all
- Over **16 million shares** dumped, mostly at any offered price
- **Within one day**: millions of investors wiped out
- **Within weeks**: $3 billion of wealth disappeared
- **Within twelve months**: $40 billion vanished
- People who counted paper profits suddenly found themselves very poor

### The Other Side: Who Bought?

- Insiders who moved to cash and gold were the buyers
- Falling prices didn't mean companies were bad — solid companies still paying dividends
- At realistic prices, stocks tumbled far below natural levels
- Those with cash picked them up for a fraction of true worth
- Giant holding companies formed: **Marine Midland Corporation**, **Lehman Corporation**, **Equity Corporation**
- **J.P. Morgan** set up food trust called **Standard Brands**
- "Like the shark swallowing the mackerel, the big speculators devoured the small"

### Was the Crash Planned?

- No evidence crash was planned for profit
- Much evidence monetary scientists tried to avert it, might have succeeded if higher-priority agendas hadn't intervened
- Once they realized inevitability, they used their privileged position to take full advantage

> "It was the calculated 'shearing' of the public by the World Money Powers." — **Curtis Dall**, FDR's son-in-law

### Natural Law No. 5

**LESSON**: Human nature drives men to place personal priorities ahead of neighbors. Even best men cannot long resist temptation to benefit at expense of others if opportunity is placed squarely before them. Especially true when means of benefit is obscure and not likely to be perceived as such. Exceptional men may resist, but their numbers are small. General rule will prevail in long run.

**LAW**: When men are entrusted with power to control the money supply, they will eventually use that power to confiscate the wealth of their neighbors.

- No better illustration than **Crash of 1929** and the lingering depression that followed

## From Crash to Depression

### The Crash's Limited Impact

- Speculators ruined, but they lost money acquired without effort
- Some unfortunate souls lost life savings — but only those who gambled on call loans
- Those who bought stock with money they actually possessed didn't have to sell; did well in long run
- For most, something-for-nothing had merely been converted back to nothing
- Stock prices plummeted, but **companies still producing, employing, paying dividends**
- No one lost job just because market fell
- "The tulips were gone, but the wheat crop remained"

### Where Was the Problem?

- In truth, there was none — at least not yet
- Crash had little effect on average American
- Unemployment didn't become rampant until depression years came later
- **Depression was caused by continued government restraint of free market**
- Drop in stock prices was long-overdue, healthy adjustment
- Stage set for recovery and sound economic growth, as always happened in the past

### Government Intervention Prevented Recovery

- **It did not happen this time**
- Monetary and political scientists now in full charge of rescue
- Saw crash as golden opportunity to justify even more controls
- **Herbert Hoover** launched multitude of government programs:
  - Bolster wage rates
  - Prevent prices from dropping
  - Prop up failing firms
  - Stimulate construction
  - Guarantee home loans
  - Protect depositors
  - Rescue banks
  - Subsidize farmers
  - Provide public works

### FDR's New Deal

- **FDR** swept into office promising even more of the same under slogan of **New Deal**
- Federal Reserve launched series of "banking reforms" — all measures to extend power over money supply

### 1931: Fresh Money Fails to Restart Economy

- Fresh money pumped into economy to restart cycle
- Rocket wouldn't lift off
- Dead weight of new bureaucracies, regulations, subsidies, taxes, welfare benefits, deficit spending, price tinkering kept it on launching pad

### Productive Foundation Crumbles

- Eventually, productive foundation began to crumble under weight
- Taxes and regulatory agencies forced companies out of business
- Those remaining had to curtail production
- Unemployment began to spread
- **By every economic measure, economy was no better or worse in 1939 than in 1930** when rescue began
- Depression not ended until outbreak of WWII and tooling up for war production

### A Dubious Save

- In almost every way, repeat of WWI drama
- Even same players: **FDR** and **Churchill** worked together behind scenes
- Churchill wanting American assistance in war England was losing and couldn't afford
- FDR wanting jolt to economy for political reasons
- Financiers (gathered behind **J.P. Morgan**) wanting profits of war
- "But that is another chapter, and this book is long enough"

### Section VI Transition

- What happened after WWII was focus of first six chapters
- Now time to reset coordinates and return to present

## Section VI: Time Travel Into the Future

### Chapter Twenty-Four: Doomsday Mechanisms

**Preview**: Decline of American prosperity; increase in government size; decrease in personal freedom; growth of taxes; evidence of elite plan to merge U.S. into world government on basis of "equality" with less-developed nations; environmentalist movement shown to be an outgrowth of that plan

### Mired in Debt

- **Annual federal deficits** have grown steadily since 1950, rate of growth now in vertical climb
- Took **198 years** for federal government to borrow first trillion dollars
- Then in just **twelve years** (mostly Reagan Administration) borrowed another **$3 trillion**
- By end of 1995 (three years Clinton): debt had grown to about **$5 trillion**

### Comprehending the Numbers

- **$5 trillion** = about 80% of all goods sold and services rendered in America throughout entire year
- Stack of $100 bills 40 inches high = millionaire
- $5 trillion would rise **3,350 miles into space**

### Interest Payments (1993 data)

- Net interest payments: **$214 billion per year**
- Consumed about **14% of all federal revenue**
- Government's **largest single expense** — greater than defense
- Larger than combined cost of: Agriculture, Education, Energy, Housing and Urban Development, Interior, Justice, Labor, State, Transportation, Veterans' Affairs

### The Hidden Tax

- Charges not paid by government — **paid by you** through taxes and inflation
- Cost currently about **$4,500 for each family of four**
- All families pay through inflation, not all pay taxes
- Cost to each **taxpaying family** is higher
- On average, over **$5,000 extracted** from your family each year
- Not for government services or previous debt
- Not for roads, buildings, welfare, medical benefits, salaries
- **Does nothing except pay interest**

### Compounding Interest

- Interest is compounded
- Even if government stopped deficit spending completely, total debt would continue growing from interest on existing portion
- In 1995, interest on national debt already consuming **57% of all revenue collected by income taxes**
- At present rate of expansion, **will consume 100% by year 2010** (includes corporate taxes)
- Interest will consume 100% of personal income taxes **much sooner**

### The Impossibility

- Without interest on national debt, could save enough to reduce corporate taxes and eliminate personal income taxes altogether
- Unfortunately, under present policies, that is not going to happen
- Congress does not live within its income
- Many expenses paid not from taxes but from **selling government bonds** and going deeper into debt each year
- Even if could save enough to eliminate personal income taxes, it would not be enough

### The Doomday Mechanism

- **Locomotive running in opposite direction**
- Government size growing **larger**, not smaller
- More people working for government than all manufacturing companies in private sector
- More bank regulators than bankers
- More farm-bureau workers than farmers
- More welfare administrators than recipients
- **More citizens receiving government checks than paying income taxes**

### The Ballot Box as Weapon

- By 1996, welfare benefits in 29 states were **higher than average secretary's wage**
- In 6 states, **more than entry-level wage for computer programmers**
- When possible for people to vote on issues involving transfer of wealth to themselves from others, ballot box becomes weapon
- Majority plunders minority
- **Point of no return**: where doomsday mechanism begins to accelerate until system self-destructs
- Plundered grow weary, eventually join plunderers
- Productive base of economy diminishes further until only state remains

### Doomday Within Government: Entitlements

- By 1992, more than half of all federal outlays for **entitlements**
- Expenses like **Medicare, Social Security, government retirement programs**
- Based on promises of future payments
- Many are contractual obligations; millions depend on them
- Cannot be eliminated, only political expediency
- Example: **$24 billion per year for food stamps** — no contractual obligation, only political expediency

### The Political Function

- Observers watch well-dressed customers use food stamps for ice cream, pretzels, candy, wine, then drive away in late-model car
- Political function of food stamp program: **not to help hungry but to buy votes**

### Entitlements: The Funds Don't Exist

- Programs with contractual obligations (Social Security, Medicare) could be turned over to private firms
- Would operate more efficiently and pay out higher benefits
- **Congress doesn't dare touch for fear of losing votes**
- Normally, issuers of contracts required by law to accumulate money into fund
- **Federal government does not abide by those laws**
- Funds exist on paper only
- Money for future obligations is **immediately spent**, replaced by government IOU
- As future payments come due, all money must come from **revenue being collected at that time**

### The Math of Doomsday

- **Entitlements currently represent 52% of all federal outlays**, growing at **12% each year**
- **Interest payments: 14%** of federal expenses
- Added together: **two-thirds of all federal expenses are now entirely automatic**, percentage growing each month
- Even if Congress stopped all normal spending (dismantle armed forces, close agencies, stop subsidies, board up buildings including White House) — would only reduce present spending by **one-third**
- Even that small amount is shrinking by **10–12% per year**
- **One does not have to be statistical analyst to figure out where this trend is headed**

### The Federal Reserve as Biggest Doomsday Mechanism

- Every cent of money supply — coins, currency, checkbook money — came into being for purpose of being loaned to someone
- These dollars will disappear when loans paid back
- Exist only so long as debt behind them exists
- Underneath pyramid of money, supporting entire structure, are **so-called reserves** (Fed's monetization of debt)
- If we tried to pay off national debt, those reserves would start to disappear
- Our money supply would be undermined
- **Fed would have to scramble** into money markets, replace U.S. securities with bonds from corporations and other countries
- Technically can be done, but **transition could be devastating**
- Under Federal Reserve System, **Congress would be fearful to eliminate national debt even if it wanted to**

### Who Owns the National Debt?

- Often said "we owe it to ourselves" — but who owes what to whom?
- **Federal Reserve holds only about 8%**
- **Foreign investors own approximately 27%**
- **Federal government agencies: 28%** (IOUs that replaced money taken from funds like Social Security)
- **Private-sector investors in U.S.: largest share, about 37%**

### Breaking Down the 37%

- Partly true that "we owe it to ourselves" or at least some of us owe it to some of us
- Those who receive interest: private investors seeking income exempt from state income taxes; large institutions (banks, corporations, insurance companies, investment funds)
- With institutions, money represents pooled assets of thousands of small investors
- **Major portion of interest on national debt does accrue to benefit of large sector of American people**

### The Bad News

- Government obtains every cent of money it pays to us by **confiscating it from us** in the first place
- If true we owe it to ourselves, also true we pay it to ourselves
- Money goes out of one pocket back into other — **minus a handling fee**
- Government takes **$1000 from us** in taxes and inflation, gives us back **$350**
- So-called "benefit" to public is but a **giant scam**

### Government Credit Crowds Out Private Credit

- When people purchase government bonds, less money available for investment in private industry
- Well known: **government credit "crowds out" private credit**
- Result: productive side of nation handicapped by unfair competition for investment capital
- To obtain new money for growth, private companies must pay **higher interest rates**
- Passed on to consumer in form of higher prices
- Many companies forced to curtail expansion plans; potentially new jobs never created
- Some forced out of business; employees put out of work
- **Economy is always retarded by government debt. Larger the debt, greater the damage.**

### The Foreign Debt Time Bomb

- **27% of national debt held by foreign investors** may not seem large, but represents **huge amount of money**
- A trillion dollars cannot be ignored
- Bonds could become great problem down the line when they mature
- So far, partial blessing — purchased with money that already existed, not inflationary
- Not difficult to imagine future conditions where bondholders decide not to renew
- To pay off bonds on maturity, Treasury would have to issue new ones
- **Fed would have to purchase new bonds with fiat money**
- **Foreign-held federal debt is a ticking time bomb**
- If should ever have to be picked up by Fed, **inflationary impact on our country would be staggering**

### What Difference Does It Make?

- Tendency to read about trends with detached fascination
- "Isn't that interesting. But where is the relevance? Why get excited over technicalities?"
- So what if government mired in debt? Who cares if interest will never be paid? What of world currency or world government? **What difference will any of it make to me?**

### The Answer

- First step: see what difference it already has made
- Our upcoming trip into future will merely extend those lines
<!-- pp. 581-600 -->

## The Decline of American Living Standards

### Economic Deterioration Through Policy

- Government policy has deliberately shifted economic resources away from the U.S. through environmental regulations, excessive taxation, and burdensome labor rules
- Heavy industry has fled American shores due to regulatory costs
- **Federal taxes** (including social security) now take more than 40% of private incomes; state/county/local taxes add to this burden
- Inflation consumes what remains — Americans spend half of each year working for the government

### Real Wages Have Declined

- **AFL-CIO study (1977)**: Real wages of average Americans declining when measured in purchasing power
- **U.S. Census Bureau (1980)** and **Consumers' Union (1992)**: Confirmed the downward trend
- Low-priced items (phone calls, gasoline, food, wrist-watches) became cheaper in work-hours, but high-priced essentials (housing, college, health care) became far more expensive

> "The average U.S. household has maintained its living standard largely because families are working more hours. Millions of women entered the work force in the past 25 years." — Consumer Reports, June 1992

- In 1970: 21 million women worked full time; by early 1990s: over 36 million
- Many families now require two earners just to maintain the buying power one earner once had

### Indicators of Economic Stress

- Home ownership percentage dropping
- Age of first home purchase rising
- Middle class shrinking
- Family savings declining
- Personal bankruptcy rate triple what it was in the 1960s
- **90% of all Americans are broke at age 65**
- Despite two incomes, real net worth of average household falling and leisure time shrinking

## The New World Order

### A Functional World Government

- The plan for world government within the UN framework is progressing (referenced in Chapters 5 and 6)
- Often called **The New World Order** — designed on principles of **socialism**
- Represents the "dream-come-true" for socialist theoreticians, politicians, and technicians

### Two Weapons of Control

1. **World military command** — will eventually control all national armies and super weapons under slogans of "peace and disarmament"
2. **World central bank** (IMF/World Bank) — with ability to issue common money all nations must accept, accomplished under slogans of "international trade and economic growth"

### Monetary Control: The Preferred Weapon

> "Of the two weapons, monetary control is the most important. The use of military force is viewed as a crude weapon in the arsenal of world government, to be used only as a last resort. The effect of monetary control is more powerful than mega-tons of atomic energy. It reaches into every shop and home, a feat that could never be accomplished by standing armies."

- Can be targeted precisely against one nation, group, or individual while sparing others
- Military force causes resentment and unrest; monetary manipulation is seldom understood by victims
- Manipulators enjoy high social status and financial reward — not victims' wrath
- **Monetary control is the weapon of choice** in The New World Order

### What World Government Could Be vs. What It Is

**Ideal scenario**: A world parliament based on minimum coercion and maximum freedom
- Would welcome cultural and religious variety
- Would encourage diversity and freedom-to-choose instead of collectivist uniformity
- Would reduce taxes already in place to stimulate production and creativity
- Would withhold membership from governments violating basic citizen rights
- Could be the greatest force for peace, prosperity, and freedom ever known

**Actual reality**: The New World Order incubating at the UN is entirely different
- Members represent "just about every dictator and warlord in the world"
- Philosophy built on socialist doctrine: all good flows from the state
- Those who don't conform must be "bent to the government's will or be eliminated"
- Cannot oppose totalitarianism because **it is totalitarianism**

## America Is the Target

### The U.S. as Obstacle to World Government

- The New World Order cannot become functional while the U.S. remains able to act independently
- America viewed as a "bull in the china shop" — currently controlled, but might break loose
- If Americans awakened to world politics and regained control of their government, they would still have military and economic power to break away
- **Prime directive**: weaken the United States both militarily and economically
- This directive comes from **American leaders**, not foreign ones — **CFR members** in White House, State Department, Defense Department, and Treasury

### The Doomsday Mechanism

- **Korean War**: First time American soldiers fought under UN authority
- Trend accelerated to include Iraq, Yugoslavia, Bosnia, Somalia, Haiti
- American military being absorbed into the UN
- Steps underway to hand over American **atomic weapons** to UN control
- Once this happens, "the doomsday mechanism will become activated. It will be too late to escape."

### Economic Exhaustion Strategy

- **IMF/World Bank** already functioning with Federal Reserve System as world central bank
- American economy deliberately exhausted through foreign giveaways and domestic boondoggles
- Object: not to help those in need or preserve environment, but **to bring the system down**
- When Americans are in soup lines, they'll accept the "carefully arranged rescue" by the world bank
- A **world currency** is already designed, awaiting only an appropriate crisis to justify introduction

## The Report from Iron Mountain

### Origins and Purpose

- Released in 1966 as a think-tank study
- Origin debated, but document hints it was commissioned by **Defense Department under Defense Secretary Robert McNamara**
- Produced by **Hudson Institute** (Croton-on-Hudson, NY) — founded and directed by **Herman Kahn** (formerly Rand Corporation)
- Both **McNamara** and **Kahn** were CFR members

### The Study's True Purpose

- Self-proclaimed: to explore ways to "stabilize society"
- Reality: "stabilize" used synonymously with "government" — meaning to **preserve and perpetuate government power**
- Study analyzed different ways government can perpetuate itself, control citizens, and prevent rebellion

> "Previous studies have taken the desirability of peace, the importance of human life, the superiority of democratic institutions, the greatest 'good' for the greatest number, the 'dignity' of the 1 individual, the desirability of maximum health and longevity, and other such wishful premises as axiomatic values necessary for the justification of a study of peace issues. We have not found them so."

- Morality explicitly rejected as concern
- Did not address right or wrong, freedom or human rights
- **Sole concern**: how to perpetuate the existing government

### War as Government Stabilizer

- Major conclusion: **war has been the only reliable means** to achieve government stability
- Only during war or threat of war are masses compliant enough to carry the yoke of government
- Fear of conquest and pillage makes almost any burden seem acceptable by comparison
- War arouses human passion and patriotic loyalty to leaders
- No sacrifice in the name of victory will be rejected; resistance viewed as treason

> "The war system not only has been essential to the existence of nations as independent political entities, but has been equally indispensable to their stable political structure.... The possibility of war provides the sense of external necessity without which no government can long remain in power."

- Historical record shows regimes that failed to maintain credibility of war threat dissolved
- War maintains class distinctions and ensures "subordination of the citizens to the state by virtue of the residual war powers inherent in the concept of nationhood"

## A New Definition of Peace

### Redefining Peace for World Government

- Approaching point where old formulas may no longer work
- Now possible to create world government with all nations disarmed and disciplined by world army
- **New definition**: "The word peace, as we have used it in the following pages,... implies total and general disarmament."
- Under this scenario, independent nations won't have capability to wage war
- Military action by world army against renegade subdivisions called "**peace-keeping operations**"
- Soldiers called "**peace keepers**" — bullets will be "peaceful bullets," bombs "peaceful bombs," even atomic bombs if necessary

### Requirements for War Substitute

The Report from Iron Mountain concludes a substitute for war must possess three properties:
1. Must be **economically wasteful**
2. Must represent a **credible threat of great magnitude**
3. Must provide a **logical excuse for compulsory service** to government

## A Sophisticated Form of Slavery

### Compulsory Service to Government

- Standing armies provide place to put "antisocial and dissident elements of society"
- Without war, forced-labor battalions would be told they're fighting poverty, cleaning the planet, bolstering economy, or serving common good
- Every teenager required to serve during most rebellious years against authority
- Older people drafted to work off tax payments and fines
- Dissidents face heavy fines for "hate crimes" and politically incorrect attitudes
- Eventually all would be in forced-labor battalions

> "Most proposals that address themselves, explicitly or otherwise to the postwar problem of controlling the socially alienated turn to some variant of the Peace Corps or the so-called Job Corps for a solution.... Another possible surrogate for the control of potential enemies of society is the rein traduction, in some form consistent with modem technology and political processes, of slavery.... It is entirely possible that the development of a sophisticated form of slavery may be an absolute prerequisite for social control in a world at peace."

- Military institutions historically provided "acceptable role" for antisocial elements
- "Juvenile delinquency" and "alienation" existed in all ages
- In earlier times dealt with by military "through press gangs or outright enslavement"
- Universal military service would be first step toward "euphemized form of enslavement"

## Blood Games

### Preoccupying the Public

- Report considered ways to preoccupy public with non-important activities so they wouldn't participate in political debate or resistance
- Recreation, game shows, pornography, situation comedies could help
- **Blood games** considered most promising option

### Characteristics of Blood Games

- Competitive events between individuals or teams sufficiently violent to enable spectators to "vicariously work off their frustrations"
- Must evoke passionate team loyalty from fans
- Must include expectation of pain and injury; better yet, blood and possibility of death
- Common man has "morbid fascination for violence and blood"

### Examples of Blood Games in Action

- Crowds gather to chant "Jump! Jump!" at suicidal figures
- Cars slow on highway to gawk at broken bodies
- Schoolyard fights draw circles of spectators
- Boxing, football, hockey, automobile races telecast daily with millions watching "each moment of danger, each angry blow to the face, each broken bone, each knockout, each carrying away of the unconscious or possibly dying contestant"
- Anger at "society" is defused and focused on opposing team

> "The emperors of Rome devised the Circuses and gladiator contests and public executions by wild beasts for precisely that purpose."

### Modern Examples

- **1985 European soccer championship (Belgium)**: bloody riot in bleachers — 38 dead, 400 injured
- **Thomas Tutko** (professor of psychology, San Jose State University): "In these other countries, it used to be their armies. Now it's their competitive teams that stir passions."
- **1964 stadium riot (Lima, Peru)**: 300+ killed
- **1969 match (El Salvador vs. Honduras)**: led to week-long shooting war, hundreds of casualties
- U.S. criticized for gridiron violence, but outbursts rare because loyalties spread among many sports — national pride not at stake

### Report's Conclusion on Blood Games

- Not an adequate substitute for war
- Violent sports distract and allow outlet for boredom and group loyalty
- But their effect on nation's psyche cannot match intensity of war hysteria
- Until better alternative found, **world government would have to be postponed** so nations could continue to wage war

## Finding a Credible Global Threat

### Requirements for a Global Enemy

> "Allegiance requires a cause; a cause requires an enemy. This much is obvious; the critical point is that the enemy that defines the cause must seem genuinely formidable. Roughly speaking, the presumed power of the 'enemy' sufficient to warrant an individual sense of allegiance to a society must be proportionate to the size and complexity of the society. Today, of course, that power must be one of unprecedented magnitude and frightfulness."

- Enemy doesn't have to be real — invented one could work just as well
- Public more readily believes some fictions than others
- **Credibility more important than truth**

### Rejected Options

**Poverty**: Examined but rejected as not fearful enough
- Most of world already in poverty — only those who never experienced it would see it as global threat
- For the rest, simply a fact of everyday life

**Alien invasion from outer space**: Given serious consideration
- Experiments along these lines may have already been tried
- Public reaction not sufficiently predictable — threat not "credible"

> "Credibility, in fact, lies at the heart of the problem of developing a political substitute for war. This is where the space-race proposals, in many ways so well suited as economic substitutes for war, fall short.... It has been hotly argued that such a menace would offer the 'last best hope of peace,' etc., by uniting mankind against the danger of destruction by 'creatures' from other planets or from outer space."

- Report released 1966 when alien idea seemed far-fetched
- Perception has changed — growing segment now believes intelligent life forms may exist beyond our planet
- Dramatic alien encounter shown on TV — even if fabricated by high-tech graphics — could stampede nations into world government
- Alternative scenario: peaceful alien contact leading to world government representing unified human species
- Either scenario **far more credible today than in 1966**

## The Environmental-Pollution Model

### The Winning Candidate

- Final candidate: **pollution of the environment**
- Viewed as most likely to succeed because based partly on observable facts (smog, water pollution)
- Predictions could be made showing end-of-earth scenarios as horrible as atomic warfare
- **Accuracy not important** — purpose to frighten, not inform
- Might be necessary to **deliberately poison the environment** to make predictions more convincing
- Focus public mind on fighting new enemy "more fearful than any invader from another nation — or even from outer space"
- Masses would accept falling living standards, tax increases, bureaucratic intervention as "the price we must pay to save Mother Earth"
- If vision of death and destruction from pollution implanted in public subconscious, global battle against it could replace war as mechanism for control

### Key Passages from the Report

> "When it comes to postulating a credible substitute for war... the 'alternate enemy' must imply a more immediate, tangible, and directly felt threat of destruction. It must justify the need for taking and paying a 'blood price' in wide areas of human concern.... One exception might be the environmental-pollution model, if the danger to society it posed was genuinely imminent.... It may be, for instance, that gross pollution of the environment can eventually replace the possibility of mass destruction by nuclear weapons as the principal apparent threat to the survival of the species."

> "It is true that the rate of pollution could be increased selectively for this purpose.... But the pollution problem has been so widely publicized in recent years that it seems highly improbable that a program of deliberate environmental poisoning could be implemented in a politically acceptable manner."

> "However unlikely some of the possible alternative enemies we have mentioned may seem, we must emphasize that one must be found of credible quality and magnitude, if a transition to peace is ever to come about without social disintegration. It is more probable, in our judgment, that such a threat will have to be invented."

## Authenticity of the Report

### Confusion Over Authorship

- Report states it was produced by **Special Study Group of fifteen men** whose identities were to remain secret
- Not intended to be made public
- One member felt report was too important; delivered copy to **Leonard Lewin** (author/columnist)
- Lewin negotiated publication by Dial Press, then reprinted by Dell Publishing

### Official Reactions

- During **Johnson Administration**, President's Special Assistant for National Security Affairs was **CFR member Walt Rostow**
- Rostow quickly announced report was "spurious work"
- **Herman Kahn** (CFR director of Hudson Institute) said it was not authentic
- **Washington Post** (owned/run by CFR member **Katharine Graham**) called it "a delightful satire"
- **Time magazine** (founded by CFR member **Henry Luce**) said it was "skillful hoax"

### John Kenneth Galbraith's Testimony

- November 26, 1967: report reviewed in book section of Washington Post by **Herschel McLandress** (pen name for Harvard professor **John Kenneth Galbraith**)
- **Galbraith** (also CFR member) said he knew firsthand of report's authenticity because he'd been invited to participate
- Although unable to be part of official group, was consulted and asked to keep project secret
- While he doubted wisdom of releasing it to public, he agreed totally with conclusions

> "As I would put my personal repute behind the authenticity of this document, so would I testify to the validity of its conclusions. My reservations relate only to the wisdom of releasing it to an obviously unconditioned public."

- Six weeks later (Associated Press, London), Galbraith jokingly admitted being "a member of the conspiracy"
- Next day, backed off: "For the first time since Charles II The Times has been guilty of a misquotation.... Nothing shakes my conviction that it was written by either Dean Rusk or Mrs. Clare Booth Luce."

### Competing Authorship Claims

