- Main theme summarized by **Princeton Professor Richard A. Falk** (CFR member):

> "The basis of all four problems is the inadequacy of the sovereign states to manage the affairs of mankind in the twentieth century."

- Handbook asked: "Are nation-states actually feasible, now that they have power to destroy each other in a single afternoon?... What price would most people be willing to pay for a more durable kind of human organization — more taxes, giving up national flags, perhaps the sacrifice of some of our hard-won liberties?"

**1989**: CFR-owned Washington Post published article by **CFR member George Kennan**: "We must prepare instead for... an age where the great enemy is not the Soviet Union, but the rapid deterioration of our planet as a supporting structure for civilized life."

**March 27, 1990**: CFR-controlled New York Times — **CFR member Michael Oppenheimer**: "Global warming, ozone depletion, deforestation and overpopulation are the four horsemen of a looming 21st century apocalypse.... As the cold war recedes, the environment is becoming the No. 1 international security concern."

**1991**: **CFR member Lester Brown** (heads Worldwatch Institute) — annual report *State of the World 1991*: "The battle to save the planet will replace the battle over ideology as the organizing theme of the new world order."

**1992 Earth Summit** official publication: "The world community now faces together greater risks to our common security through our impacts on the environment than from traditional military conflicts with one another."

> "How many times does it have to be explained? The environmental movement was created by the CFR. It is a substitute for war that they hope will become the emotional and psychological foundation for world government."

